<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BIG CAT BRAWL, DODGERS LOSE TO BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Darren Dreifort said he was fine, but the welts on his
body suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   And Dreifort will never say the pitch that hit Andres Galarraga
in the left thigh and touched off a bench-clearing brawl in the
second inning of Saturday's 7-5 Dodgers loss to the Atlanta Braves
was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   But Braves manager Bobby Cox doesn't care. He knows what he saw
and it looked a lot like last Sunday's game in Los Angeles, when
Dreifort hit Galarraga in almost the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very intentional, no doubt about it,'' the usually
soft-spoken Cox shouted after the game. ``You had an idiot on the
mound today. The guy is a dope.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was cheap, weak and selfish on his part. He is
baseball's biggest dope.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong words but not nearly as powerful as the swing that flew
over the head of Dreifort after Galarraga charged the mound.
Dreifort dropped to the ground to avoid the 6-foot-4, 250-pound
Galarraga, who said earlier in the week he would no longer stand by
as pitchers tried to drive him off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   There were strong emotions on both sides as the brawl lasted
several minutes. Dreifort and Galarraga, who were ejected by
home-plate umpire Bruce Froemming, wrestled on the mound before
they were joined by teammates. Galarraga raised a sweat. Dreifort
looked like a rag doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see this was coming after the Big Cat (Galarraga)
got hit in L.A.,'' said Dodgers second baseman Eric Young, a former
teammate in Colorado. ``It takes a lot to get him this way. But
he's been hit a lot this season and I think he is taking it
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga has been hit 22 times this season, a club record, and
134 times in his career, more than any active player. Sunday, he
was struck by Dreifort in the second inning after hitting
game-winning, three-run homers the two previous previous days. He
now has 39 homers, but that power has come at a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy stands right on top of the plate,'' Dreifort said.
``His back foot is almost on the plate. He dives over the plateevery time. You have to go inside or he will kill you.'' That was
Galarraga's intent when he charged Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time he did it (last Sunday) I turned away,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he is throwing at me on purpose. If I didn't
charge the mound, everybody in baseball would have been laughing at
me. I had to defend myself. I wanted to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's pitch incited the brawl, but it also ignited a
three-run rally that gave the Braves a lead they would never lose.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping Florida, the Dodgers were guardedly optimistic
they were heading in the right direction. Now they are facing Cy
Young Award winners Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine in the final two
games of the series. Talk about frightening.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers missed both last weekend when they dropped two of
three to the Braves. Their only victory came in a pitcher's duel
between Dreifort and left-hander Denny Neagle. This time, Dreifort
was gone after 13 pitches and Neagle (12-11) struggled through five
before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers battled, scoring three in the fourth. Braves third
baseman Chipper Jones homered in the third off right-hander Mike
Judd, who took over when Dreifort was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre, who had a single and game-winning homer Friday
night in Miami, had a two-run single in the inning to get the
Dodgers within 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was anything good about this game, it was that we got
to see some guys that don't play much,'' said Hoffman, who also got
two innings out of recent call-up Sean Maloney. ``That will help
them down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams batted for Ryan Kelsko against Mark Guthrie in
the fifth and increased the Braves' lead to 6-3 with a two-run
single. Trenidad Hubbard and Raul Mondesi against made it a one-run
game with RBI singles in the sixth, but the Dodgers never got any
closer.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Dodgers eight games behind the New York
Mets in the wild- card race. Former Dodger Mike Piazza hit a grand
slam for the Mets, who come to Los Angeles next weekend for a
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be in a position to have to win all those
games,'' Hoffman said. ``It would be good to win here and show how
we match up against the top teams. It is going to be tough the next
two days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had planned to go with a six-man rotation on the
upcoming homestand when right-hander Ismael Valdes was scheduled to
return. But Valdes lasted only three innings Saturday in a
minor-league rehabilitation assignment. Dreifort, with one-plus
inning Saturday, could be moved up in the rotation, but Hoffman
wasn't thinking about that after facing the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been a disaster today,'' he said. ``When I saw
Galarraga charge the mound, I was very worried Darren could have
really been hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
