<HEADLINE>
COVENANT MARRIAGE LAW LURES COUPLES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have already promised God to love, honor and cherish.
</P>
<P>
   But about 75 married couples wanted to find out Saturday how to
get the state of Arizona involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before God, we're vowed. We've already made the commitment
that divorce is not an option,'' said 35-year-old Kim Schmidt,
standing next to her 34-year-old husband, Marc. ``We want to make
that promise on paper, before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidts, who've been married 15 years, were among the
information seekers who attended a seminar at the downtown Hyatt in
Phoenix on Arizona's new covenant marriage law.
</P>
<P>
   The law, the second of its kind in the nation, makes it harder
to obtain a divorce. It took effect on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this public statement can encourage (other couples) to
work a little harder on that relationship,'' Marc Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   A covenant marriage puts legal limits on the grounds for
divorce. It says husband and wife must live apart for two years
before they can legally split.
</P>
<P>
   It says a spouse may try to leave the relationship only if there
has been
</P>
<P>
   adultery, abuse, abandonment, alcoholism or drug abuse, or if a
spouse has been sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   A covenant marriage can also end if both people agree to the
divorce, the law says.
</P>
<P>
   Couples-to-be who want a covenant marriage must agree to
premarital counseling. But those already married the traditional
way, who want to marry under the covenant, can forgo the
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   They do need to pay the $50 fee, however.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Leo Godzich said covenant couples will be a shining
example of
</P>
<P>
   commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the covenant movement starts spreading to other states,
couples will be confronted with the word `covenant' and what a
marriage means,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and Louisiana are the only states with covenant marriage
laws. This year, 19 states tried and failed to pass covenant
legislation, said Len Munsil, an attorney and covenant advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reaction against the system we have today whereby a
person can leave a marriage at any time for any reason, or no
reason at all,'' Munsil said.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple to be married under the new law are Gail and
Jean Michelli.
</P>
<P>
   They had been married for 30 years until Jean got tired of the
marriage and asked for a divorce. He then remarried and divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the couple are back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disobedient. I chose not to honor the commitment we
made,'' Jean Michelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean said the two-year waiting period would have been enough for
him to realize the marriage needed counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Couples) think of it as a game,'' Gail Michelli said. ``It's
not a game.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 16,736 divorces in Maricopa County last year. Half
the marriages in Arizona end in divorce, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Nancy Steele, who have been married four years, said
their marriage is already a covenant. They attended the session,
but said they wonder if the new state law is worth the paperwork
and the $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, in our plain-vanilla marriage, we entered into it
until death do we part,'' Mark Steele said. ``We're happily
married. And, I say, if it ain't broke, don't fix it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
