<HEADLINE>
COPPING TO CAPITOL OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
It's clear now that, sooner or later, you'll catch on. Maybe you'll
be downtown, looking west toward the Washington Monument, and see
only a saguaro.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or you'll be on the east side, where the Capitol dome should
dominate the skyline _ not the dome of a thunder cloud boiling over
an unbroken horizon.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll begin to wonder if you've been betrayed. To sense
you've been double crossed. To suspect you've been sold down the
river, which you suddenly notice is dry, because it's not the
Potomac, it's the Salt.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll know _ in spite of this newspaper's distortions and
deceptions _ you DO NOT live in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   You live in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   (Or maybe Cleveland, Miami, Portland, Pittsburgh, Chicago, San
Francisco and so on.)
</P>
<P>
   You'd never have been able to tell from reading the local news
or watching TV, not for the past week or so.
</P>
<P>
   But take a look outside.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a pool in your back yard, but it's small and
kidney-shaped, and reflects a barbecue grill, not an obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't cherry trees lining the streets, either. They're
palms.
</P>
<P>
   And the famous Mall?
</P>
<P>
   It's . . . a mall.
</P>
<P>
   No Air &AMP; Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap. &QL; 
CONFESSION TIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The time has come for those of us in the news business to fess
up.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since President Clinton made his historic confession, we've
been deceiving you, acting as if every city in America was Washing
ton, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   There's no White House here.
</P>
<P>
   There are White Mountains, but they're a day's drive away. And
much more pristine.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say what led us to do what we did, filling page after
page with news from the nation's capital. It was, as a powerful and
embarrassed man once said, ``a critical lapse in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, no sensible journalist would dally with Washington in
lieu of Phoenix. No more so than he'd choose a naive intern over a
smart, challenging professional woman.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it happened.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the past several days arrogantly trying to gauge
political winds from the East, ignoring the damp breeze swirling
north from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Each afternoon, monsoon winds herd rain clouds into bunches at
the outskirts of town, near the mountain tops. That's where they
stay most days, the setting sun toasting their underbellies like
marshmallows. &QL; 
SHAME TO WASTE IT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such things go unnoticed in Washington, where everyone is too
busy looking down on everyone else to look up at the sky.
</P>
<P>
   We've got an abundance of sky where we live. It's a shame to
waste it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame _ as we shine a light on the Capitol _ to ignore
the subtle shade of a paloverde tree.
</P>
<P>
   Or the slanting shadows on Cam elback Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Or the wavering heat on our wide city streets.
</P>
<P>
   There are wide thoroughfares in Washington, too. One difference
is, our streets lead home. In D.C., they lead to traffic circles,
where resi dents go round and round. News people from all over the
country were in there with them recently, spinning wildly, getting
dizzy and disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   But as a famous man once said while trying desperately to appear
contrite (though appearing only des perate), ``Now is the time _ in
fact, it is past time _ to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the jackals in the East chew the corpses they choose.
</P>
<P>
   I know it may be difficult for you to believe me, or anyone else
from this paper, given our recent indiscre tion, but you're NOT in
Washing ton.
</P>
<P>
   From the beautiful desert, we can study the carcasses at a safe
dis tance, well beyond the stench of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, open the window, take a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   Ahhhhhhhhhh. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
