<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE WAKES UP, BUT COWBOYS LOSE TO RAMS, 22-14
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ After weeks of stuttering and sputtering in Chan
Gailey's new offense, the Cowboys finally flexed their aging
muscles last night.
</P>
<P>
   It was circa 1995 for Troy Aikman, Michael Irvin, and Emmitt
Smith, who led a first-half Cowboys charge that bullied the St.
Louis Rams in exhibition football at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams stayed with their starters throughout most of the third
quarter and rallied for a 22-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But when it was first team vs. first team, the Cowboys
dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed his first eight passes and finished 10-for-14.
Irvin caught six for 100 yards. Smith rushed 12 times for another
110.
</P>
<P>
   On their first two offensive series, the Cowboys marched 82 and
91 yards for touchdowns in drives that resembled the efficient way
the team used to play when it was considered a serious Super Bowl
contender.
</P>
<P>
   It was 14-0 Cowboys before the Rams had three first downs.
</P>
<P>
   When work was done for Aikman and company, the Cowboys, who also
got inspired play from a first-team defense playing without Leon
Lett and Deion Sanders, had outgained the Rams, 258-108. The total
included 141 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this was a Rams team coming off a 5-11 season. In
two previous exhibitions this year, they had been outscored by
three touchdowns. And because of a contract dispute, they were
without their best defensive player, cornerback Ryan McNeil, who
led the league with nine interceptions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But for a first-team Cowboys offense that had scored one
offensive touchdown in three previous preseason games, it was the
kind of confidence booster needed to continue preparing for the
Sept. 6 season opener against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we won't have to answer any more questions about it (how
they have struggled this summer). I think we have always been
confident in this offense. We just have not had the success in the
last couple of games,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and Gailey were quick to note that there is still room
for improvement. There were still too many breakdowns, most
prominently a missed block on a Rams blitz that led to an Aikman
interception, and a complete breakdown of the offensive line that
led to, for the second week in a row, a failed fourth-and-one
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The sloppiness handcuffed the Cowboys on their final three
drives of the first half, when they scored no points and had four
first downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only disappointments were not putting points on the board
after starting with good field position,'' Aikman said of a Cowboys
drive that began at their 49. ``And not being able to convert on
fourth-and-one. Overall, though, I was real pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   All summer, Gailey kept telling a disbelieving public that there
could be days like this, when the Cowboys coaches had a strong game
plan and the team kept its mistakes to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened during the first 16 minutes. There were no
penalties, and Gailey played to his strengths, with Aikman, Irvin,
and Smith accounting for most of the team's yardage in the first
two drives. Irvin easily beat the single coverage of cornerback
Dexter McCleon, McNeil's replacement, for most of his six catches,
including one for 46 yards. Smith had a 47-yard run behind a first
team offensive line that opened gaping holes all night, and scored
a touchdown on a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when called upon, other Cowboys stepped up, especially Billy
Davis, who continues to make Gailey's job of choosing a No. 2 wide
receiver difficult. Davis kept the first Cowboys scoring drive
alive with a sliding reception on third down. And he ended it with
a sliding, 6-yard touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Cowboys' first team unit limited Rams
quarterback Tony Banks and company to six first downs and 34 yards
rushing in the first half. For the fourth consecutive week, the
first-team defensive line did not record a sack, but young
defensive ends Greg Ellis and Kavika Pittman combined for three
quarterback pressures on Banks. The pressure forced Banks into a
6-for-16 first half.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey does not plan to use his starters for much more than a
quarter in the preseason finale against Jacksonville next week. So
last night was the final dress rehearsal for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, the curtain comes up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
