<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, CHAN SEES PROGRESS, ALBEIT LIMITED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Better, yes. Much better, actually. But still not
good enough to cheer up Chan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We improved, and that was our goal, but I'm not satisfied,''
said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who might be in need of a real
quick crash course in realism.
</P>
<P>
   There is no coaching medicine to improve mediocrity, and until
further notice, that's where the Cowboys are stuck. So on an
evening when the good is much more prevalent than the awful, which
wcase here last night, go ahead, Chan, get yourself some
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this Trans World Dome visit, a trio of exhibition
season malfunctions for the Cowboys had ranked somewhere between
rot and reek. Therefore, it could be said the first 30 minutes
against the St. Louis Rams was a vast improvement over nothing, but
that misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   The how, who and why didn't necessarily matter. When the
Cowboys' starting units lined up against the Rams, it was
imperative that positives finally flow, particularly on the
offensive side.
</P>
<P>
   Locker room voices had indicated all week that the Cowboys were
even carrying a load of self-imposed pressure into this game, an
almost unheard of August admittance about it not being too early to
show concern.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, an ``old-school'' offense was on display, providing
some flashbacks to the way it was. The way it was a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt by land, Troy and Michael by air, ripping off yardage,
and, yes, a couple of touchdowns, as if Buffalo had just shown up
to play the Cowboys in that first Super Bowl of the '90s. Well, OK,
that's stretching it, but it's been a long and barren exhibition
season.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, in particular, looked super sharp, not only
scooting through nice holes provided by the offensive line, but
also creating yardage on his own. The creating part has been
missing for Smith, but 110 yards on 12 carries in only one half was
Emmitt as good as he's been in a long time. Ditto for the offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman and Michael Irvin spent most of the first two
quarters playing uncontested pitch-and-catch, although in fairness,
Irvin was abusing a young, overmatched cornerback. Dexter McCleon
will be on the Rams bench if and when a solid corner named Ryan
McNeil decides to end a contractual holdout.
</P>
<P>
   In the two quarters the first unit offense was on the field,
Emmitt, Aikman and Michael accounted for 210 yards and led the way
to a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Just as telling, the offense played ball control, knocking 18
minutes off the clock in the first half. Nothing helps the Dallas
defense like not being on the field, which goes back to the key to
the dynasty success, speaking of another long-ago memory.
</P>
<P>
   Let it be noted, however, that the whipping boys of the defense,
ends Greg Ellis and Kavika Pittman, both had their most solid
performances of the preseason. In other words, they were noticed,
making tackles and chasing quarterback Tony Banks into hurried
throws.
</P>
<P>
   But just because positives easily out-totaled negatives _
finally _ in a preseason game, when the bad things did happen, they
were glaring.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a second-quarter screen pass.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is big on screen passes, but he may be finding out why
Norv Turner and Ernie Zampese weren't. Those things don't work for
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman tried to drop a screen over the middle, a play that
seemed to be going nowhere from the start. Unfortunately, the ball
was tipped, and also intercepted, giving the Rams their first lift
of the first half. Plus, the interception killed a possession for
Dallas that had started at midfield, and it led to a St. Louis
field goal. Screen passes _ who needs them?
</P>
<P>
   Later in the second quarter, the Cowboys were sitting on a
fourth-and-one from the Rams' 35. Emmitt went up the middle,
gaining nothing. Fourth-and-one? Yes, the Cowboys do need them, but
rarely convert anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So while the offense started against the Rams with a vast amount
of steam, as the first half wound down, the momentum was gone.
Thanks and no thanks to a busted screen pass and a futile
fourth-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gailey went to his bench in the second half. All that did
was ensure the Cowboys would remain winless in the preseason. Let
the record show St. Louis won, 22-14.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, give the Cowboys credit for a lot of first half
positives _ finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
