<SLUG> BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASLEY BLOSSOMTROIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was injured all the time. He stopped hitting. He was an
erratic fielder. He was demoted to the minors. He was unwanted. He
was headed no where in a hurry. He was miserable.
</P>
<P>
   And then Damion Easley on July 31, 1996, escaped purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels traded him to the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely the low point of my life,'' says Easley, who grew
up in Long Beach. ``I had been an Angel fan ever since I was a kid.
I loved that team. And I came up with a lot of the players now
playing on it. A lot of them are still my close friends. I was a
part of that group. I didn't want to leave. But I knew I had
reached a point where, unless a few things changed, I would have to
go. I did. No regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding!
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley has developed in Detroit into the player the
Angels thought he would become in Anaheim when he arrived on the
scene in 1992 as a heralded prospect only to spend a good portion
of his time on the disabled list during the next four, frustrating,
unpve seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But it all has magically turned around for Easley.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer gets injured. He hits home runs. He drives in runs.
He keeps his batting average in the .290 range. He makes the
All-Star team. He appears in the event's home-run hitting contest
right alongside the Mark McGwires and Ken Griffeys. He earns
himself a three-year, multi-million dollar contract.
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley has pulled off the unusual he's become a
legitimate major league star only a brief time after he seemed
destined for baseball oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things definitely have been going my way,'' said Easley the
other day in the visitors clubhouse at Edison Field before his team
faced the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   How could Damion Easley go from being a reject prone to ailments
to being a durable performer ranked among the top second basemen in
the major leagues?
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one thing, he credits the more than the 200, 45-minute
sessions he had with a Marina Del Rey hypnotherapist named Pete
Seagal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started them in 1995 to deal with some personal issues not
related to baseball,'' says Easley. ``And then it turned out the
hypnotherapy made me a stronger person, and it helped me in my
baseball career. I became more mature, and could handle adversity
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley also attributes weightlifting to his turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very inconsistent in taking care of myself physically
when I was with the Angels,'' admits Easley, who was plagued by
shin splits and shoulder injuries during his tenure with the team.
``Now I hit the weights after every game. I never miss a workout.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley has packed 15 muscular pounds on his 5-foot-11 frame
since departing the Angels, and he feels the extra strength in the
190 he now carries has resulted in his hitting 22 home runs last
season and already 21 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much stronger now than when I was with the Angels,'' says
Easley. ``The drives I used to hit in the power alleys would go for
doubles or be caught. Now I have enough strength for them to reach
the stands. It's just a case of physical and mental maturity. I'm
now 28.''
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley no longer gets injured, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just take care of myself better,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you miss playing for the Angels?'' I asked Easley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it would be nice being part of a team involved in a
pennant race like the Angels,'' he said. ``But I'm very happy with
the Tigers. We're a young team, much like the Angels were a few
years back when I first joined them. We've got a lot of good young
players who are going to get a lot better. Hopefully, we'll all
stay together and have some good years in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley lives in the off-season in Glendale, Ariz., with his
wife, Dawn, and three children, Rocky, 9, Tazmin, 4, and Nathaniel,
2.
</P>
<P>
   He played at Long Beach City College in 1988, and signed with
the Angels the following year.
</P>
<P>
   He knows the Angels probably now regret getting rid of him, but
doesn't begrudge them for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't producing and I was hurt a lot,'' he says. ``I
was frustrated, and I'm sure the Angels were frustrated. The change
of scenery definitely worked out well for me. I have no complaints.
None whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
