<SLUG> BC-DRUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG CZAR'S NEW PLAN FOR BORDER
</HEADLINE>
 WAR-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ America's drug czar will soon propose sweep ing
remedies to try to patch gaping holes in the Southwest border,
where tons of cocaine and mari juana continue to slip through
undetected, even though the U.S. is spending $2 billion a year to
keep drugs out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proposals, the result of two years of study, will be
announced this week and will include putting a federal official in
charge of each of the 24 entry points and naming a coordinator to
oversee the entire 2,000-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the national drug control
officer (or ``drug czar''), is to curb interagency rivalries and to
put somebody in charge of the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, he says, the United States clamps down on one segment
of the border only to see smugglers retreat to a less-guarded area.
McCaffrey also wants to modernize inspection and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The druggies know where the holes are,'' said James McDonough,
McCaffrey's director of strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, despite the com mitment of 11,000 federal agents
and officials, the nation is still losing the battle of the border.
While there is no way of ensuring that his plan will help,
McCaffrey said that after two years of studying the drug battles at
the border, he is ready to try.
</P>
<P>
   The retired four-star general and former Persian Gulf War
division commander believes the United States suffers not only from
a shortage of border resources but also from a lack of coordination
among the federal agencies that police the border. They include the
Customs Service, the Immigration and Naturalization Service, the Na
tional Guard, the Drug Enforcement Administration and the
Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that 60 percent of the cocaine and more
than half of the marijuana that enter the country each year cross
the Mexican border. The border also is an important gateway for
heroin and methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine seizures at the border have fallen from 41,840 kilos in
1995, to 35,608 kilos in 1996, to 17,383 kilos last year, according
to the drug czar's office.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey's plan would clarify vague or duplicative assignments
and, in some key cases, establish entirely new responsibilities for
many of the 10 primary agencies operating along the border that
stretches from Brownsville, Texas, to San Ysidro, Calif. Arizona
has six entry points along the way.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a federal official from one of the lead
agencies, most likely the U.S. Cus toms Service, would be placed in
charge at each of the ports _ all overseen by a newly created South
west border coordinator expected to be based at El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey hopes to win enough support from affected agencies so
he can send the recommendations to President Clinton by the fall.
Por tions of the plan would require congressional approval, and at
least one congressman from the South west is on board.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, a former Border Patrol
sector chief in El Paso, said a new approach is necessary because
``we have, in varying degrees, an uncoor dinated effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the Border Patrol in the early 1970s when President
Nixon proposed a border manage ment agency,'' Reyes said. ``It was
not followed through on, and there was a tremendous amount of
resist ance by federal agencies. The differ ence now is that we
have a Cabinet-level official (McCaffrey) fully behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, no one monitors the entire border except President
Clin ton, ``and he has a full plate already,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The drug czar is to unveil his proposals during meetings Tuesday
and Wednesday with federal border officials in El Paso, one of the
nation's busiest ports. The Arizona Republic obtained details in ad
vance.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is at least partly formed from lessons derived from
military strategy. McDonough, like his boss, was a celebrated Army
officer.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough, who led troops in Vietnam, said lives were lost when
the service branches could not successfully integrate missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the military learned, it is better to coordinate its
separate services and arms,'' he said. ``So, too, can we learn to
coordinate at the border.''
</P>
<P>
   At most ports, even the most fundamental task of inspecting cars
and trucks is divided among agen cies with different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   At Nogales, for example, the Immigration and Naturalization
Service routinely inspects vehicles lined up in half of the lanes
approaching the Arizona border. The Customs Service handles the
other half. The split evolved be cause of the border's dual mission
of uncovering both illegal drugs and undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spotters'' use binoculars to survey the entire scene from the
Mexican side, then report back to drug smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sit on a hill overlooking the cargo (inspection)
operation,'' said P.T. Wright, customs director for the Nogales
port. ``They have a little picnic under the mesquite trees. We feel
like they're looking primarily at which trucks we're sending in for
(extra) examination.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials in the drug czar's office fear that the spotters
also may be looking for any differences they can exploit in the
respective agen cies' inspection procedures.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey's plan would, for the first time, mandate standard,
border wide procedures for inspecting vehi cles for drugs. He wants
little variation from port to port or agency to agency, to prevent
spot ters from detecting an opening.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also would officially declare the federal Border Patrol
as the lead agency for the vast sections of border between the
ports _ including areas so remote that McCaffrey describes them as
``an invisible line in the sand.'' Cur rently, Border Patrol agents
share the in-between areas with other agencies and local
authorities from Arizona, California, New Mexico and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Border Patrol virtually de facto has that lead now, but
they can't claim they've got ad, and they don't have all the
authority that would come with it,'' said Chuck Blanchard, chief
counsel in McCaffrey's office and a former Arizona state senator.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey believes his plan could reduce the flow of drugs over
the border by 80 percent in the next 10 years. Accomplishing that
would require not only the organizational fixes but also
cooperation with Mexico and increased funding by Congress for
drug-screening equip ment and new border agents. None of those
propositions is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCaffrey hasn't for mally presented his recommenda
tions, federal agencies were reluctant to discuss them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly aware of his proposal that's being
discussed,'' said Roger Maier, a Customs Serv ice spokesman on the
border. ``But I don't think we have all the details of what he's
proposing, and until we do, we really can't comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Maier noted that the volume of cocaine seized in the first two
quarters of 1998 was up dramati cally in some border regions from
1997, based partly on a seven-month program emphasizing ran dom
inspections. The drug czar's office said it was too soon to assess
whether this was the beginning of a turnaround or just a ``blip.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey's ideas are likely to be attacked on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies may worry whether their autonomy could be undercut, and
unions are likely to look closely at any changes affecting workers'
assignments or pay. Others may find the recommendations too
military like, even though the drug czar's office has opposed a
plan languish ing in Congress that would permit troops to be
dispatched to help secure the border.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is growing because border traffic is on the rise,
and smugglers are using increasingly sophisticated methods to evade
de tection.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 900,000 U.S.-bound trucks _ about one-quarter of the
total crossing the border _ were subjected to drug-control inspec
tions. Cocaine was found in just 16.
</P>
<P>
   This year, one of the largest border busts came in May when
customs inspectors at Nogales un covered 1,743 pounds of cocaine
hidden in a pair of huge engines of the type used in earth-moving
equipment. &QL; 
 &UR; Jeff Barker can be reached at (202)
 &UR; 662-7264 or at jeff.barker &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
