<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHERNOMYRDIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKTOR CHERNOMYRDIN: OLD-SCHOOL POLITICIAN RE-TAKES HELM 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-SHAKEUP, RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-REACT) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSCOW _ The last time Viktor Chernomyrdin took the reins of the
Russian government from a brash band of reformers, in December
1992, he said nothing would change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for deepening the reforms. There is no way back,''
Chernomyrdin pledged then, hours after President Boris Yeltsin
sacked his chief economic adviser, Yegor Gaidar, and made
Chernomyrdin prime minister in his place. But things did change: by
1995, economic reform was near a standstill and Chernomyrdin let it
be known that he thought Western market theory had done the nation
``more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Yeltsin has gone and done it again, firing Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko and an entire government of free-market reformers
to make way for Chernomyrdin's return. Neither Yeltsin nor
Chernomyrdin were saying on Sunday what the switch means. Clinton
administration officials said Sunday night that they had been
assured by Chernomyrdin that continuing the economic overhaul of
Russia remains a top priority, although specifics were sparse.
</P>
<P>
   But if history continues to repeat itself, Chernomyrdin will
preside over a government that rocks few establishment boats and
largely prizes the status quo over painful change. Chernomyrdin
innovated little and held fast to many traditions during his
previous five and one-half years as prime minister. Many Western
experts charge that his refusal to dismantle the government
bureaucracy and the industrial oligarchy long allied with it are at
the root of this summer's economic catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say he brought something to Russia that the
reformers have never been able to secure: stability.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Chernomyrdin is, at heart, an old-school
politician of the Soviet stripe. His entire life was spent in the
petroleum industry: he was born in the southern Ural Mountain
region of Orenburg, educated as an oil-and-gas economist, and
worked seven years at a refinery before getting into city politics
in 1967. By 1982 he was the Soviet Union's deputy minister for the
gas industry, and by 1989 he had transformed the ministry into
Gazprom, a state-owned monopoly that sold gas throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was running Gazprom when the Soviet Union collapsed
in 1991, and in late 1992 Yeltsin plucked him from the Russian
energy ministry to replace Gaidar.
</P>
<P>
   His term did not begin well. After pledging to continue reforms,
he quickly slapped price controls on the economy to combat
inflation _ a move anathema to free-market advocates _ and was
forced to remove them within weeks. He soon tangled with Anatoly
Chubais, a leading economic adviser to Yeltsin, saying Chubais'
program to privatize state-owned industry was akin to Stalin's
forced collectivization of farms.
</P>
<P>
   Such skirmishing continued through his term as prime minister,
though Chernomyrdin cooperated more closely on inflation-fighting
and privatization after the economy and the ruble took a steep
nosedive in October 1994. In 1997, he seemed overshadowed when
Yeltsin named two key reformers, Chubais and Boris Nemtsov, as
deputies to Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin survived because of his unswerving loyalty to
Yeltsin, his ties to the communists who still dominated the
parliament, and his ability to work with Western leaders like Vice
President Al Gore, with whom he served as chairman of a commission
on U.S.-Russian issues.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed another asset too: virtual membership in the family
of so-called oligarchs who control the major industries, banks and
media in Russia. Chernomyrdin was one of them when he ran Gazprom,
and his role in the government undoubtedly helped secure their
support when Yeltsin successfully won a second term in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with this web of conflicting relationships, critics
say, is that Chernomyrdin has performed as if he were paralyzed by
it. The government's privatization program slowed markedly during
his first tenure, as did efforts to improve tax collection and
reduce the amount of trade conducted through barter. He enjoyed
decent relations with the communist Duma in part because his
government offered few proposals _ such as spending cuts _ that
offended it.
</P>
<P>
   Big banks and industries largely enjoyed free reign during
Chernomyrdin's time. His old friends at Gazprom, for example,
struck a deal with the government that dramatically reduced their
monthly tax payments _ and which was promptly revoked after
Chernomyrdin lost the prime minister's job this spring.
</P>
<P>
   During all this time, critics say, Russia's structural economic
problems grew unmolested. In particular, they say, Chernomyrdin
made no attempt to crack down on a banking industry that had become
addicted to risky speculative schemes, to restructure industries
and promote domestic competition, to trim the bureaucracy or to
control government spending. Those same tasks _ plus a national
economic collapse _ now await him .
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Western advisers who were present at the birth of
Yeltsin's economic reform program in the early 1990s are
nevertheless repelled by that notion. ``My assumption is that
Russia's going into a tailspin like Indonesia and Bulgaria,'' said
Anders Aslund, a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment in
Washington who resigned as a Yeltsin adviser in 1994 due to
unhappiness with Chernomyrdin. ``The best you can say about his
term as prime minister is that when he was weak, some reforms were
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say Chernomyrdin is no longer the
Soviet apparatchik of his gas ministry days, but a man who has
grown in office and who can work with the West.
</P>
<P>
   When Yeltsin dismissed Chernomyrdin almost without warning in
March and replaced him with Kiriyenko, the president said the
attack on economic problems required new blood. The rumor then was
that Yeltsin had acted because Chernomyrdin harbors ambitions to
succeed him as president.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's party, Our Home Is Russia, is the second-largest
faction in the Duma, Russia's lower house of parliament, and he has
long been the favored candidate of his oligarch allies.
</P>
<P>
   All he has lacked is public support, usually drawing but
single-digit ratings in polls, and his stolidity and manling of
Russian grammar and syntax are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one considers what could have been done, and then what we
did do over this long time, one can conclude that something was
done,'' he once said. Now he will have a chance to do still more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
