<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGNANCY-SMOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BYPRODUCTS PASSED TO FETUSES, RESEARCHERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Mass.)   (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers have found the first direct evidence that a
cancer-causing substance from tobacco is transmitted to fetuses by
pregnant smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hecht of the University of Minnesota Cancer Center said
his findings established that the nicotine-derived chemical NNK is
not only received by the fetus but processed by the body. The
chemical is the only known lung carcinogen found solely in tobacco
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the rate it is passing through the body or the
time spent there, but the study shows substantial exposure of the
fetus to a substance known to cause cancer,'' Hecht said in an
interview before presenting his paper on the findings at this
week's national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Collaborating with German researchers who provided urine samples
from 48 newborns, Hecht's laboratory found byproducts of NNK in 22
of 31 samples from newborns whose mothers smoked during pregnancy.
None were found in the newborns of nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht's study, which was sponsored by the National Cancer
Institute, detected a substance called NNAL-Gluc, a derivative of
NNK produced in the human body. Its presence in the urine samples
suggested that the newborns had not only taken in but processed the
carcinogen NNK, he said. He called the finding an unacceptable
risk.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not determine whether the infants with the traces
of NNK byproducts in their urine were born addicted to nicotine or
would be at greater risk of developing cancer, Hecht said. He
pointed out that the exposure to the carcinogen might continue for
many years after birth, through secondhand smoke, because most
women who smoke during pregnancy continue to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht used a customized gas chromatography system in the
analysis, the same method he used in reporting last year that
NNAL-Gluc was in the urine of nonsmoking adults exposed to
secondhand smoke. The method used in that study was 20 times more
sensitive than what he used in a 1993 study of nonsmokers exposed
to tobacco smoke from a smoking machine in a small chamber, the
first demonstration that nonsmokers could take up and metabolize
NNK.
</P>
<P>
   ``In newborns there is less material to study and the
concentration is relatively low, but the methodology we have been
using has become increasingly more sensitive and reliable so we are
able to take on more difficult studies,'' Hecht said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to expand the laboratory research to clinical
trials to explore links between the presence of the chemical at
birth and the development of childhood cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking during pregnancy has been linked to greater risk of
miscarriage, increased chances of complicated births, low birth
weight, sudden infant death syndrome, respiratory infections, and
learning and behavioral problems. But the connection to childhood
cancers is less clear.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying the carcinogens in the urine of a newborn is a major
indication of the potential role and the transmission of those
compounds, said Leslie Robison, coordinator of nationwide
epidemiological studies for the Children's Cancer Group, a network
of 2,800 pediatric cancer specialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
