<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7971 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-REACT-550(2TAK     08-23 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-REACT-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT WILL NOT BE CANCELED, U.S. OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-SHAKEUP, RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-CHERNOMYRDIN,
RUSSIA-REACT) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Clinton administration officials said Sunday
that they were troubled by President Boris Yeltsin's decision to
fire the reformist Russian government so close to the summit
meeting with President Clinton next week in Moscow. But a spokesman
said that Clinton had decided to go ahead with his trip.
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged that they were taken by surprise by the
move Sunday, which also reinstated former Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin. Five months ago, Yeltsin dismissed Chernomyrdin
without warning and installed the young Sergei Kiriyenko as prime
minister with a Cabinet of economic reformers with no discernable
political constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't affect the trip or the timing of the summit at
all,'' said P.J. Crowley, a White House spokesman. ``We have
important bilateral issues. This is an internal Russian matter, and
we obviously will watch it closely. We will continue to work with
the Russian government to advance the reform agenda. What faces
acting Prime Minister Chernomyrdin is the need to take effective
steps to address Russia's economic difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Yeltsin's action raised doubts about his control
and stability, one official said, ``It depends on your starting
point.'' Senior officials say Yeltsin has ``his ups and downs,''
and that he has never regained the stamina and focus he displayed
before his heart attack in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can get up for a big meeting or telephone call with
Clinton,'' one official said. ``But it's not clear he can work for
more than a few hours at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton did not try to reach Yeltsin on Sunday by
telephone, Vice President Al Gore spoke with both Kiriyenko and
Chernomyrdin, who is closer to Gore than to any other U.S.
official. Gore tried to gauge the political climate before Clinton
is due to arrive in Moscow on Sept. 1, and to ask how Washington
can help calm markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's purpose was to urge a continuation of the policies of
economic reform,'' a senior White House official said.
``Chernomyrdin has demonstrated in the past that he's more of a
reformer than many people thought, and he has a lot more support in
the Duma,'' the Russian parliament, which has been blocking reforms
demanded by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The official said it was inappropriate for Gore to raise the
question of a summit postponement. Another official said, ``It
would be a great mistake for us to pull the plug.''
</P>
<P>
   But some prominent and experienced voices outside the government
urged postponement and expressed concern over the apparent U.S.
policy of supporting Yeltsin no matter what he does.
</P>
<P>
   Zbigniew Brzezinski, the national security adviser when Jimmy
Carter was president, called on Clinton to postpone the Moscow
summit for a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no point for a bleeding president to be visiting a
sick and unstable president,'' Brzezinski said in an interview. ``I
think a postponement would be very good for both sides. Under the
circumstances, it will be very difficult for Clinton to concentrate
on long-range issues, and they need to be discussed by leaders able
to make their policies stick. Right now, it will be a summit of
posturing and pretense on both sides. And the United States and
Russia need serious, useful summits.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brzezinski said that it was clear that Yeltsin ``is passing from
the scene,'' and he urged the Clinton administration to ``reach out
and establish a dialogue with other leaders,'' including Moscow
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov; former Gen. Alexander Lebed, now the governor
of a Siberian region; economic reformer and Yeltsin critic Grigory
Yavlinsky; and Communist Party leader, Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to very clearly and deliberately get off the `My dear
friend, Boris' kick,'' Brzezinski said. ``Yeltsin governs at most a
perimeter of 30 kilometers outside Moscow, and even that is not
under his full control.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Clinton plans to meet opposition and
parliament leaders on Sept. 2 in Moscow, and that all the men
Brzezinski named were invited, including Lebed.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Chernomyrdin, Brzezinski said, ``begins to turn a
tragic situation into a farce.'' Chernomyrdin's return had been
pressed on Yeltsin for some time by the so-called ``oligarchs'' of
the Russian economy, in particular by Boris Berezovsky, who once
served as Yeltsin's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The oligarchs stand to lose a lot of money because of the
devaluation of the ruble last week _ which Yeltsin insisted would
never happen. ``We now have what we might call a provisional
oligarchical government,'' Brzezinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Anders Aslund, a former economic adviser to the Russian
government, described the Yeltsin move as a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means Yeltsin is finished, it makes him look like a puppet,
and Russians can't stand weak leaders,'' said Aslund of the
Carnegie Endowment, and a former diplomat in Moscow. ``This really
puts Clinton in an awful situation. You don't want to go to a
country where there is so much uncertainty in the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The reversion to the stolid Chernomyrdin will not please the
markets, Aslund said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin is the man who ran Russia into its big economic
troubles, and the oligarchs are very happy to have him back,'' he
said. ``It won't provide confidence to the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said that market confidence was Gore's
theme with Chernomyrdin, who seemed aware of Russia's problems with
key parliament sessions coming. ``We'll find out this week if the
shift of authority leads to any noteworthy changes of emphasis in
the Russian economic plan and in the level of support the Duma is
willing to provide,'' the official said. ``The market reaction will
be very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimitri Simes, president of the Nixon Center, a Washington-based
think tank, said Kiriyenko's government was too narrow and too
liberal, ``uninterested in dialogue with the Duma and contemptuous
of public opinion and attitudes.'' Chernomyrdin, for all his
faults, Simes said, has demonstrated he has support among foreign
investors and in the parliament, where he controls the second
largest faction.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Clinton administration seemed to fumble for a
response, with the president at Martha's Vineyard, some top
advisers at the beach and others at home in Washington trying to
recover from a stressful week.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Secretary of Defense William Cohen were all
on Sunday talk shows, but their interviews were taped before the
news came out of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Until this latest shock from Moscow, senior administration
officials were minimizing the risks of the economic upheavals,
which officials attributed largely to the Asian economic crisis and
the softness of oil prices, to Yeltsin and his government of young
reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, senior Treasury officials were not prepared to provide
Russia any more money after the failure of the last IMF loan
package of only a month ago, which sent $4.8 billion to Moscow as
part of a $22.6 billion package.
</P>
<P>
   And senior State Department and White House officials were very
angry with Yeltsin's sharply critical comments after the U.S.
missile strikes last week against targets in Afghanistan and Sudan.
Yeltsin, perhaps for domestic advantage, was harsh in his
reactions, blaming Washington for not consulting him, not providing
evidence and not first working through the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   To American leaders who felt they were acting with urgency to
protect more American lives, Yeltsin's comments were ``offensive,''
one official said, ``and went over very badly around here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
