<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAWAII-REPUBS-ART-2TA     08-23 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-REPUBS-ART-2TAKES(1,200)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA CHANGE IN HAWAII: REPUBLICAN LEADING IN POLLS FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
 (Duplication warning: also moved in `a' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ For the last seven years, Hawaii has felt the winds
of economic change blowing only one way across the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the country has prospered, enjoying job growth,
state budget surpluses and contented citizenry _ all to the benefit
of many political incumbents facing re-election this year _ Hawaii
remains a stubborn exception.
</P>
<P>
   Here, despite the spectacular vistas of ocean, mountains and
lava fields that make tourism the backbone of the state economy,
turmoil in Asian financial markets has rocked the island like an
unrelenting hurricane, causing a sharp decline in investment,
minimal growth in tourism, job loss and public pessimism. The
annual economic growth rate here in recent years, half of a
percent, pales beside a national rate that has reached as high as
3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, economists here have detected slight
indications that the worst may have passed and that Hawaii could
finally be turning a corner _ much to the relief of Gov. Benjamin
Cayetano, the latest in an unbroken line of Democratic governors
since Hawaii joined the union in 1959. Upon his election in 1994,
he inherited the worst fiscal crisis in state history, and now that
the budget has been balanced for two years, he is trumpeting his
policies as a major reason to re-elect him in November.
</P>
<P>
   But Cayetano, the state's first Filipino-American governor, may
yet become just another victim of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As if the stars over Hawaii's sparkling beaches and pristine
waters have suddenly realigned, a Republican, Maui Mayor Linda
Lingle, is favored to defeat him in November, according to the
latest statewide polls. How startling is that? Among the 76 members
of the state Legislature, only 14 are Republicans, and across
Hawaii, Republicans are outnumbered by such a wide margin that some
say they are embarrassed or reluctant to admit their affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the enduring sluggish economy seems to be pushing
many people beyond a point where party loyalty determines their
vote, and after four decades of Democratic rule, the state's 1.2
million people might finally be in for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing sense here that Hawaii has become a little
like the old Soviet Union or North Korea with its centralized,
absolute power,'' said Randy Roth, a law professor at the
University of Hawaii here on the island of Oahu and president-elect
of the state bar association. ``Monopoly of political power has cut
off all debate, and that has evolved into the political culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth, whose nonpartisanship allowed him to moderate a local
radio talk show for five years, became so impressed with Ms. Lingle
that he abandoned his neutrality last week to endorse her and join
the campaign as a volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Economic policy and one-party rule were never major concerns in
Hawaii until the collapse of the Japanese yen in the early 1990s
ended years of heavy investment by Japanese banks. The economic
activity had become so frenetic and dazzling that Cayetano
officials now concede that it stunted any creative planning by the
previous administration of Gov. John Waihee III.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a boom period, and government wanted to stay in
control,'' said Seija Naya, a former bank economist who is now
director of the state's Department of Business, Economic
Development and Tourism. ``They added more regulations, charged
more fees and made it harder for businesses to receive approvals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese investors barely noticed. Then the bubble burst,
and recession set in. Since 1991, many hotels and businesses built
with Japanese money have sold for a fraction of their original
cost. And no longer do Asian investors knock on doors of fancy
homes and offer the owner $1 million or more to sell on the spot,
as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian withdrawal overshadowed other disturbing developments.
Production of sugar and pineapple, once staples of the state
economy, has been falling for decades as the Philippines and
Caribbean nations produce them more cheaply. Only a few plantations
are still operating, and the number of agricultural jobs in the
state decreased by 36 percent, to 7,200 last year from 11,300 in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also hurt the state economy, largely
through the reduction of personnel at the state's military bases.
In 1996, the overall number of federal employees in Hawaii fell by
almost a quarter, to 74,119, from a high of 97,853 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Cayetano, 57, a lawyer and former state legislator, has worked
hard to blunt the impact of the Asian crisis. In an interview at
the Capitol last week, he recited a long list of accomplishments,
saying he has reduced the size of government by 500 people, cut the
state's personal income tax for the first time, increased spending
on marketing efforts to attract visitors to islands other than
Oahu, and created novel incentives like eliminating landing fees
for airlines to attract new carriers to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made some hard decisions that have hurt us
politically,'' he said. ``But that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever so slowly, his policies are beginning to help nudge the
state forward again. Tourism from the mainland is rebounding,
compensating for Asian visitors who are staying fewer days and
spending fewer dollars. Unemployment is starting to drop. New small
businesses are opening. An embryonic high-technology industry is
emerging.
</P>
<P>
   But those changes have done little to dampen growing support for
Ms. Lingle, who is attracting people in both parties who say
Cayetano and the Legislature have done too little too late to make
any meaningful recovery possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lingle, 44, a native of St. Louis who came to Hawaii in 1976
as a journalist, has served as Maui's mayor the last eight years.
Her opponent in the Sept. 19 primary, former Honolulu Mayor Frank
Fasi, is not viewed as a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   In part because her island is favored as a vacation spot more by
Americans than Japanese, Maui has resisted much of Hawaii's
economic downturn. The number of jobs on Maui has increased in five
of the last six years, enabling Ms. Lingle to sharpen her attack on
Democratic policies that have not done more to help the state
economy. She has outlined a five-point revitalization strategy,
which includes a comprehensive plan to diversify the economy and
simplify business regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turning point in our history,'' she told a rally of
about 600 voters this week at a high school in the middle-class
suburbs of east Honolulu. ``It's time for a change, and change is
about joining the other 49 states with economic revitalization that
is taking place all across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending the rally was Calvin Griffin, the owner of a small
tent manufacturing company who described himself as an independent
voter and frustrated over policies that have caused him to
subcontract work to California and Mexico, rather than employ
Hawaiians. He said he came to hear more of Ms. Lingle's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could create 50 to 100 more jobs, but I've had to cut back
because of restrictive regulations,'' Griffin said. ``I think it's
because of the good ol' boy network here. It's not what you know.
It's who you know.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though few of Ms. Lingle's ideas are radically different from
Cayetano's, she has nonetheless caught a wave of voter
disenchantment, emerging at a time when many Hawaiians are
receptive to the idea of change if only for change's sake. Of
Hawaii's two House seats, both held by Democrats, one is in
jeopardy. Rep. Neil Abercrombie, who is seeking a sixth term to
represent the Honolulu area, is fighting for his political life
against Quentin Kawananakoa, who is expected to win the Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lingle has also captured the attention of leading
Republicans on the mainland. Just last week, she flew to New York
City for a fund-raiser with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani that she said
brought her $100,000 in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Cayetano argued that his administration was taking steps to
eliminate the red tape that frustrates small business owners like
Griffin. He also said that any governor would have been stymied by
the problems arising from such a dramatic drop in foreign
investment as Hawaii experienced, to less than $500 million in 1994
from $3.6 billion in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Though conceding that the state must do a better job finding new
sources of jobs and revenues to ease the reliance on tourism as the
major economic engine, he said many voters had ignored the
accomplishments of his administration and failed to see the nascent
signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged that convincing voters that the state
is finally on the right track could be a daunting challenge this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big mood for change here,'' he said, referring to
Ms. Lingle. ``She is the favorite to win the Republican primary.
She is a good speaker, and she has painted herself as a fresh face
on the screen. But we have planted the seeds so we can diversify
the economy. And finally we are seeing some positive signs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GLOOM-NYT &LR;      08-23 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GLOOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS SHAKEN BY PRESIDENT'S ADMISSION
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-STARR-STRATEGY, CLINTON-CHURCHES,
CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-VACATION) 
(jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton began his speech
acknowledging a relationship with Monica Lewinsky, many federal
officials were hoping it would put an end to the distractions and
malaise that have affected much of the work of government of the
last seven months. Instead, policy mavens working on issues like
housing and health care, AIDS and international problems said they
had experienced a kind of collective shudder.
</P>
<P>
   A few felt personally offended by the president's unsavory
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, who had been a 21-year-old intern
at the White House and whose link to the president was made
irrefutable by his admission.
</P>
<P>
   But most simply expressed profound disappointment, more
professional than personal. Their faith shaken, many of these
officials said they now faced a potential sustained fallout that
threatened to weaken not just Clinton's legacy but his
administration's muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Jennings, a White House aide who coordinates health
policy for the president, said he had a sense of ``lost
opportunities and missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're frustrated that this has distracted from our ability to
push his agenda,'' Jennings said. ``We are disappointed in him for
contributing to his problems in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   For an administration characterized by its relative youth and
verve, last Monday's presidential speech, with its blend of
confession and defiance, seemed to exhaust and bewilder. ``Everyone
here is best described as sort of numb, and dismayed,'' Jennings
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all his soldiers,'' Jennings added. ``If he and Mrs.
Clinton want to do something, we'll do it for them. I don't think
anyone here feels any less commitment to do positive things for
this country. But there's a sense of frustration that we can't
focus on issues that really mean something to people day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the president's evident engagement in foreign policy
matters, several aides and federal officials said they harbored
serious doubts about his ability, or desire, to push for a domestic
agenda as he wrangled with his legal troubles. Clinton had no
choice but to react to a foreign policy emergency. But the
officials were considerably less optimistic about issues like
health care and environmental policy, issues that typically require
long attention spans and a willingness to slug it out with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Months and months have been wasted,'' said Ezekiel Emanuel,
the chief bioethics officer at the National Institutes of Health,
adding that there has been ``a lot of drift'' since the first
accusations of sex and lies in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Clinton's reputation for compartmentalizing his
problems, a talent that has kept him focused even during his most
trying moments, Emanuel could not help but wonder whether the
Lewinsky matter and its expected repercussions on Capitol Hill
would tap him out. ``It's got to sap the guy's energy and ability
to focus,'' Emanuel said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in Congress have been grumbling about
Clinton's arm's-length posture since early this year, saying it
made governing in tandem, always a delicate prospect, even more
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, many of Clinton's supporters had offered him the
benefit of the doubt, and a few loyal followers risked their own
credibility defending him publicly and privately. One official
seemed shaken on a more personal level about Clinton's admission.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who worked on Clinton's 1992 campaign and now works on
foreign policy for the administration dismissed the Lewinsky
allegations several months ago. ``We worked very hard for this man,
and I don't believe he did those things,'' she said at the time.
``I just don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, when asked about the president's admission of ``a
relationship with Miss Lewinsky,'' the same official, again
speaking on the condition of anonymity, said: ``This is really a
very painful topic. I don't want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were not surprised that Clinton committed an
indiscretion. They said they could not fathom how anyone who had
worked with the president for an extended period of time could
indulge in ``choirboy'' illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why everyone is now walking around with shock on their faces
is a mystery to me,'' said Sandra Thurman, the director of the
White House Office of National AIDS Policy who also helped the
Clinton team handle the uproar over Gennifer Flowers in the 1992
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thurman likened the scandal's effect on policy to a ``slow
leak'' in a boat, one that does not necessarily spell doom for its
passengers. Acknowledging that she feels ``a sense of
frustration,'' she added: ``Our work continues, but the Lewinsky
matter does make the water a little choppy to navigate. It doesn't
change the respect I have for the president or how I feel about his
commitment to addressing the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
