<HEADER>
A7985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-PAKISTAN-600&AMP;A     08-23 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-PAKISTAN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVOR INSISTS ATTACKED AFGHAN CAMP WAS RELIGIOUS SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-RDP, ATTACK-SUDAN, ATTACK-AFGHAN-TERRAIN,
ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-ALBANIA-SHOOT, ATTACK-KENYA) 
(js) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESHAWAR, Pakistan _ Dr. Ahmad Sarwar insists he is not a
terrorist, that he was at a camp not far from here, on the other
side of the border in Afghanistan, for religious studies. The 60
students in the camp last Thursday were reading and studying the
Koran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just finished our dinner, we were preparing to go to
bed,'' he said in the Hayatabad hospital here, where he was
visiting an injured comrade on Sunday. ``We saw a fireball coming
toward us, which hit an area 15 yards away.''
</P>
<P>
   They ran for cover, he said, and there were five or six more
explosions. He escaped injury. Twenty-one people died, 15 while
sleeping in the mosque, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sarwar, 38, was at the camp known as Harkat Mujahedeen, one of
those hit by U.S. missiles last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the attack was to break what the United States says
is a terrorist network led by Osama bin Laden, the man the
Americans say was responsible for the bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Sarwar denied Sunday that the camps were for anything other than
religious purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Moslem has the right to study in a religious school,''
he said. ``We had no guns. We did no wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarwar said he is an Afghan. In the hospital where he spoke with
reporters, another man, Habib-ur-Rehman, 22, lay hooked up to an
intravenous feeding machine, suffering from serious injuries from
the missile attack. He too said that he is an Afghan who had been
at the camp for religious purposes. But Pakistani reporters who
interviewed the men Saturday said that both are Pakistani.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials, as well as Pakistani journalists and
residents of this region, said the camps the Americans hit were
military training centers. They say that two camps were for
Pakistanis and Afghans and another was for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   They say that those trained in the Harkat Mujahedeen camp _ the
name comes from a Pakistani-based Islamic movement _ are sent to
fight in Kashmir, where Pakistani-backed rebels have waged a long
war for independence from India, Pakistan's regional enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Harkat Mujahedeen is the name for a group that was called Harkat
Ansar until the State Department put it on its list of terrorist
groups last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, bin Laden was rebuked by Mullah Mohammed Omar, the
spiritual leader of the Taliban, the fundamentalist Islamic
movement that is the de facto government of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Omar was upset that after the missile attack bin Laden publicly
issued new threats against Americans, saying that the war had just
begun. ``I have sent my envoy to tell him that he should show
restraint, and that we cannot have two parallel emirates in
Afghanistan,'' Omar said in a telephone interview Sunday with
Rahimullah Yusufzai, the bureau chief here for The News, an
English-language daily. ``We have conveyed to him that the Islamic
Emirate of Afghanistan will take appropriate measures to give an
answer to the attack on its soil by the U.S. at an appropriate
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has been operating in Afghanistan for two years. While
the Taliban have made repeated promises to restrict his activities,
the Clinton administration says they have not done so.
</P>
<P>
   The reprimand reflects a struggle between the two men for the
limelight and not a split over policy or activities, said Yusufzai,
who has been covering the Taliban for several years. Omar is
apparently unhappy that the Taliban's recent victories _ they have
vanquished most of their opponents and now control most of the
country _ have been lost in the focus on bin Laden's bombs and
bombast.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Taliban authorities in Afghanistan have refused to allow
journalists to enter the country since the missile attack, giving
rise to conjecture among journalists and diplomats that the sites
hit were indeed military camps and not religious schools, as the
Taliban contend, and that the number of casualties was not high.
</P>
<P>
   Four senior journalists who tried to reach the area where the
missiles hit have been missing since Friday morning and are
presumably being held by the Taliban at Khost, the town nearest to
the camps attacked by the Americans. They are B.K. Bangash, a
Pakistani photographer with The Associated Press; his younger
brother Said, a photographer with Agence France-Presse; Zaheeruddin
Abdullah, an Afghan reporter for AP; and Salahuddin, who uses only
one name, an Afghan reporter with the Reuters news service.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it was that he had managed to escape death when the
missiles had landed so close to him, Sarwar said Sunday, ``God
Almighty save us because we are Moslems and God helps Moslems and
not non-Moslems. We are innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, seeming to belie his insistence that the camps were for
only for the purpose of religious education, he said, ``We will
show the Americans when we strike back how God punishes them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
