<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Los Angeles Dodgers
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: 1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: LHP Tom Glavine (16-5, 2.53;
13-14, 3.90 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. LHP Brian Bohanon (6-8, 2.85;
0-1, 5.73 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Notes: Glavine resumes his quest for his fourth 20-win season
and first since 1993. This is his first outing of the year against
the Dodgers, one of only two teams with winning records against the
lefthander. He'd won four straight decisions, the last two
complete-game shutouts that extended his scoreless innings streak
to 23, before San Francisco beat Glavine 6-2 Wednesday. That outing
(eight singles, five runs, five innings) was Glavine's shortest in
20 appearances since May 3. Bohanon, acquired July 10 from the Mets
for ex-Brave reliever Greg McMichael, is 4-4 with a 2.52 ERA in
eight starts with L.A., where's he's thrown far better as a starter
than he did in Flushing. He became just the second left-hander to
start for the Dodgers in the last seven seasons (Carlos Perez,
Sunday night's starter, became the third). Bohanon is coming off a
6-5 loss Wednesday in PIttsburgh. Three of the six runs he allowed
were unearned, two scoring on Bohanon's own throwing error.
Primarily a reliever in New York (four starts, 21 relief
appearances), Bohanon served up Rafael Belliard's epic home run
last Sept. 26, Belliard's second career homer and first after 10
years and 1,869 at-bats. Tony Graffanino, the Braves right-handed
hitting second baseman, will be in the lineup. With good reason:
he's 4-for-4 lifetime off Bohanon, with a homer; Gerald Williams is
a career .750 hitter (6-for-8) against him.
</P>
