</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDONARO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Election ad spending a hot topic in California
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. _ The residents of the central California
coast have grown accustomed to costly advertising by outsiders in
their political affairs, but this year they may have their
congressional campaign to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups that spent heavily on radio and television
advertising in successive congressional campaigns are planning more
modest forays or nothing at all in the district that takes in a
sizable chunk of the Pacific coast between Los Angeles and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And the people who endured ads about late-term abortions, terms
limits and other issues are grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mind them speaking out. It's the amount of money they
spent that really bothers me,'' said Suzette Caddy, a homemaker
from San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   Caddy was among 350 Republicans who sat in an unairconditioned
junior college gymnasium Sunday to hear Speaker Newt Gingrich
endorse Republican Tom Bordonaro in his rematch with Democratic
Rep. Lois Capps.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.), chairman of the House Republicans'
campaign committee, made a separate visit to the district this
weekend for Bordonaro.
</P>
<P>
   Capps beat Bordonaro in a closely watched special election in
March to fill the seat held by her husband, Walter, who died of a
heart attack in October.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Capps ousted Republican Rep. Andrea Seastrand in 1996,
when a dozen independent groups flooded the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans both complained that the candidates'
views were lost in the cacophony of ads. ``It became a race of what
others wanted it to be and not necessarily the message I wanted to
get out,'' Bordonaro said.
</P>
<P>
   But the anticipated change in 1998 is not some noble gesture on
the part of the independent groups that evade federal limits on
campaign spending by running ads that technically do not support or
oppose anyone, but make clear where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in the view of Eric O'Keefe, whose term-limits group
plans up to $10 million in ads nationwide this year, this election
is not in doubt, despite the high-level campaign stops this
weekend,.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, Capps would win it and we don't see any reason
to go in,'' said O'Keefe, director of Americans for Limited Terms .
</P>
<P>
   Capps signed the group's pledge not to serve more than six
years, and benefitted from its advertising when Bordonaro refused
to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are willing to speak as bluntly as O'Keefe, but the
conservative Campaign for Working Families, which advertised
Bordonaro's support for and Capps's opposition to a ban in certain
late-term abortions, did not include Bordonaro on the list of
candidates it has endorsed for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And in another sign, Linder refused to commit the resources of
the Republican campaign committee, which is planning a $37 million
advertising campaign much like those of the independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional district is considered closely divided between
Democrats and Republicans, but University of California at San
Diego political scientist Gary Jacobson said Bordonaro is more
conservative than the district. The one issue that O'Keefe said
could make the contest closer is President Clinton's relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Gingrich also
touched on the topic in his remarks, recalling his first
congressional campaign in 1974 in the wake of President Nixon's
resignation from office. He lost that race, which he blamed in part
on disillusioned Republicans who chose not to vote that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not drawing any direct parallels with this year,''
Gingrich said, conveying precisely the opposite impression.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
