<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SHAKEUP-525&AMP;AD     08-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SHAKEUP-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN DISMISSES ECONOMIC REFORMERS, REINSTATES CHERNOMYRDIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-CHERNOMYRDIN, RUSSIA-REACT) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a desperate grasp for political support, President
Boris Yeltsin Sunday fired his new team of economic reformers and
reinstated Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's surprise decision came just five months after he
derided Chernomyrdin as a spent force and cast him out of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt action raised fresh doubts about the Kremlin's
commitment to tough economic reforms, as well as unsettling
questions about Yeltsin's ability to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has hired and fired top aides so often that government
shake-ups have become a common feature of Russia's politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's decision to substitute the stolid Chernomyrdin for
the reform-minded Sergei Kiriyenko was a stunning one _ even for
the mercurial Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin offered no public explanation Sunday night for his
decision, which was disclosed in a terse statement on the evening
television news, just after the reports on the day's sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
   To many commentators, however, it seemed that the Russian
president had decided that his political survival was more
important than plowing ahead with an aggressive program of economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   While Chernomyrdin, 60, is seen by most of the Russian public as
an uninspiringly figure, he is a consensus figure for much of the
power elite.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial oligarchy sees Chernomyrdin as a far more
sympathetic and pliable leader than the brainy Kiriyenko. The
Russian press has been rife with reports that Boris Berezovsky, the
tycoon and media mogul, was plotting to restore Chernomyrdin to
power.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also appears to be calculating that the appointment of
Chernomyrdin will deflate the repeated calls in the
Communist-dominated parliament for Yeltsin's resignation. As the
former head of the Soviet gas industry, Chernomyrdin has maintained
good relations with the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The same factors that make Chernomyrdin an acceptable leader for
financiers and Communists, however, make him a questionable choice
to extract Russia's from its economic quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   During his first five years as prime minister, Chernomyrdin
presided over Russia's unsteady march toward capitalism. But he
also tolerated much of the cronyism and many of the half-measures
that have helped bring Russia to its current impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin acknowledged as much just last March when he told the
nation that he was firing Chernomyrdin because a new, young team
was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is whether the return of a veteran
politician like Chernomyrdin would restore a sense of political
stability or add to the feeling that Yeltsin was grasping at straws
in his efforts to cope with the escalating financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian banks on the brink of insolvency and the ruble in
decline, Russia faces a number of critical policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It must decide on a way to restructure its short-term debt. It
must determine how many politically connected banks it can afford
to bail out. It must also find a way to reassure anxious foreign
investors, who have been fleeing in droves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Kremlin sought Sunday night to reassure the Clinton
administration that the shake-up was not a economic retreat.
Chernomyrdin and Kiriyenko spoke separately Sunday evening by
telephone with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said that both Russian officials ``put a
strong emphasis on continuing the march.'' But he acknowledged that
the neither provided any specifics or explained the reason for
Yeltsin's move.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian politicians were far less charitable.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Lukin, a leading member of the opposition Yabloko
party, said that Yeltsin's decision was evidence of ``profound
confusion and uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Anders Aslund, a former economic adviser to the Yeltsin
government and a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, described the shake-up as ``a setback on all
fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin helped cause the crisis,'' Aslund added. ``To
bring him pack is like reappointing Suharto in Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, the suddenness of Sunday night's move added a
further, unwelcome element of instability. The last time Yeltsin
dismissed his government, he ended up reappointing most of his top
aides to government posts. But Sunday night's statement did not
make clear which Kremlin aides would be reappointed and which would
be sacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
