<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8006 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MILLION-YOUTH-MARC     08-23 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-2TAKES(720)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE APPLICATIONS ERUPTED INTO RACE-TINGED FIGHT OVER YOUTH
MARCH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In late January, New York City received two
applications from a nonprofit organization in Washington seeking
permission to stage a ``First Amendment Educational Event.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the applications were routine if somewhat unclear,
representing only two of the tens of thousands of requests the city
receives every year for block parties, parades and street fairs. In
another sense, the two pieces of paper were the bureaucratic
equivalent to kindling; in the months to come, they would pit an
out-of-town black nationalist who spouts anti-Semitism with a smile
against an outspoken white mayor with few ties to the city's black
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Khalid Abdul Muhammad _ best known for his anti-white
diatribes _ has charged in a lawsuit filed in federal court that
the discriminatory policies of the Giuliani administration prompted
it to deny his application for a Million Youth March in Harlem on
Sept. 5, the Saturday of the hectic Labor Day weekend. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, meanwhile, has alternated between keeping his
counsel and denouncing the event as a poorly planned ``hate march''
that his aides expect will take place in some form, permit or no
permit.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle of this race-tinged quarrel is the
community of Harlem, whose leaders are now bracing for an event
that several of them never wanted. Some criticize Muhammad for
promoting an event that couples, however subtly, the instructive
message of black-youth empowerment with destructive messages of
intolerance. They also say that for all his talk of black unity, he
was woefully late in sharing his plans with most of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me get this straight,'' said Bill Perkins, the community's
City Council member. ``You're going to have a party in my house and
you don't even tell me about it?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, several leaders say Giuliani has used harsh,
simplistic language to describe an event that also stresses pride
in the black community and loving guidance for its young. The mayor
can afford to generalize, they say, because most of his political
support comes from white and conservative communities, far from the
streets of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   These leaders say many people may participate in anti-Giuliani
protest rather than in pro-Muhammad support. After all, they argue,
Muhammad has neither the appeal nor the money to stage a
significant event _ especially when another, better-organized event
for the country's black youths is being held in Atlanta on the same
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of any individual who has been more deliberately
destructive than Khalid Muhammad, but what separates him from just
being a racist is that his statements are all calculated to evoke a
reaction,'' said state Sen. David Paterson of Harlem. ``And he
tried to use inflammatory language to dupe Mayor Giuliani into
attacking him. And since Giuliani is an unpopular person in the
African-American community, he then comes back to the community and
plays himself off as a martyr, an Adam Powell who is being
attacked, or a Malcolm X. He disguises himself as the current-day
Adam or Malcolm, when in fact he's a cheap carbon copy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Paterson said, the mayor ``gave the marchers what
they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing such opinions as ``absurd'' on Saturday, Giuliani
used the very language that makes some Harlem leaders cringe. ``We
either had to just ignore it and pretend that a person who has
engaged in the worst kind of rhetoric about Jews, about whites,
about Catholics, about the pope _ that he should be allowed to
carry a banner leading a lot of children. Or we could say something
about it, which we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides leave the First Amendment implications of
blocking the march to be discussed in court, with the next hearing
scheduled for Wednesday. But they maintain that the administration
has wisely handled one of the most delicate, and potentially
volatile, predicaments that a municipality can face. As for the
mayor's occasional comments, Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington said New
York City was more than just Harlem; there are Jews, Roman
Catholics, gay men and lesbians _ all concerned with the message of
Khalid Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know that the leader of this city is focused,''
he said. ``They want to hear what he's thinking.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At first, no one knew what to think, in part because Muhammad's
plans kept changing. In the applications filed in January, his
aides requested the date of Sept. 19, not Sept. 5; they now say
they want to reach young people before schools and colleges reopen.
One request asked for Eastern Parkway in Brooklyn; the other asked
for Malcolm X Boulevard in Harlem. In a third request, organizers
had also asked for Central Park, Randalls Island ``or street.''
</P>
<P>
   If Muhammad's intentions were unclear, his history was not. The
man behind the applications is so virulent in his anti-Semitic,
anti-white speeches that he managed to annoy Louis Farrakhan, the
minister of the Nation of Islam who has also been known to make
anti-Semitic remarks. Since being ousted from the Nation of Islam
hierarchy in 1994, Muhammad has become a college-campus attraction
who commonly refers to Jews as ``bloodsuckers'' and ``hook-nosed.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Washington, the discussions between the city and
the organizers began poorly and got worse. After the two sides
failed to agree on a site for the march or a date, Muhammad told
the city in last May or early June that the march would take place
in Harlem over the Labor Day weekend. City officials explained that
more than 100 permits had already been granted for activities in
Harlem for that Saturday, that the before-school sales of local
businesses would be disrupted and that the police for the holiday
weekend were already taxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he tells us what he's going to do,'' Washington
recalled, ``against the will of the city, without permits.'' He
added, ``They virtually hijacked the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Malik Shabazz, a lawyer from Washington and a close aide of
Muhammad's, said the organizers had become frustrated with what
they perceived to be an institutional thwarting of their rights to
free speech. ``Essentially, they were trying to derail the
process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By early July, Harlem's leaders had learned from news reports
that an event called the Million Youth March was probably coming to
their neighborhood. They also learned that both the city had been
discussing this possibility for weeks but never called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us felt that they're calling on us to deal with this,
but when we have other issues _ youth issues or other concerns _ we
don't get the calls back,'' Perkins said. ``But overriding that was
the sense of responsibility that this was taking place in our
neighborhood. And regardless of the poor behavior of the mayor, we
had a responsibility to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington dismissed those concerns, saying that notification a
few days earlier would not have changed the dynamics. And there was
another factor. ``The Giuliani administration doesn't negotiate by
consensus,'' he said. ``They're legislators. They don't run
programs, they don't operate the city, with all due respect to
them. Never do we call people and ask for their advice ...''
</P>
<P>
   Paterson said that attitude was both typical and self-defeating.
``No one is denying that he's excellent in lowering the crime rate
and being the catalyst for business and economic development,'' he
said of the mayor. ``Black people are affected by that, too. But he
comes to the table with such a negative understanding of how black
people feel: `They're not going to support me, so I'm not going to
pay attention to their concerns.'''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad issued thinly veiled threats of what might happen if
the city did not relent, and reminisced about bringing 50 armed
followers to a Ku Klux Klan rally in Jasper, Tex., in June. He also
threatened to lead an angry march, including gang members, through
the Jewish neighborhood of Crown Heights in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have radical revolutionary youth who will be coming here,''
he said, ``who will be quite ready and quite prepared in the
numbers of hundreds and thousands and millions to fight this devil
in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani assailed Muhammad as a hatemonger _ correctly, Paterson
said. But he said the mayor had coupled that condemnation with the
denial of the march permit, allowing critics to contend that the
strong-willed mayor was violating constitutional rights to block
yet another message that he found offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, the Rev. Calvin Butts III, a prominent Baptist
minister who was criticized earlier this year for calling Giuliani
a racist, expressed his support for the march, but not for
Muhammad. The mayor seized the opportunity to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have forgotten, but I don't, the hate language he used
in reference to me,'' Giuliani said last Thursday. ``So I would
expect that he would naturally gravitate toward a march that
engages in this kind of hate rhetoric against Jews, against other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterson, Perkins, and others in Harlem saw the mayor's remarks
as gratuitous and inflammatory. Perkins said he immediately told
Washington to deliver a message: ``Tell him to please shut up. Now,
you put it to him the way you think appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear where this fight over the rights to a Saturday in
Harlem will lead. Although most agree that a Million Youth March
would not attract a million people _ organizers predict about
150,000, while city officials expect a much smaller number _ there
remain many questions without answers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem, an early critic of Muhammad,
declined to say whether the city could have handled the situation
better. He said his time and thoughts would be better spent on
joining others in preparing Harlem for the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sensitive thing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
