<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGTRIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS POISED TO BATTLE BEASTS OF THE EAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are places that so many Angels seasons have gone
to die. New York. Boston. Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mention of the 10-game East Coast trip that begins
tonight at Yankee Stadium has caused Angels players and coaches to
shudder at the thought. During the just-concluded homestand, mere
mention of ``the trip'' was met with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real easy to look ahead to the Yankees, Boston and
Cleveland,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said last Monday. ``But
we've got to take care of business. If we have a big homestand,
it'll take some of the sting away from going on that trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began the homestand one-half game ahead of Texas,
then went 5-2 against the White Sox, Tigers and Blue Jays and head
into tonight's game against the Yankees with a xx-game lead in the
AL West. It isn't as big a cushion as the Angels would like to
have. After all, Texas had to play the same three beasts of the
East last week and didn't lose much ground to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the tables are turned.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch time begins immediately, because the Angels will play
five games against the Yankees in four days. Two are makeup games
resulting from the falling expansion joint at Yankee Stadium in
April. A day-night doubleheader is scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are on pace to win more games than any team in
baseball history. Yet the Angels start the series as the only team
in baseball not to have a losing record against New York. The
Angels and Yankees have split six games so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look and see the Yankees are 20 games up and
say, `What motivation do they have?''' said Angels second baseman
Randy Velarde, an ex-Yankee. ``But their motivation is trying to
break the (wins) record. We're not going to catch them off guard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect to win five games in a row (in New York),''
center fielder Jim Edmonds said. ``But we expect to have five
well-played games. We've played well against the Yankees this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it a make-or-break trip and you'll have an argument. No
matter what lies ahead on this trip _ which includes three against
the Red Sox and two against the Indians _ the Angels have
maintained that one-game-at-a-time mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not a make-or-break trip,'' Collins said. ``We have
too many games to play after that. We've still got five games with
Texas. Make-or-break trip? No, but it's a huge trip. Playing the
Yankees five times, you could go 0-5 before you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels don't have the talent the Yankees have, and one could
probably say the same thing about the Angels when compared with
Boston and Cleveland. But there is something about this Angels
team, players are saying.
</P>
<P>
   A season-long rash of injuries has slowed the Angels but not
stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the dead-on talent of other teams I've been
on,'' said pitcher Jack McDowell, formerly of the White Sox,
Yankees and Indians. ``But this team knows how to grind to be
successful. I like this team. It perseveres. It has the aspects
needed to win. This team has been through everything and it's still
scrapping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a guy in the top 10 in home runs or the top 10
in RBIs,'' Collins said. ``But what we do have is guys in the top
10 in effort. And we have seven guys in the top 10 of players who
go from first to third on a single. They've played every night
hard. It's why this is a fun team to watch, a fun team to be
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
