u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-800(2TA     08-23 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: APPOINTMENT SEEN AS YELTSIN'S DESPERATE MOVE TO RESTORE
CREDIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-SHAKEUP, RUSSIA-CHERNOMYRDIN, RUSSIA-REACT) 
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ What can you say about a president who fires his
government, then reappoints the prime minister he fired five months
ago, at a moment when his country is teetering on the edge of
financial collapse?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the latest surprise move by President Boris
Yeltsin of Russia is widely seen as an act of desperation, carried
out at a moment when his political credibility and clout are in
danger of being swept away by Russia's latest financial shock
waves.
</P>
<P>
   One question now is whether Yeltsin is trying to salvage his own
leadership at the expense of the program of economic reform that he
has embraced since coming to power seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another more troubling question is whether Yeltsin, who at 67
has seemed increasingly infirm in rare recent public appearances,
is orchestrating this latest political upheaval himself, or whether
he has already become a figurehead manipulated by unseen forces _
doomed to repeat the pathetic performance of some of the Soviet
Union's last ailing leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden dismissal of Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, which
had been rumored in Moscow all weekend, was in itself not so
surprising, considering the political storms that blew up this week
over the government's decision to let the ruble drop in value and
to freeze Russian debts. Kiriyenko, a 36-year-old former banker,
was chosen by Yeltsin in March in part because he had no political
base and was thus free to make unpopular decisions. Sunday night,
he was dismissed essentially for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   In reappointing the 60-year-old Viktor Chernomyrdin, an
old-style Soviet manager, Yeltsin is reaching out to a familiar
political figure, whose ties stretch deep into the back benches of
the anti-Yeltsin opposition in the Russian Parliament and also to
the so-called ``oligarchs,'' as Russia's band of politically
powerful bankers and tycoons are known.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin offers the prospect of a government with a broader
base of political support, which could blunt the opposition, and
quell its unending debate over whether the president should be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Such political calculations, however, do not answer the question
that many Russians have been asking for months now, as they watch
their country lurch from crisis to crisis, waiting for some kind of
political and economic stability so they can get on with their
lives: Is Yeltsin running the country, they ask, and if he isn't,
then who is?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's action by Yeltsin, taken without explanation and
without a personal appearance by the president, was hardly
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sign of wild panic in the Kremlin,'' said Aleksei
Melnikov, a spokesman for an opposition party headed by Grigory
Yavlinsky, a liberal reformer who has been one of Yeltsin's most
consistent critics. ``The country is on the threshold of a banking
crisis, and the best they can do is put their prayers on
Chernomyrdin.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksander Livshits, a top Yeltsin economic adviser who resigned
last week as the country went into a monetary tailspin, expressed
loyalty to both Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin, but his assessment was no
less blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very serious,'' he told a television
interviewer on Sunday night. ``I, as you know, have never been
inclined to panic, but I have to say that in its seriousness, this
is unprecedented in all the years of reform. We have never yet been
in such a situation before.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past two weeks, as Russia's banking crisis ran
headlong into the government's own cash crunch, Yeltsin has used
his annual August vacation to take shelter from the political
fallout. Last weekend, he moved closer to Moscow to consult with
top officials and in the end, gave his approval to the government's
controversial anti-crisis program. But he has yet to step forward _
as he did last May during an earlier crisis _ to take
responsibility and to lend the government his political support.
</P>
<P>
   The president has been openly mocked in much of the Russian
press for his absence. Such contempt for him would have been
unthinkable in the early years of his government, when he still
wore the popular glow he had earned as the leader of the
anti-Communist opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, even before he climbed on the tank to rout the
1991 coup, he was the only politician of popular stature who could
wade into a crowd, urging weary Russians to challenge authority and
to take control of their future.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, as people have struggled to figure out the
value of their currency, he was being remembered for having said,
as recently as eight days ago, that the ruble would not be
devalued. He also pledged that day to keep Kiriyenko in his job.
``I will keep him on,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   His behavior during his two public appearances in recent weeks _
at a Novgorod meatpacking plant, and, on Friday, to review naval
exercises off the Arctic circle _ did little to restore public
faith. He stomped through the sausage factory like the Communist
boss he once was and made painfully unphotogenic grimaces during
meetings with sailors aboard a navy cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television viewers have already compared Yeltsin to the
late Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev in his final years, when his
wooden demeanor became the butt of Russian underground humor. But
in a more sinister view, many analysts were saying Sunday that
Yeltsin, in appointing Chernomyrdin, has revealed himself to be a
captive of the ``oligarchs,'' many of whom are now fighting a
behind-the-scenes battle to save their banks from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been saying that the Chernomyrdin appointment
suggests that economic reformers in Russia have not been strong
enough to hold up to crony capitalism, which they fear will now be
set free to hold the Russian economy hostage to their own private
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Which way the Chernomyrdin government will move is unclear,
despite Chernomyrdin's reassurances to Vice President Al Gore that
he will continue the austere program of economic reform hammered
out last month with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue will be the future of Boris Fyodorov, the
tough-talking director of Russia's tax police, who was named deputy
prime Minister in charge of economic policy last week. Fyodorov,
who resigned once from Chernomyrdin's earlier government, was due
to make an announcement on Monday on restructuring Russia's
domestic debt. The issue has been closely watched by foreign
investors for signs of preference for Russia's beleaguered banks.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Chernomyrdin manages to muddle through the financial
crisis, it may not be enough to save Yeltsin's credibility, or any
hopes he may have held for another run for the presidency in the
year 2000. Even before the summer's tumultuous events, Yeltsin was
clearly losing the support of Russia's media barons, who have been
openly courting other presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Russian public likely to forgive the president for
having left them, as they see it, in the lurch. ``Public trust in
Yeltsin and Kiriyenko was already sinking,'' said Igor Babichev, a
newspaper editor in the central Russian city of Kaluga, late last
week. ``Now it has been completely buried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
