<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday night games still out: Yankees-Rangers.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 4-2 (94-32), Orioles 4-3 (69-61), Red Sox 5-2
(76-52), Blue Jays 4-3 (66-64), Devil Rays 1-6 (49-79).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Red Sox continue to hold on to a big
advantage in the wildcard race, their big bat continuing to be MVP
candidate Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken scored his
1,500th run on Saturday. He also picked up his 2,848th hit the game
before, passing Brooks Robinson for the franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Red Sox lefthander Steve Avery pitched a
season-high seven innings Friday in a 9-2 win over the Twins while
Roger Clemens won his 10th straight for Toronto, a 7-0 shutout over
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Yankees can reach win No. 100 this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Orioles placed Scott Kamieniecki on the DL
with a bulging disk in his right upper back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Red Sox have put Pete Schourek in the rotation
and moved John Wasdin to the bullpen. The club was considering
putting Avery in the rotation but he has struggled there while
Wasdin has had better luck working as a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Before the season started, many
pointed to this weekend's series between the Yankees and the
Mariners as a big one. But this set means nothing as New York has
36 more wins than Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Royals 4-3 (59-71), Indians 4-3 (71-58), Twins 3-4
(57-72), Tigers 2-6 (50-79), White Sox 1-6 (56-72).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Indians extended the contract of manager
Mike Hargrove through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: While Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams is
leading the league with a .353 average, Minnesota's Todd Walker is
making a late run, hitting .340.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Indians may have the third-best ERA in the
league 4.29, but it is significantly higher than the league-leading
Yankees (3.61).
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Kansas City shortstop Jose Offerman has
reached base in 41 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Royals righthander Hipolito Pichardo will miss
the rest of the season with a right elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The White Sox recently drew 511 canines to their
third annual Dog Day Afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Indians host the A's this
weekend. Oh boy!
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: A's 6-2 (60-71), Angels 5-2 (71-59), Mariners 4-3
(59-69), Rangers 2-4 (67-61).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: What is wrong with the Rangers? They made one
big deal after another before the trading deadline but find
themselves 3 games off the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: After going 10 games with just two RBIs, Rangers
designated hitter Juan Gonzalez drove in five runs Saturday and
pushed his league lead to 126.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Angels got a big boost when Jack McDowell
came off the DL and threw shutout innings last Wednesday in a win
over the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. had just one homer
in the last 21 games before hitting one Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Rangers righthander Roger Pavlik will undergo
rotator cuff surgery this week, ending his season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: This might sound incredible but 47 baserunners have
tried to steal with Anaheim's Jeff Juden on the mound and 42 of
them have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Angels have been hot but they
have to open the week with Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
