<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday night Braves-Dodgers game not listed.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Mets 6-3 (72-58), Braves 3-2 (85-44), Phillies 4-4
(64-66), Expos 2-5 (51-80), Marlins 1-5 (45-85).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Mets lead league, Phillies 8 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The 32-year-old Greg Maddux won his 200th game
and only four pitchers currently younger than the Braves
righthander have 115 wins or more - John Smoltz (140), Ramon
Martinez (123), Mike Mussina (117) and Andy Benes (115).
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Braves collected nine hits against the
Giants last Tuesday and all nine were doubles.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Braves closer Kerry Ligtenberg has not given up
an earned run in his last 20 games while Braves righthander John
Smoltz has won seven straight.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Braves castoff Paul Byrd won again, this time
the Phillies righthander beating the Rockies 6-1 on Saturday as he
retired 13 of the last 14 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Braves placed Mark Wohlers on the disabled
list for what they term the ``inability to pitch'' while the
Marlins placed reliever Matt Mantei on the DL with a sprained right
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Expos are close to signing outfielder Vladimir
Guerrero to a long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: Florida general manager Dave
Dombrowski will interview for the vacant GM job with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Pirates 6-0 (62-68), Astros 5-2 (81-50), Cubs 3-3
(71-59), Brewers 3-3 (62-68), Reds 3-3 (59-71), Cardinals 3-5
(62-68).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Cubs 1 game back, Cardinals and Brewers 10
games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Mark McGwire broke Babe Ruth's record for
homers in three consecutive seasons by hitting his 52nd homer
Saturday. Hitting another one Sunday, McGwire has 163 homers over
the last three years while Ruth hit 161 from 1926-28.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Milwaukee's Bobby Hughes hit a 434-foot homer at
County Stadium on Saturday, the second longest at the park this
season behind Andres Galarraga's 435-foot shot back on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Randy Johnson is 4-1 with the Astros with 45
strikeouts in 37 innings.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Ron Gant hit his 20th home run and gave the
Cardinals four players with 20 or more homers in one season for the
first time. McGwire has 53, Ray Lankford has 23 and Brian Jordan
has 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Cardinals activated righthander Juan Acevedo
from the DL. He took the roster spot of released catcher Tom
Pagnozzi.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: McGwire was upset about a story that disclosed he
uses an over-the-counter testosterone-producing strength enhancer
legal in baseball but not in the NFL, NCAA and Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: McGwire has to face Braves
pitching for four games. The last time he went hitless against
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Giants 3-3 (69-61), Rockies 4-4 (60-71), Padres 3-3
(83-47), Dodgers 2-3 (64-65), Diamondbacks 3-5 (49-82).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Giants 3 games back, Dodgers 8 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Nobody had a winning week and the Giants failed
to make up any ground in the wildcard hunt.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Giants second baseman Jeff Kent has hit 13
homers and driven in 27 runs in the last 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: San Diego's Kevin Brown and Andy Ashby each have
16 wins.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Colorado's Curtis Goodwin is 0-for-16 as a
pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Dodgers placed righthander Darren Hall on
the DL with a rotator cuff problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth, who has been
on the disabled list since June 5 after shoulder surgery, has told
the club he will play in the Dominican Winter League to help get
ready for next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's happening this week: The Giants return home Tuesday for
three against the Mets and four with the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
