<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NCSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Cain breathes new life into NC State program
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. -- A year ago, you could have gotten any odds you
wanted that North Carolina State would have a new head football
coach by the end of December.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack had become spoiled, stringing together seven
straight bowl appearances from 1988-94 before Mike O'Cain let
things slip in '95 and finished 3-8. When the 'Pack followed with
another 3-8 finish, O'Cain looked to be out the door.
</P>
<P>
   But two things happened last year that enabled the affable State
coach to secure a new five-year deal. The Wolfpack shocked everyone
by opening with a 32-31 win at Syracuse and then, following a
mid-season swoon, finished by outscoring Florida State in the
second half of a game they lost 48-35 and built on that by winning
their last three.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-5 mark didn't net the 'Pack a bowl, but it did give O'Cain
new life.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State enters this season without tailback Tremayne Stephens
and running mate Carlos King, but returns quarterback Jamie
Barnette, All-ACC receiver Torry Holt and most of its offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the 'Pack will be missing six starters, and that
may be more devastating than having to find a new running game.
</P>
<P>
   To add more mystery to what may be a transitional year, Barnette
badly sprained his knee in a tag football game in June and has yet
to get back to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So what's to make anyone believe State may be better this year
than last?
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sure there is anything,'' said O'Cain. ''The only
thing this year, we're going into the season with confidence.
That's something we didn't do last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you get past Holt and a suspect Barnette in the offensive
skills department, there is little to recommend the Wolfpack.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel we've got a sound offensive line,'' said Ian Rafferty,
a 6-6, 300-pound senior tackle. And I think we're going to be able
to run. You can't win just by throwing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question is who's going to run it. Senior Jeff
Butler is penciled in at fullback and junior Rahshon Spikes at
tailback, Spikes rushed for 297 yards last year with six touchdowns
while Burler managed eight yards on six carries.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who set a State record by grabbing 12 passes and scoring
five touchdowns against FSU in State's wild second-half comeback,
must step up early until State develops its running game.
</P>
<P>
   He had 62 catches for 1,099 yards and 16 TDs in '97, but almost
went pro in the spring. ''It's critical we get Holt the ball,''
understated O'Cain. ''Your job as a coach is to get the ball to
people who can do something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, for his part, is eager. ''I thought about turning pro, but
decided I wasn't ready mentally,'' he said. ''I've got insurance
(for injury) and all that's behind me now. I'm ready to concentrate
on the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, State finished in the bottom half of the ACC last
season and nothing seems to point to a great leap this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a young defensive line, but potentially the best one
we've had in years,'' said Bobbie Cotten, a senior defensive end.
Strong safety Rodney Redd is the leader of a no-name secondary that
may struggle early due to inexperience. ''We've got to take an
us-against-the-world attitude,'' Redd says about playing defense.
''The way America is set up, nobody wants to see defense. They want
to see the long pass or the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just that nobody wants to see State play defense as
it allowed 20-plus points in seven games last season. The forecast
seems to be that O'Cain should be thankful he got his new five-year
deal when he did.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Tuesday: Maryland
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
