<SLUG> BC-US-WEST-STRIKE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U S WEST STRIKE TALKS RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Colo., Idaho, Iowa, Minn., Neb., N.M., N.D., Ore.,
S.D., Utah, Wash., Wyo.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A week into a strike against U S West by about 34,000
members of the Communications Workers of America, negotiations
resumed Sunday amid reports of equipment sabotage and accusations
of unfair practices by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Talks continued into the evening without any progress being
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began on Aug. 16 when the union's 3-year contract
expired and agreement could not be reached on the issues of
mandatory overtime, health care and a performance-pay plan. A
federal mediator, Jim Mahon, ordered the two sides to return to the
bargaining table on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The regional telephone company provides service to 25 million
customers in Arizona, Colorado, Idaho, Iowa, Minnesota, Montana,
Nebraska, New Mexico, North Dakota, Oregon, South Dakota, Utah,
Washington and Wyoming. About two-thirds of its 51,000 workers are
members of the Communications Workers of America. Employees in
Montana are covered by another union and have continued to work.
</P>
<P>
   The union has complained that the company is failing to supply
enough information for the negotiations. For its part, U S West
says the union is not bargaining in good faith, an accusation the
union denies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bargaining agents are more than happy to negotiate,'' said
Sharon Cordova, president of Communications Workers of America
Local 7777. ``The resolution that the company wants us to sign off
on is what's on the table, and they don't want to talk otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   A U S West spokesman, David Beigie, made a similar statement.
``As we approached the contract deadline, they had us chasing down
enormous minutiae, very little that had to do with the contract
settlement,'' Beigie said. ``We don't believe they're serious about
getting to a resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the major sticking point is the union's objection
to the proposed performance-pay plan, under which the company's
7,100 technicians would have the option to receive a bonus of up to
20 percent on top of their base salaries for meeting specific
targets, like making a certain number of repair calls in a given
period. The plan would be mandatory for employees hired after Jan.
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new concept in business, and big labor is not happy
about it,'' Beigie said. ``They may want to make an example out of
U S West, and then it's no longer about local phone service in the
Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has also proposed an 18 percent wage increase over
five years, a 20 percent pension increase, the elimination of some
fully paid health-care packages and deductions in overtime pay. The
union says the proposed concessions would hurt customer service.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Close to two dozen acts of equipment sabotage have been reported
in Oregon, Colorado and New Mexico since the strike began. Most of
these acts have involved wire and cable boxes being broken into and
wires being cut.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 reward has been offered for information about an
incident on Aug. 16, the first day of the strike, in which a large
amount of cable was cut near a hospital in Colorado Springs,
leaving hundreds of customers without service for several hours.
Later in the week, someone poured gasoline down a manhole and set a
nearby phone and cable line on fire near a hospital in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The union has denied any involvement in these incidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
