<HEADER>
A8028 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UNT-TEX     08-23 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UNT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS' HEFTIER OFFENSIVE LINE EXPECTED TO CARRY THE LOAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Jiggling, bouncing and gasping, 1,518 pounds of
starting offensive linemen plodded from end zone to end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen times.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   University of North Texas football coach Darrell Dickey greeted
his players with a stress test before two-a-days began. The stress
was the running. The test was whether the offensive linemen would
endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We survived six days in an R.V. together. We can do this,''
offensive tackle Vinny Patterson said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   From a raucous South Padre trip in a cramped recreational
vehicle to a not-so-neat pad that houses many of them, Patterson
and Co. play together and ``play'' together.
</P>
<P>
   And a strong bond between UNT's big boys might well be enough to
hold together an offense with a new scheme and an inexperienced
quarterback until a bit of confidence can be gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've addressed that topic plenty of times,'' said Phillip
Armour, a three-year starter at center. ``The key to this whole
season, we feel, is us. The whole season is going to rely on us _
the examples we set and how we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider this summer lesson No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   All 1,518 aforementioned pounds stayed in Denton to train, a few
living together in a small rented house near campus. That's a lot
of big, hot, sweaty bodies in a small space _ an emphasis on big _
and that's not even mentioning the week in July when the air
conditioning went out.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson weighs in at a healthy 304 pounds while his fellow
starters have a bit of heft, too. Try Armour (300), Shane York
(282), Laymonde Lee (294) and Brad Winn (338) on for size.
</P>
<P>
   A summer of lifting, running and eating had everybody stronger
and healthier by two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've got something we need to develop in our entire
program and in our entire athletic department,'' Dickey said, ``and
that's pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride took a beating for this ensemble during the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Armour, Patterson, Lee and Winn started that season, too.
Expectations were almost as high as now, and by midseason had been
crushed by inconsistency and injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd play a good game and then we'd come back and lay an
egg,'' Eagles offensive line coach Spencer Leftwich said. ``We'd
play a good half. We'd play a bad half.''
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistency proved contagious. UNT rushed for an average of
84.7 yards in seven losses compared to 232.5 yards in its four
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Lee attributes much of that schizophrenic output to
schizophrenic line play.
</P>
<P>
   Guys realized, and Dickey reminded them, inconsistent line play
will bury them this season when a bunch of inexperienced
quarterbacks will be leading UNT.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not blocking, then we can't run. If we're not pass
blocking, then we can't pass and especially with a young
quarterback he can't gain the confidence that he needs,'' Patterson
said. ``So we need to step it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has begun laughing again, thinking of that trip to
South Padre. He has a small laugh for such a big body, but once he
really gets going, laughter ripples through all 304 pounds of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a lot of big bodies in one place,'' Patterson
admits.
</P>
<P>
   Said Eagles wide out Jay Young: ``I was by far the lightest
person on the trip _ by about 150 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   A 10-hour drive brought them to South Padre where Patterson and
Winn were immediately enticed into a game of tug-of-war. For
competition, four linemen from the University of Texas were
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your ironic twists.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot like the season that awaits them.
</P>
<P>
   The supposedly smaller, weaker guys from UNT were going against
the supposedly bigger, stronger athletes from supposedly bigger,
better State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we get up there and start pulling and pulling,'' Patterson
said, ``and finally we beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson begins laughing again. The irony isn't lost on him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
