<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8034 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN     08-23 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLADE' CARVES OUT TOP SPOT AT WEEKEND BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wesley Snipes' ``Blade'' sliced up rivals for an
easy victory at the nation's box office with an estimated $16.8
million at 2,322 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, studio
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in five weekends that the slate had not
been topped by Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which
finished a strong second with $10.1 million at 2,671 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade,'' based on a Marvel Comics hero who is part vampire,
received a strong publicity push from New Line dating back to early
summer. Analysts credited the studio with a savvy campaign that
overcame mixed reviews and an ``R'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Line has to be relieved since they opened `Blade' during
what's traditionally the dead end of summer,'' said Arthur Rockwell
of Drake &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of Reel Source, said the film drew
surprisingly well among females and projected ``Blade,'' which
carried an estimated $45 million price tag, will reach $50 million
by the end of its domestic run.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum noted that New Line has managed to generate strong
results from late-summer releases of similar properties such as
``Mortal Kombat'' and ``Spawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They really own this period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Line distribution chief Al Shapiro said ``Blade'' topped
internal estimates by $3 million to $4 million and drew well from
all demographic groups and regions. He credited strong efforts by
Snipes and co-star Stephen Dorff to promote the movie and added
that a sequel is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a sequel weren't under consideration before, it probably is
now,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The second-place finish by ``Saving Private Ryan'' gave
DreamWorks' D-Day epic $142.7 million after 31 days, placing it
64th on the list of all-time domestic grossers after ``The Santa
Clause.''
</P>
<P>
   Its weekend-to-weekend drop was a mere 23 percent and trackers
believe its final take will top $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we'll continue to see `Saving Private Ryan' play well
for some time,'' said distribution executive Don Harris. ``People
have really responded to this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's sixth weekend of ``There's Something About
Mary'' performed the impressive feat of rising one spot in the
chart to third place with $7.6 million at 2,189 sites to pull its
total to $103.9 million after 40 days. ``This film has tremendous
repeat business,'' Rockwell noted.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy, made for a minimal $25 million, became the ninth
1998 release to cross the $100 million barrier, joining ``Deep
Impact,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``The Truman Show,'' ``Mulan,'' ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' ``Armageddon,'' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' ``Mary'' is the 175th movie to hit the milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's second weekend of ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' came
in a respectable fourth, with $6.4 million at 1,398 locations,
followed by Paramount's third weekend of ``Snake Eyes,'' with $5.1
million at 2,642 screens, and its lukewarm opening of collegiate
comedy ``Dead Man on Campus,'' with $4.7 million at 1,797 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a close seventh was Fox's fourth weekend of ``Ever
After'' with $4.6 million at 1,867 sites, followed by Sony's
opening of ``Dance With Me'' starring Vanessa Williams, with $4.5
million at 1,467 locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think Sony is a little disappointed,'' Rockwell said
of the latter entry.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell noted that studios releasing late-summer movies often
have to settle for second-tier titles such as ``Dead Man on
Campus'' or ``Dance With Me'' in order to keep a continued flow of
new titles for mutliplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's fourth weekend of ``The Parent Trap'' continued to draw
solid numbers in ninth, with $3.9 million at 2,169 theaters to go
past $51 million. Warner's second weekend of ``The Avengers''
limped home 10th with $3.6 million at 2,466 theaters as the
action-fantasy _ recipient of some of the most scathing reviews in
memory _ suffered a stunning 65 percent drop from its opening
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Avengers' is a movie that should have never been made,''
Rockwell said of the $60 million project.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros., which has seen most of its films underperform
expectations during the past two years, received more bad news this
weekend as its opening of Leslie Nielsen's spoof ``Wrongfully
Accused'' was nearly dead on arrival in 12th place with $3.4
million at 2,062 theaters. Miramax's third weekend of ``Halloween:
H20'' finished 11th with $3.5 million at 2,360 sites and has topped
$47 million.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's eighth weekend of ``Armageddon'' was 13th with $2.6
million at 1,423 theaters and reached $184.9 million. It ranks 28th
on the all-time domestic list behind ``Snow White and the Seven
Dwarfs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two new entries posted impressive results in limited release _
Gramercy's ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' Neil LaBute's
exploration of infidelity, took in $340,000 at 32 screens, and
Miramax's romantic comedy ``Next Stop: Wonderland'' grossed
$120,000 at eight theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business has reached $4.4 billion and is close to
$500 million, or 13 percent, ahead of the same period last year.
Summer business, from Memorial Day weekend to Labor Day, is on
track to hit $2.5 billion, or about 12 percent up from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's ``Titanic,'' which is responsible for much of the
1998 gains, drew $570,000 at 570 theaters in its 36th weekend to
push its overall domestic total to $599.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' face competition next
weekend from Miramax's opening ``54,'' starring Mike Myers and Neve
Campbell in a disco re-creation of the rise and fall of Studio 54,
and Warner's debut of ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' a look at the
life of the late Frankie Lyman. Bucksbaum said ``54'' has a decent
shot at topping the slate at about $10 million due to the star
power of its leads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
