<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-CHURCHES-AR     08-23 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-CHURCHES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM SERMONS ON CLINTON'S SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
 (also moved in `w' category; with CLINTON-STARR-STRATEGY,
CLINTON-GLOOM) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's acknowledgment of an inappropriate
relationship with Monica Lewinsky was a focus of sermons in
churches around the nation Sunday. Following are excerpts from
several sermons, as recorded and transcribed by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   `We Are Not Quite Sure Where It Will Take Us'
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Manzelmann, Cornwall Congregational Church,
Cornwall, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some sad and revealing confessions by the president
of these United States. Some may be glad, I suppose, but others may
well be a bit shaken by it. I don't suppose we were really very
surprised by these confessions, but had hoped against hope that it
wasn't so. And we are not quite sure where it will take us. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are texts about forgiveness which some may want to think
about. And there are texts which bring it home to us as well. Paul
says quite clearly, `We all fall short.' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And Jesus, who never wants us to be too hasty with our
judgments, said, `Do not judge so that you may not be judged
yourself. For with the judgment you make you will be judged, and
the measure you give may be the measure you get.' The words may
sting a bit. Well, he makes it come home, doesn't he? Not just
there, but here. It's endless. It makes us mad. It makes us sad. We
are tired of it. Let us get on with our life together. There are
other, more frightening things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   `Whatever the Loss, There Can Be an End to Grieving'
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hardy S. Clemons, First Baptist Church, Greenville,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The sermon was based on 1 Samuel 16:1-3, in which Samuel anoints
David to lead Israel after rejecting many other men deemed
unsuitable:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we never know the answer to our grief will take
until we've gone all the way through the valley and the shadow of
death, but for Samuel in this case, he did find an answer to the
grief that was debilitating him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we are aware that Israel is not the only nation
that has grieved over a tall, handsome, brilliant, powerful leader
and his struggles with character and sin. We know something about
that kind of national grief as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot speak for you. I can tell you about my hurt, my
anger, my sorrow, my incredulous unbelief at what we have
experienced in these last days, but I'm not here to talk about that
situation, I'm here to say that whatever the loss that occasions
grief, there can be an end to grieving. This is our hope as
believers. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If grief is ever going to end, it will end when you learn
you've got to do it badly before you do it well. I think we see
that to some extent with Mr. Clinton this week. All sorts of
reactions have come forward about what he should have said and what
he shouldn't have said. I would love to have been a consultant to
him in the writing of that speech. I believe I could have helped
him if he would have let me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also came away from that speech with a genuine respect
for a man who will get up, having looked the nation in the eye and
lied, who looked in our eyes and said, `What I did was not only
inappropriate, it was wrong.' And if he didn't do it to my
satisfaction, I don't think that's as important as that he did do
it.
</P>
<P>
   And I would invite you to apply that to whatever grief you may
be struggling with in your own experience, related to illness,
related to death, related to some other disappointment or loss. It
is very important to do it badly in order to learn to do it well.
Grief will last long enough for us to learn that.''
</P>
<P>
   `Not Judging, Acknowledging Very Painful Truth'
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nathan D. Baxter, Dean of Washington National Cathedral
</P>
<P>
   ``We may yet have legitimate suspicions about the political
motive of the endless investigations. However, we can no longer
deny that the haunting shadows we have dreaded are indeed much more
the sad reflections of a soul we would love, than the projections
of a partisan body politic which would assault it. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Jesus taught, `Judge not that ye be not judged.' And I
know all too well the truth in St. Paul's words where he says `that
all have sinned, you and I, and fallen short of God's glory.' But
this is not judging, it is acknowledging a very painful truth. I
still believe Mr. Clinton loves his country and I know that he
loves his family, and I know that he loves his God. And I know that
God loves him. But our desire to keep sin private or ignore
immorality is a judgment upon all of us. Unless we acknowledge
moral failing _ without excuse _ the soul of our nation will not
heal. I believe, more importantly, our children will be even more
confused as to whether the truest treasure of our common life as a
nation is found in the state of the economy or the character of our
moral integrity. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that there is a social agreement in human
society, among the children of Eve and Adam. A standard which is
often abused but is still the barometer of our moral life, and that
is modesty. We do expect, including in our sexual matters,
responsible behavior, self-control and respect for the
sensitivities of others. People of faith understand that this
commitment is not just moral but it is also holy _ it is blessed of
God. Responsibility, self-control and respect. This is modesty, our
moral contract as a community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract of modesty belongs in business, it belongs in
religion, it belongs in law, and in the social sector, just as it
does in politics. But we often wink at its abuse in politics
because we say politics is about the negotiating of power, and
therefore we believe that politics by nature is dirty work. But I
know some very fine politicians, and they remind me that politics
is also about stewardship. It is about the stewardship of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately what should make us respect leaders in a democracy
is not simply intelligence, or charisma, or competence with power,
ideology or any professional skill or native gift. The most
important characteristic of leadership in a democracy is the
ability to demonstrate accountable character, morally accountable
character. Ultimately, the real power of politics is moral.''
</P>
<P>
   `It Is Appropriate For Us To Come Together in Prayer'
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. Kie Bowman, Hyde Park Baptist Church, Austin, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an interesting week, a challenging time in our
country. Our president is involved in a personal scandal that could
end up disgracing the personal office of the president. This puts
us at risk as a nation. Therefore it is appropriate for us to come
together in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As de Tocqueville told us, America is great because America is
good. And he said that America will only continue to be great only
as long as it is good. Today, we need to pray for this nation. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, we lift our president before you today. As 1 Timothy
Chapter 2 tells us, we are to pray for our leaders. So Lord, I lift
the president of our country before you. Give him moral courage and
give him wisdom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
