<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK24     08-23 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's a (black and blue) guy to do? Not sit out, 'Big Cat'
offers
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andres Galarraga has this recommendation for NL
president Leonard Coleman: ''No suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Galarraga thinks he deserves for charging the mound
Saturday after Darren Dreifort hit him with a pitch for the second
time in a week, then missing with a Big Cat left hook that emptied
both benches and led to Galarraga's ejection. Coleman will begin
his inquiry into the incident today and his decision _ likely a
suspension, three games _ is expected later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   But Galarraga, who served a three-game suspension last season
after a similar incident following a Dennis Cook drilling, thinks
he shouldn't miss a single game.
</P>
<P>
   ''No suspension,'' said Galarraga, who's now been hit a
franchise-record 22 times this season. ''Twenty-two times is too
many to be too nice, too patient, not to hit anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when both Galarraga and Bobby Cox insist Dreifort
intentionally threw at the first baseman _ both last Sunday in Los
Angeles and Saturday at the Ted.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the only time I think was intentional all year,'' Cox
said of Dreifort. ''This guy, twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Why don't they hit me when I strike out four times?'' said
Galarraga. ''They only throw at me when I hit a home run...It's
right there. No question they're throwing the ball at me.''
</P>
<P>
   No question the Braves would've responded in kind, too, had
Dreifort not been wrestled to the ground by Galarraga. The pitcher
left the game with an abrasion on the right elbow. It could've been
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd like to have hit the pitcher and Dreifort didn't come
back out (to hit),'' Cox said. ''We were gonna stick him one pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga will appeal if Coleman suspends him, as the first
baseman unsuccessfully did last year. This time, he said, is
different. ''I've been hit 22 times, I don't fight anybody,''
Galarraga said. Besides, ''I don't understand them suspending the
hitter. I think the pitcher (is worse). The pitcher's starting
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the Dodgers' insistence that Galarraga crowds the
plate before stepping into the pitch and Dreifort was merely
pitching him inside, ''I'm not diving into the ball,'' he said.
''There's no question they're throwing at me intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox may speak to Coleman and ''Tell him what happened before.
When he watches the tapes, he'll see what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've never had a problem here (with hitting batters and then
retaliation),'' said the manager. ''This is different. This guy
will be dealt with. You hit the nicest guy in baseball. He's
picking on the wrong guy. He's (Galarraga) got too many supporters
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cather's rib
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cather, sent down to Class AAA Richmond July 16, is back in
Atlanta _ for medical reasons. The reliever is scheduled to have
his first right rib surgically removed this week to correct a
circulatory problem that caused pain in his pitching arm, then
tightness that temporarily prevented him from gripping a ball
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Cather, who's already undergone nerve and blood tests here
peformed by Braves orthopedist Joe Chandler, will have further
tests and then likely surgery by Dr. Joe Miller, a thoracic
vascular surgeon at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ''He should be fine by spring training,'' said Chandler, who
said ex-Brave farmhand John LeRoy and John Hudek both had surgery
for similar conditions in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler described Cather's condition as, ''After he pitches, he
gets aching pain down his arm and tightness so he can't grip
anything. After 30 minutes, it goes away.'' The problem, which has
affected Cather for about a month and bothered him once last year
in the post-season, occurs during the pitching motion.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he throws, he gets temporary suspension of his
sub-clavian artery,'' said Chandler. The first rib is likely
depressing the artery, restricting the blood flow and causing pain
and tightness. Chandler said tests have shown no nerve damage or
blood clots. If further tests confirm the rib is responsible,
surgery is likely this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cather was 2-2 with a 3.92 ERA in 36 appearances with Atlanta
before being sent down. In Richmond, he was 0-1, 5.87 in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hail to El Presidente
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Martinez, who won his 244th career game Aug. 9 in San
Francisco to surpass Juan Marichal as the winningest Latin American
pitcher in baseball history, was honored in a pre-game ceremony.
Surrounded by his family, the 43-year-old Martinez received several
gifts: An action oil portrait of himself from his teammates; a
glass etching from Braves management commerating his career
achievements; and a proclamation declaring Sunday ''Dennis Martinez
Day in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   And one more gift: A videotaped tribute from Marichal shown on
the stadium scoreboard. ''Dennis has always been a great athlete,
very dedicated to his profession,'' said Marichal, the Giants' Hall
of Famer. ''That's why he has been able to break this mark.''
</P>
<P>
   After thanking his family and teammates, Martinez offered his
primary goal with Atlanta: ''To win another World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing and healing
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have signed their top draft pick, pitcher Matt
Belisle of Austin, Tex. The 6-3, 205 right-hander, 18, is
recovering from reconstructive surgery on his left knee after
tearing his ACL in April _ the same injury suffered by Chipper
Jones in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just regular reconstruction and they said it'll come
back 100 per cent,'' said Belisle, who'll be examined by Chandler
today. The surgery was performed by Dr. James Andrews in
Birmingham. Belisle, who said his recovery has been ''ahead of
pace,'' is scheduled to report to the Braves' Instructional League
in Orlando in September, after another examination by Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't do some things _ full-out sprints, go all-out on the
mound yet,'' said Belisle, who's been throwing on the side. ''I'm
taking things slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Belisle, who had a scholarship to the University of Texas, was
actually chosen in the second round as the 52nd pick overall. The
Braves lost their first round selection after signing Galarraga as
a free agent in the off-season. At McCallum High, Belisle was 5-2,
with a 1.69 ERA and had 72 strikeouts in 51 innings. He was ranked
38th among the nation's top prospects by Baseball America.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
