<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weak spots leave Falcons plenty to trim
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves seemed sullen Sunday
afternoon, and he had reasons. There were a few disturbing signs in
Saturday night's 28-22 loss to Pittsburgh, including the play of
right offensive tackle Corey Louchiey, the play of reserve safeties
specifically, and the play of all Falcon reserves in general.
</P>
<P>
   Also, NFL rosters have to be cut to 60 players by 4 p.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves wouldn't say when the 18 (or more) cuts will be made, but
it's possible some will occur today _ when players are off, other
than for film review, stretching and lifting _ and the rest
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey, whom the team signed to a two-year, $3.5 million
contract in the offseason, was inconsistent, particularly in pass
protection, in his first action after missing two weeks with a
groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Corey played a very poor game,'' Reeves said. ``He
seemed very unsure of himself. I'm not happy with the way he
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey was not alone in catching his coach's eye. The Falcons
gave up 204 rushing yards, 179 of them in the second half when
reserves took over. Pittsburgh had runs of 62, 47 and 40 runs. Time
after time, safeties were out of position.
</P>
<P>
   Devin Bush was out with a strained knee. Second-year strong
safety Chris Bayne, a college linebacker, saw a lot of action, as
did second-year free safety Marcus Wimberly and rookie free safety
Omar Brown. Rookie free agent strong safety Brad Trout didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   None stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to work on the position of our safeties (against the
run),'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two reserve safeties will be cut. Bayne has
special-teams prowess on his side; Brown, a fourth-round draft
choice, has the fact his waiver could cost the team $234,000 if
another team claimed him.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have more difficult decisions this year than last,
meaning there's more talent. But there are enough weaknesses that
Atlanta will scour the waiver wire the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Louchiey, seventh-rounder Ephraim Salaam was Saturday,
but he was much better the previous two weeks at left tackle.
Likewise, fellow rookie tackle Jose Portilla didn't look good
Saturday on the left side, after being fairly solid the previous
two weeks on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' coaches like their potential, and both ought to
make the team, joining rookie guard-center Bob Hallen, the team's
second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the Falcons will probably keep 10 offensive linemen.
If Louchiey makes it, he and the other starters make five. Also,
10-year veteran Dave Widell will make the team as a backup
center-guard. He's also the backup deep snapper.
</P>
<P>
   Add the three rookies, and that leaves one spot.
</P>
<P>
   In some years, 14-year veteran Adam Schreiber perhaps would make
the team on deep-snapping ability alone. But Schreiber played right
guard in the fourth quarter Saturday behind Gene Williams and Scott
Adams because, if he's going to make a team that could have three
rookie linemen, a viable backup must be found.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jeremy Akers, on the practice squad last season, and
undrafted rookie tackle Michael Edwards have barely seen action in
the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, barring a trade or free agent signing, the
10th spot will come down to a decision among Adams, Schreiber and
tackle Nate Miller, who started the first two preseason games in
Louchiey's spot but is out with a nerve problem in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players who have the worst chances of surviving the
cutdown to 60 are those who have seen limited action in the
preseason, either because of injuries or coaches' decision: Rookie
DLs Henry Slay and Ben Huff, DT William Gaines (back/knee), DE
Barry Mitchell (quad/elbow), CBs Randy Fuller (ankle) and Kwame
Ellis, WRs Corey Allen (ankle/knee) and Van Johnson, rookie FB
Darren Fisk and K David Akers.
</P>
<P>
   That's 10 players. Add two safeties, offensive linemen Edwards
and Akers, and either Adams, Miller or Schreiber, and that's 15
(the last offensive lineman may not go until rosters are reduced to
53 Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said ``it's possible'' the team will keep six backs. But
if it's five, like last year, it's down to seventh-rounder Ken
Oxendine, who leads the team with 109 yards on 25 carries, or
eight-year-veteran Harold Green, who's more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Among receivers Todd Kinchen, Keith Crawford, Mercury Hayes and
Kevin Thornal, who was on the practice squad last year, and
undrafted rookie Octavus Barnes, probably just two _ and maybe only
one _ will make the team. Kinchen has been the most impressive;
Barnes has had his moments.
</P>
<P>
   Waiving either Green or Oxendine and two of these receivers
makes 18.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities, excluding surprises, include TEs Ed Smith
and Brian Saxton, CB Lenny McGill, LBs Ben Talley and Ruffin
Hamilton, and rookie QB John Dutton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
