<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE FEAR OF DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't pretty. Marcia Kramer, the host of a
television interview program on WCBS-TV, wanted to know why
Geraldine Ferraro, a Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate, was
so assiduously avoiding debates with her primary opponents, Charles
Schumer and Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kramer is the reporter who elicited the famous ``did not
inhale'' quote from Bill Clinton. When she gets onto something, she
is relentless.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro is nothing if not thin-skinned. She began her
campaign back in January by saying she wouldn't debate at all
unless her rivals signed a written pledge not to engage in personal
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   That was widely seen as absurd and Ms. Ferraro backed off.
Still, there have been no televised debates so far and only two are
planned. Both are scheduled for the final Sunday of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for any debate among the three candidates
to be more openly hostile than the encounter that aired Sunday
between Ms. Kramer and Ms. Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kramer was not a disinterested party. She had hoped to land
a debate for her program, ``Sunday Edition.'' That was fine with
Schumer and Green, but Ms. Ferraro declined. So ``Sunday Edition,''
taped on Thursday, had separate interviews with the three
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro's interview was first and it was clear almost
immediately that both the host and the guest were angry. Ms. Kramer
repeatedly accused the candidate of ducking debates and Ms. Ferraro
insisted that she had not.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, an exasperated Ms. Ferraro said: ``Marcia, I'm
surprised at you. I really am surprised.'' She accused Ms. Kramer
of being ``unprofessional.'' And during a commercial break, she
added the caustic comment: ``I was curious which campaign you are
working for.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can decide who came off better in the televised
exchange. But on the issue of debates, Ms. Kramer had a point.
Nearly everyone outside the Ferraro campaign agrees that Ms.
Ferraro is the reason there has been no televised debate so far,
and only two public forums at which all three candidates appeared
together.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Ms. Ferraro has been the cloistered
candidate in this important race, the candidate who behaves as
though she has something to hide. It's as if she were burdened by
the fear that some terrible misfortune would occur if she stepped
before the television cameras and joined in the rough and tumble of
a genuine public debate with Schumer and Green.
</P>
<P>
   As she is the front-runner and the best-known candidate, Ms.
Ferraro may be be right. She might come off poorly by comparison.
She could make a devastating gaffe. From a purely political
perspective, she may be doing the right thing. But for voters
looking for the best alternative to Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a
candidate-in-hiding can only be a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro adamantly insists that she is not hiding. Her
campaign spokesman, Stephen Gaskill, said: ``She's done 50 public
events in July and 43 thus far in August. That's hardly hiding from
the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday, Ms. Ferraro said she believes an
incorrect impression is being created by press coverage that is
more favorable to her opponents. When asked why the press would be
fairer to Schumer or Green, she replied, ``Probably because I'm the
front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Green have been chasing Ms. Ferraro since she
announced her candidacy in January. Schumer, and especially Green,
who has raised relatively little money, have been anxious to
debate. Invitations have poured in from around the state. But Ms.
Ferraro's response, with very few exceptions, has been simple and
unambiguous _ no.
</P>
<P>
   The polls have consistently shown Ms. Ferraro to be well ahead,
although there have been indications recently that her lead is
weakening. Her strategy, however, is not changing.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Green have both said they would be willing to
participate in additional debates between now and the final Sunday
before the election. Ms. Ferraro said she would have no part of
that. ``No,'' she said. ``I won't be bullied into this, and that's
what I think the press is doing.'' (BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
