<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' JOHNSON BELIEVES HE HAS MASTERED END GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ ``You know I'm slow, right?'' Keyshawn Johnson
asked, then chuckled before getting into his Ferrari on Sunday.
``I'm so slow, no one's getting me the ball. Can't outrun
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   So he sped off, for emphasis, laughing all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson likes to think of himself as the Jets' most important
receiver. He always has, and he still does. And despite the Jets'
acquisition of the redoubtable Curtis Martin at running back,
quarterback Glenn Foley says he will be looking for Johnson when he
throws the ball downfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson who has shown up during the Jets' exhibition season
is quite different from the player they made the league's overall
No. 1 draft pick in 1996. This is a more svelte, yet more powerful,
player _ and someone who understands the position of wide receiver
better. His routes have become disciplined. Imagine a 6-foot-3-inch
210-pounder who knows where he is going, while the smaller and
lighter cornerbacks do not.
</P>
<P>
   That growth translated into a sterling game against the Giants
last Thursday: 6 catches for 99 yards. On two of the catches, he
embarrassed the Giants' defenders, catching one ball 6 yards away
from cornerback Phillippi Sparks, and another so far in the clear
it was difficult to tell which Giants were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to published quotes from some Giants defenders that he
had boasted during the game of being a gang member, Johnson said:
``Maybe it was because we got 400 yards of offense against them
that they were complaining. Maybe their great players were upset.
Maybe they said things to me, too, but you didn't hear me moaning
about things they said. Maybe they spoke to me first.''
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson said Sunday that he was not a gang member.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition season, which ends Friday night at Chicago, will
lead Johnson into a more important, if symbolic, gauge of where he
is. Johnson and the Jets open the regular season at San Francisco.
And that means facing Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been playing videotapes of Rice and other great
receivers for months, since the Jets' last regular-season game
against Detroit, when they missed the playoffs as Johnson failed to
hold on to a pair of passes in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that game I said to myself, `I'll never let that happen
to me again,''' Johnson said. ``I can be a special player in this
league. This is only my second year in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he really knows that this is going to be his third season.
But he explains: ``In my rookie year, I was in the minor leagues.
Now I'm in the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   His rookie season was the 1-15 debacle that, in a sense, helped
turn the franchise around. For it was then that the owner, Leon
Hess, decided enough was enough, and hired Bill Parcells as the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells repeated Sunday that the outspoken and often
controversial Johnson gives him no trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to do well,'' Parcells said. ``Think he's hard? He's
one of the easiest guys I've got. The more he knows, the more he
knows what he doesn't know.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Johnson said Sunday that what he did not know had to do with
routes. As a rookie, as he had through his college career, Johnson
was able to outmuscle the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to be a better receiver,'' he said. ``I already was a
good football player.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes showed him how to come back to the ball, for instance,
or ``not making every route look the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson even does some coaching himself these days. He put on a
headset against the Giants in the fourth period, when he was long
out of the game, to communicate with the offensive coordinator,
Charlie Weis. Johnson also makes suggestions on altering the
alignments so he can take advantage of defenders.
</P>
<P>
   He also spent hours in the off season working on a big problem:
keeping his feet inbounds on sideline catches. He hired a personal
trainer who drilled him on footwork and threw ball after ball to
him as Johnson ran toward the sideline. He had to reach for the
ball while keeping his feet inbounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm becoming a receiver rather than a baller,'' said Johnson,
who has caught 133 passes and has 13 touchdowns in his two seasons.
``A baller is a guy who's got enough athletic ability to get to the
ball. But now I'm a receiver.''
</P>
</TEXT>
