u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-EXCLUSIVE-INSURANCE     08-23 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EXCLUSIVE-INSURANCE-FRAUD-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURER TAKES ON DOCTORS AND LAWYERS OVER ALLEGED FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Tenn., Fla., Pa.)   (Eds.: This story has been added to the New York Times A1 reefer
box; the story has also moved in `f' category)  
(EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(jw) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As automobile accidents go, it was not much: Two teen-agers
driving home from school in Southern California were bumped from
behind. They later told investigators that they felt a little pain
in their backs and necks.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the crash they went first not to a doctor but to a
lawyer. The lawyer sent them to a clinic and the bills started to
mount up. After two months the bills for one boy, 19, came to
$3,740. For his friend, 14, the cost was $4,090.
</P>
<P>
   As Allstate, the insurance company that covered the boys'
accident, sees it, the bills _ including one for $250 for an
initial exam that the boys said took a few minutes _ were grossly
inflated.
</P>
<P>
   The case is but one that Allstate plans to cite on Monday, when
it intends to notify about a dozen Southern California doctors and
chiropractors and their assistants that they are being sued for $25
million for repeatedly overbilling or billing for services they
never provided, in hundreds of cases over the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Cases like the one involving the two teenagers, insurance
industry executives say, are part of a widespread pattern of fraud
across the United States. The Insurance Research Council, an
industry organization in Illinois, says that nearly 40 percent of
the claims for auto accident injuries now involve fraud. And a
fortune is at stake. Last year alone, insurers received claims for
more than $42 billion for auto-accident injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While insurance fraud is a problem as old as insurance itself,
industry experts see a disturbing variation on the theme: Rather
than premeditated criminal activity involving supposed accident
victims, insurers say some doctors and clinics are capitalizing on
real accidents and real injuries by seeking reimbursement for
procedures not required and never performed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Insurance Research Council says 90 percent of the
offenses are not planned but are ``opportunistic fraud'' in which
professionals, and sometimes patients, seize a chance to profit
with little apparent likelihood of being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Allstate, the country's second-largest auto insurer, is
starting to go after doctors and clinics across the country where
they are finding evidence of such overbilling.
</P>
<P>
   The California suits, which were filed under seal two months ago
as required by that state's law and will be served to the parties
Monday, are the first of their kind by a major auto insurer. But
they are not the last. Edward Moran, the chief of investigations
for Allstate, said the company was developing cases against other
doctors and clinics in San Francisco; Chicago; Memphis, Tenn.;
Miami; Philadelphia and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want doctors to know there is a price to pay for committing
insurance fraud,'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees about the magnitude of the problem. Leaders
of the American Medical Association and the Association of Trial
Lawyers of America, the leading organization of personal injury
lawyers, say they believe the insurance industry is vastly
overstating the extent of the fraud. They say they suspect that
charges of fraud are a cynical tactic by insurers to limit the
reimbursements they pay out.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is not simply a figment of the insurance
industry's imagination. In recent years there have been some
stunning cases of respected hospital and health maintenance
organization officials being charged by government investors with
overbilling for Medicare and Medicaid services.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, however, auto insurers have not systematically
attacked the problem. In the past, they tried to deny suspicious
claims _ which they continue to do _ or tried to discount them when
they were negotiating settlements. But the problem has only grown
worse, the insurers say.
</P>
<P>
   The latest suits are an extension of earlier efforts by
Allstate, by State Farm, the largest auto insurer, and by some of
their competitors to file civil suits and help build criminal cases
against gangs around the country that make a business of staging
fake accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, organizers, known as cappers, recruit people to
drive into the paths of unsuspecting motorists and cause crashes.
Then, often working through corrupt lawyers and doctors, the
recruits, often three or four in a single car, begin building up
fake medical bills for submission to insurers.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Allstate sued 45 doctors, lawyers, and
fake-accident organizers in Los Angeles for $107 million in the
largest suit ever filed in connection with fake auto accidents.
State Farm has filed several suits against fake-accident rings and
is at work on several more.
</P>
<P>
   The latest suits in Southern California are different. The
accidents, as far as the insurers know, were real. And, also as far
as they can tell, all the fraud took place in clinics where, to
increase their earnings, all the doctors and chiropractors had to
do was indicate on insurance forms that they had performed costly
procedures when, in fact, they had done little or no work.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say that in some of the overbilling, patients are
silent partners in fraud with their doctors, often encouraged by
personal injury lawyers. The practice of settling auto insurance
claims, the insurers say, is generally to pay two or three times
the amount of medical bills for pain and suffering. So the more
doctors charge, the more a patient and his lawyer are likely to
get.
</P>
<P>
   For example, with medical bills of $2,000 an insurer might pay a
settlement of $6,000; with bills of $4,000, the settlement can
often be $12,000. (The incentive for fraudulently building up
claims like this is reduced or eliminated by some no-fault plans
that provide payment for pain and suffering only for catastrophic
injuries.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many patients may be unaware that their treatment is being
padded. They often pay little attention to their bills, seldom
bothering to check billing codes, descriptions of treatments and
costs, even if they are decipherable, because they know the
insurance company is paying. And often, when lawyers are involved,
doctors' bills go not to the patient but to the lawyer for
forwarding to the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the nature of the treatment for some of the most
common auto accident injuries, whiplash and other strains and
sprains, is not altogether unpleasant. So it may be difficult for a
patient to protest if he is offered 25 sessions of massage,
ultra-sound and alternating hot and cold packs, when a dozen might
suffice. To further complicate matters, professionals may truly
differ on how many such therapy sessions are enough.
</P>
<P>
   In its suits against doctors, Allstate says it is not trying to
dictate treatment. ``We're not challenging doctors' individual
decisions,'' Moran said. ``We're challenging a pattern of billing
at the highest possible level in order to inflate claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Randolph Smoak, chairman of the AMA's board of trustees,
said that while insurers may challenge a doctor's choice of billing
codes, he believes there is little deliberate abuse. Rather than
taking doctors to court, as Allstate is doing, he said, the first
step should be a discussion to resolve billing differences.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Kass, an insurance fraud specialist in the Los Angeles
law firm of Manning, Marder &AMP; Wolfe working for Allstate, said the
insurer was not moving against doctors suspected of overbilling in
a few instances, but against ``personal injury mills treating
hundreds and hundreds of people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Allstate had not tried to negotiate with the doctors it
was suing or advised them of the legal action out of concern that
incriminating evidence might be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors and lawyers feel besieged. ``What the insurance
companies are doing is attacking the only source of help these
injured people have, the doctors who treat them and the lawyers who
represent them,'' said Mark Mandell, the president of the
Association of Trial Lawyers of America.
</P>
<P>
   In the cases now being developed by Allstate, the insurer is not
trying to prosecute those involved in the accidents, Kass said.
Trying to establish whether patients were aware of fraud is
difficult, he said. But the doctors, he said, lay down a trail of
evidence by submitting falsified bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
