<HEADER>
A8068 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SHAKEUP-1STLD-     08-23 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SHAKEUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN DISMISSES ECONOMIC REFORMERS, REINSTATES CHERNOMYRDIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for additions and refinements; bottom third is new)  (See also: RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-CHERNOMYRDIN, RUSSIA-REACT) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On Sunday, President Boris Yeltsin, in an anxious bid
to shore up his political support, dismissed his new team of
economic reformers and reinstated Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's surprise decision came just five months after he
derided Chernomyrdin as a spent force and cast him out of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt action raised fresh doubts about the Kremlin's
commitment to tough economic reforms and posed unsettling questions
about Yeltsin's ability to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has hired and dismissed top aides so often that
government shake-ups have become a common feature of Russia's
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But his decision to substitute the stolid Chernomyrdin for the
reform-minded Sergei Kiriyenko was a stunning one _ even for the
mercurial president.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin offered no public explanation Sunday night for his
decision to dismiss Kiriyenko and the entire Cabinet and name
Chernomyrdin acting prime minister. The move was disclosed in a
terse statement on the evening television news, just after the
reports on the day's sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   To many commentators, it appeared that the president had decided
that his political survival was more important than plowing ahead
with an aggressive program of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   While the 60-year-old Chernomyrdin is seen by most of the
Russian public as uninspiring, he is a consensus figure for much of
the power elite.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial oligarchy sees Chernomyrdin as a far more
sympathetic and pliable leader than the brainy Kiriyenko. The
Russian press has featured reports that Boris Berezovsky, the
tycoon and media mogul, was plotting to restore Chernomyrdin to
power.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also appears to be calculating that the appointment of
Chernomyrdin will deflate the repeated calls in the
Communist-dominated parliament for his resignation. As the former
head of the Soviet gas industry, Chernomyrdin has also maintained
good relations with the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The same factors that make Chernomyrdin an acceptable leader for
financiers and Communists, however, make him a questionable choice
to extract Russia from its economic quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   In his first five years as prime minister, Chernomyrdin presided
over Russia's unsteady march toward capitalism. But he also
tolerated much of the cronyism and many of the half-measures that
have helped bring Russia to its current impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin acknowledged as much in March when told the nation that
he was dismissing Chernomyrdin because a new, young team was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is whether the return of a longtime
politician like Chernomyrdin would restore a sense of political
stability or whether it would stoke feelings that Yeltsin was
grasping at straws in his efforts to cope with the escalating
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian banks on the brink of insolvency and the ruble in
decline, Russia faces a number of crucial policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It must decide on a way to restructure its short-term debt. It
must determine how many politically connected banks it can afford
to bail out. It must also find a way to reassure anxious foreign
investors, who have been fleeing in droves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin sought Sunday night to reassure the Clinton
administration that the shake-up was not a economic retreat.
Chernomyrdin and Kiriyenko spoke separately Sunday night by
telephone with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said the Russian officials ``put a strong
emphasis on continuing the march.'' But he acknowledged that
neither official provided any specifics or explained the reason for
Yeltsin's move.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian politicians, however, were far less charitable.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Lukin, a leading member of the opposition Yabloko
Party, said Yeltsin's decision was evidence of ``profound confusion
and uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, the suddenness of Sunday night's move added a
further element of instability. The last time Yeltsin dismissed his
Cabinet, he ended up reappointing most of his top aides to
government posts. But Sunday night's statement did not make clear
which Kremlin officials would be reappointed and which would be
sacked.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Boris Fyodorov, a top Kremlin aide and the nation's
senior tax collector, remained unclear. Fyodorov's appointment was
hailed by Western officials in the hope that Russia might finally
be cracking down on tax delinquents and putting an end to insider
deals.
</P>
<P>
   But Fyodorov does not have the best of relations with
Chernomyrdin. He mocked Chernomyrdin as a do-nothing official
during Chernomyrdin's first term as prime minister. Western
investors said they had been assured that Fyodorov would keep his
job for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is a matter of hours, days or weeks is not clear,''
a leading investment banker said.
</P>
<P>
   As a technical matter, Chernomyrdin was named acting prime
minister and will have to be confirmed by parliament for his
appointment to become permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian constitution, Yeltsin has two weeks to
nominate a permanent prime minister. If the parliament rejects
Yeltsin's choice three times, the president has the right to
dissolve the legislature and call for new parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin is unlikely to face the bruising confirmation
battle that Kiriyenko endured this spring. Gennadi Zyuganov, the
Communist leader, was temperate in his criticism of Yeltsin's
shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an upside down decision,'' Zyuganov said. ``The
president had another option: first hold consultations with members
of the parliament, determine priorities in this issue and then
act.''
</P>
<P>
   With presidential elections scheduled for the year 2000, the
Communist opposition is likely to use the shake-up as an
opportunity to discredit the Yeltsin government and to lobby for a
power-sharing arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Chernomyrdin wins easy confirmation, there was a
surrealistic quality about his selection Sunday. For weeks this
spring, the nation's business was brought to halt as Yeltsin argued
that the government needed new people and new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Yeltsin has come full circle, forfeiting much of his
credibility in the process. Nikolai Ryzhkov, the leader of a
left-wing faction in the parliament, said that the president's move
was completely illogical.
</P>
<P>
   American policymakers, for their part, sought to put the best
face on Sunday's events. But extracting promises from Yeltsin that
the economic reform will continue will be a pressing task when
President Clinton arrives in Moscow next week for a summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko, for his part, seemed resigned to his fate. Just five
months ago, the 36-year-old former energy minister and banker was
plucked from relative obscurity and hailed by Yeltsin as Russia's
best hope to usher in a new era of reform. In his brief tenure, he
lobbied hard for politically unpopular reforms and, like other
reformers before him, emerged as the scapegoat for all of Russia's
economic ills.
</P>
<P>
   After he learned of Yeltsin's decision, Kiriyenko called Gore to
say goodbye and to try to reassure the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sunday evening, he and Boris Nemtsov, another pro-reform
member of the dismissed government, strolled out of their offices
in the White House, the Yeltsin government's headquarters, to talk
with striking coal miners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing concrete was discussed,'' one miner later told the
press. ``They just came down to talk, for a regular chat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
