u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-HILLIARD-N     08-23 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-HILLIARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLIARD GIVING GIANTS A REASON TO SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jason Sehorn's injury last week was a lightning
strike to the heart of the team. But just as one young star was
being carted from the stage, another was fortuitously stepping into
the void.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ike Hilliard was the player whose absence devastated
the Giants. Thursday, it was not lost on some Giants that it was
Hilliard who brought the Giants back to life after the depression
of the opening kickoff, when Sehorn's knee ligaments were torn.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the first half, Hilliard made it evident why he is
special _ for what he sees and what he makes others see.
</P>
<P>
   The first moment came early, a simple but significant adjustment
Hilliard made at the line of scrimmage. On a third down, the Jets
seemed poised to blitz one of their safeties, and with the kind of
nonverbal communication so essential between quarterback and
receiver, both Hilliard and Giants quarterback Danny Kanell knew
what they had to do.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard had to break off his intended pattern and slant across
the middle. Kanell had to hold the ball long enough for Hilliard to
get across the field, even though it would mean taking a hit an
instant after releasing the football.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard found the gap in the defense; Kanell released the ball
and went down in a heap. Hilliard shielded the football from the
defender, Ray Mickens, who was arriving a bit late. A 12-yard gain
led to a field goal four plays later.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a guy like Ike,'' Kanell said later, ``I can throw the
football to a spot, and you know he's going to get to that spot
first. A risky play becomes a dependable play. A play like that
picks everybody up. We all saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard's second defining moment came immediately afterward.
What the rest of the team saw next, as Kanell said, was infectious
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the Ike Hilliard I know come to the sidelines,'' Giants
Coach Jim Fassel said. ``He came over with his eyes wide and with a
smile you could see from across the field. He's a spark. I've often
thought he could be the personality on offense for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard had seven receptions for 74 yards in Thursday's game.
He also drew a pass interference penalty near the goal line in the
first quarter when Aaron Glenn, the Jets' top cornerback, knocked
him down trying to keep him from catching a pass along the right
sideline. That penalty set up a 1-yard touchdown run by Tiki
Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively for the Giants, the first quarter was Hilliard's
time to shine. On the team's first possession, Hilliard caught
three passes from Kanell. The first of those was another
quick-hitting pattern over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ike caught the pass and split four guys coming in on him,''
Fassel said. ``He grabbed it and advanced it up the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsaid in that brief evaluation was that Hilliard withstood a
jarring, direct hit from two Jets in what is a very crowded and
potentially dangerous part of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard injured his neck catching a downfield pass over the
middle 11 months ago. He had season-ending surgery, and for months,
Hilliard has weathered the questions about how he would hold up to
contact again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was getting tired of talking about it,'' Fassel
said.
</P>
<P>
   That line of questioning should lessen now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Hilliard said after Thursday's game when that
sentiment was related to him. ``I will appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard, 22, is a playful man of few words. He is popular with
his teammates, and his presence has lifted the offense. With
Hilliard at flanker, game-breaking plays seem possible again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing football,'' Hilliard said. ``But sure, it
feels good to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashing a smile, Hilliard added: ``But hey, I told you all
along that I'd be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it's good news that the Giants sorely need.
Hilliard's return on Thursday came not a minute too soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
