<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-AARON-LADN     08-23 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-AARON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD 755 HOMERS MIGHT BE OUT OF REACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The greatest sluggers in baseball are focused on
Roger Maris at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Off in the distance, barely visible, is a lithe, yet powerful
figure with a record even more profound than Maris' single-season
home run mark of 61. And while not even Mark McGwire can dream of
that record, one day someone will have his sights set on this man,
and the nation will be riveted as it was a quarter century ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Henry Aaron did the impossible: He caught and then
passed Babe Ruth to become the most prolific home run hitter in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's 755 home runs, the last of which was hit in 1976, is
perhaps American sports' greatest statistical monument and a record
that some believe will never be broken given the evolution of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The math is simple.
</P>
<P>
   If 28-year-old Ken Griffey Jr. averages roughly 35 home runs
over the next 12 years, he'll catch Aaron. Juan Gonzalez, also 28,
would have to average closer to 40 over the same period, and
McGwire, 34, would need an average of about 55 over six years.
Sounds plausible, right? Well, plausible and realistic are entirely
different.
</P>
<P>
   Stats, Inc.'s ``Baseball Scoreboard'' gave Griffey (336 homers)
only a 27 percent chance of catching Aaron after last season,
although that figure could exceed 30 percent after this year.
McGwire (434) was given a 15 percent chance, Gonzalez (289) 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's one of the hardest records to break,'' said Don
Zminda, vice president of publications for Stats. ``So many things
have to go right. I mean, so few great players in history have not
missed a significant amount of time because of injury or had one or
two bad years that threw them off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just never happened to Aaron.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, now 64 and an executive with the Atlanta Braves, was a
star from the start, but no one would've imagined early in his
career that he might challenge Ruth. As former teammate and
broadcaster Ernie Johnson said, ``He was a skinny line-drive
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he wasn't particularly large during his playing days:
6-foot, 180 pounds. He didn't hit tape-measure home runs. Heck, he
never even hit 50 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Aaron would have been given only a 5 percent chance
of reaching 756 homers at Griffey's age, according to Stats'
formula, which was devised by Bill James and is based on how far
the player is from a particular goal, how quickly he's getting
there and how much time he has left.
</P>
<P>
   How'd Aaron get to 755? He averaged 38.3 his next 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistency, that was the name of the game,'' said Aaron, who
doesn't dwell on the record and seems almost uncomfortable talking
about it. ``I think I'm most proud of that aspect, the consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how did I do it? Staying focused on what I had to do. Once
a player loses that, no matter how much ability he has, he won't be
able to accomplish anything at this level. It's why players seem to
have some good years and some bad years, because they read
yesterday's news instead of focusing on today.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron and several others suggested that the times helped him
keep that focus. In his day, Aaron and his peers didn't make
millions of dollars or enjoy the security of multiyear contracts. A
bad year could result in a pay cut they couldn't afford, the
prospect of which kept their minds in the game.
</P>
<P>
   There are players today like Paul Molitor, the 41-year-old
designated hitter for the Minnesota Twins who appears to be as
motivated by his place in baseball history as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, several baseball people have asked the same
question: How many active players will have the incentive to play
the years _ Aaron played 23 _ necessary to challenge the sport's
career records?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past generations of ballplayers, today's stars can decide
they no longer want to spend time away from their families without
even considering the financial implications. In other words,
whether a player challenges Aaron's record might come down to will.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really true,'' Zminda said. ``It probably helped Aaron
that he was underpaid compared to now. It encouraged him to keep
playing. Griffey might decide at 35 or so that he has enough money
and not play any more.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until his mid-30s that Aaron's name was first linked
to Ruth's.
</P>
<P>
   When players typically begin a serious decline in production,
Aaron continued to find the fences. After he turned 36, he hit 201
homers _ 159 between 36 and 39, an average of 40 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he remained in good condition, those unusually strong
wrists never failed him, he had the advantage of playing in
homer-friendly Atlanta (although he played his first 12 seasons in
cavernous Milwaukee) and he avoided injuries. Again, however, he
said it came down to focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like drafting a pure quarterback or trying to
make a quarterback. Which do you want?'' Aaron said. ``I was a pure
hitter, I could always hit. That was a big part of it....
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more than ability, though. It comes back to focus. You
have to be able to throw out what you did yesterday and do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Griffey has the right makeup to challenge Aaron.
One, he seems to love the game, which could give him the longevity
he would need. And, two, as his boss, Seattle Mariners manager Lou
Piniella, has said, he has that even temperament and unwavering
confidence that lends itself to consistency.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Aaron was. It's impossible to tell from his demeanor
whether he went 4 for 4 or 0 for 4 on a given day, said former
teammate Johnson, who described Aaron as perpetually ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   His temperament certainly showed as he approached Ruth. When it
became clear that he had a shot at the record, Aaron received
thousands of hate-filled, racist letters and many death threats
from those who couldn't accept the fact an African-American was
about to eclipse the great _ and white _ Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it affected Aaron. However, for the main part, the
anger and fear for his family boiled inside him; he didn't show it
much on the outside, according to those around him. And he
certainly didn't let it affect his play. In the face of it all, the
homers kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever challenges Aaron's record one day likely will have to
play in a good hitter's park, he'll have to avoid injuries, he'll
have to remain motivated and he'll have to keep that focus. But he
!ital!won't!off! have to live the nightmare Aaron lived.
</P>
<P>
   Even now he dismisses it, saying, ``It didn't make me feel one
way or the other. There are just a lot of angry people in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of person who will hit 756 home runs: strong
inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of me just going out and performing,'' he
said, trying to explain how he managed to remain productive while
shrouded in a fog of bigotry. ``All the time people were writing
those letters and all that stuff, it was instilled in my brain that
I was a baseball player. I was always in control of my temper. I
had to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a lot of things in my career. I had a son who
died at only 3 days old. I went through a divorce later in my
career. And at the height of the Babe Ruth chase, I was able to do
what I had to do. It was my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Maris had some problems. People just have different
makeups. Why is Michael Jordan the way he is? He's not that much
better than a lot of other players. He just stays focused because
he knows what he wants. It was the same with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' Gary Sheffield says a player has a better chance to
catch Aaron if he's not playing for a contender. ``On a good team,
you're always playing in close games with the game on the line,''
he explained. ``On a bad team, the opposing pitcher knows even if
you homer, it's only one run. The year I hit 42 (1996), we weren't
very good. After my first 15 homers, I had 18 RBIs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many knowledgeable people believe Aaron's record will stand
forever. Frank Robinson, No. 4 on the all-time list with 586
homers, went so far as to tell the Washington Post recently, ``I
don't see anyone coming close to Aaron.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who disagree? Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Said the home run king: ``Anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He should know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
