u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-STRATEG     08-23 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-STRATEGY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORN BETWEEN LAWYERS AND AIDES, CLINTON CHOSE STRATEGY OF DENIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``allegations'' to ``accusations'' in grafs 1 and 4
of 1st take and graf 2 of 2nd take; changes ``Ms.'' to ``Miss'' in
graf 4 of 2nd take) (See also CLINTON-GLOOM, CLINTON-CHURCHES) 
(mk) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Jan. 21, the morning the accusations about
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky first
appeared in the news media, the political consultant Dick Morris
was in New York City when his pager went off. The call, Morris said
in an interview, was from the president.
</P>
<P>
   That morning, there had been heated deliberations between
lawyers in the office of the White House counsel, Charles Ruff, and
the White House communications and political team, according to
several current and former White House aides interviewed in the
past week.
</P>
<P>
   A White House adviser said the lawyers wanted the president to
say very little and insisted that the word ``sexual'' not appear in
Clinton's first official statement about Ms. Lewinsky, which was
due to be released by Mike McCurry, the White House press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Several political and communications advisers, who had weathered
previous accusations involving Clinton, were pressing for as much
early candor as possible, the ``more rather than less approach,''
as one of them labeled it in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently torn himself over the best approach, the president
reached out once again to Morris, the political consultant who had
helped orchestrate his comeback from the brink of other disasters,
including the 1994 election that delivered the House to the
Republicans. Morris, whose position as a Clinton insider had been
shattered by his own sexual misconduct in 1996, said he was not
surprised to get the call.
</P>
<P>
   The president told Morris that he had ``slipped up'' with Ms.
Lewinsky but that the charges against him were untrue, Morris said.
The adviser offered to take a poll to see what the attitude of the
voters would be if the president admitted an affair with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Before the poll results were back, Clinton proceeded shakily
through a first day of questions, with a vague statement (the
president ``never had any improper relationship'' with Ms.
Lewinsky), and an oddly present-tense response in a PBS interview
(``There is no sexual relationship _ that is accurate.''). In the
following days, backed in part, Morris said, by his polling, the
denials only became more forceful.
</P>
<P>
   All last week, in the wake of the president's belated admission
that he ``did have a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that was not
appropriate,'' there has been a barrage of second-guessing about
decisions that were made last January. Should the president have
been more truthful, earlier? Why did he mislead the public for
seven months? Why was he not more apologetic? Why did he use
lawyerly phrases such as ``legally accurate''?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to many of these questions rest in the tension
between the president's political and legal interests and, of
course, inside himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matrix of political and legal considerations in these
cases is beguiling. You can't ever get it just right,'' said
Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who has defended many political
figures and who attended a White House meeting of Democratic
operatives on Wednesday. ``The adversary function of a legal case
rests on saying nothing and making people prove a case. The
political system functions by running at the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   After the PBS interview, with Jim Lehrer, some members of the
political team reacted with horror. One White House adviser said
that Clinton sounded like a zombie programmed by lawyers. Harry
Thomason, the Hollywood producer who had helped orchestrate some of
Clinton's most successful political moments, including his
acceptance speech at the 1992 Democratic convention, was so worried
that he called Hillary Rodham Clinton, who encouraged him to come
to Washington, reported an account in The New Yorker. He arrived
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Morris said, he had reported his polling results back
to the president. The public would forgive admission of a sexual
dalliance, but not that the president had been untruthful about it
in his sworn deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones case, which has since been dismissed, was one of two
highly worrisome legal matters closing in on the president back in
January. The other was the continuing investigation by the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. Anything the president said
could have serious ramifications on both. The lawyers were also
concerned that if the president provided different versions of the
story, he would be vulnerable to a perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   But the political situation seemed equally precarious. As there
were last week, there were predictions in the early days that the
president would be forced to resign or face impeachment. The
political advisers wanted the president to communicate effectively
with the public.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle, there was a president who, according to his
speech last Monday, was motivated ``by a desire to protect myself
from the embarrassment of my own conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Lehrer interview on Jan. 21, there was a vocal
clash between the political and communications team and the lawyers
in a confrontation that one participant recalls ``bordered on
getting violent.'' A group of aides then confronted Clinton's lead
outside lawyer, David Kendall of Williams &AMP; Connolly, to complain
about the lack of information coming from the lawyers. According to
one aide, Kendall, who did not return a call to comment for this
article, responded sharply to criticisms that he was not
sufficiently sensitive to the president's political needs by saying
that the aides did not understand the obligations of being a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The political advisers, including Rahm Emanuel and Paul Begala,
said a White House adviser sought assurances from the lawyers that
the president's denial of a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
did not rely on an exclusion for oral sex. Last week there was ``an
intense feeling of personal betrayal,'' said a former White House
aide. Several White House aides and advisers said they were
uncertain whether the lawyers knew the assurances were disingenuous
at the time they were given.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Jan. 23, the lawyers, joined by Mickey Kantor, a
longtime adviser and friend of the president and Mrs. Clinton, were
insisting on a wall of silence. McCurry was asked whether the
president had told the full story of his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky to his advisers. ``If, by advisers, if that includes his
attorneys, he may have,'' McCurry responded. ``But I can't answer
that, because he has not with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Also that Friday, the president reassured his Cabinet, who
gathered at the White House to discuss the upcoming State of the
Union Address, that he was innocent of accusations of having sex
with an intern and telling her to lie about it. ``I'm going to be
fine, and you will be, too,'' he told them. After the Cabinet
meeting, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and three other
Cabinet secretaries met with reporters in a show of support for
Clinton. By this time, several top political advisers had also been
personally assured by the president that the accusations were
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Over that weekend there was a barrage of new reports about Ms.
Lewinsky. Clinton conferred with Thomason and watched the Super
Bowl with the Rev. Jesse Jackson. His political situation seemed to
be worsening.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, with help from Thomason, who was watching a live
video feed from another room in the White House, Clinton had
practiced an emphatic, public denial. Wagging his finger and with
his wife standing by his side, Clinton told 200 people gathered in
the Roosevelt Room for a child-care policy meeting, ``I want you to
listen to me, I'm going to say this again. I did not have sexual
relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Also present in the Roosevelt Room that day was Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., who found the president's denial reassuring
then, but last week said her faith in the president's credibility
had been ``badly shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was misleading, a strong and public categorical
denial from the president seemed to bolster both his legal and
political standing back in January. It seemed to give the Jones
lawyers and Starr little to work with. (Ms. Lewinsky was not yet
cooperating with prosecutors and in the Jones case she, too, had
filed an affidavit denying a sexual relationship). His denial also
energized Clinton's defenders, including his wife, who appeared on
the NBC program ``Today'' to defend him.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' poll also made it clear the voters, too, were most
comfortable with a denial, though he was soon excluded from the
group advising the president. A former White House aide said that
when word of Morris' possible reappearance reached Begala, he
threatened to quit if Morris was brought back. Begala declined
comment, while Morris said ``the lawyers felt the president should
not talk to me anymore because our conversations were not
privileged.'' Morris was called before Starr's grand jury last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months of denials, supplemented by a quasi-apology, have
hurt the president legally and politically, several former aides
said, with one saying Clinton turned an embarrassment into a
possibly impeachable offense. But another adviser stressed that the
president bought valuable time, months in which the White House has
denounced Starr and driven up his public disapproval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Back in January, the president's public denials about Ms.
Lewinsky were quickly followed by a successful State of the Union
address, which helped remind the voters why they elected Clinton.
Some aides were hoping last week that the president's order to bomb
terrorists' sites could have a similar effect.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of the past seven months has been heavy, whether or
not the president survives his legal and political troubles.
Current and former aides are only beginning to come to terms with
the fact that the president lied to them, too. In interviews last
week, several sounded deeply anguished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
