<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8089 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-23 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEIVER IS READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Freshman receiver Freddie Mitchell is in fine
working order, finally. His hands work; he catches everything in
sight. His mouth works; he's not bashful about his accomplishments.
And this summer, his brain worked, clearing the way for Mitchell to
play for the first time in 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took one session of summer school, I did real good, got
everything straight, and I should be on a roll,'' said Mitchell, a
Lakeland, Fla., native who sat out last season because he didn't
attain a qualifying ACT score until October.
</P>
<P>
   He enrolled immediately and eventually joined UCLA's baseball
team as an outfielder. Academic concerns dictated he concentrate on
schoolwork and one sport, football. Eight summer-school units
later, he expects to be eligible this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get my fill of academics,'' he said. ``Now I've got a
year under my belt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, hoping Mitchell will energize their slumping
punt-return unit and replace Jim McElroy as the primary deep
threat, welcomed him aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a playmaker,'' receivers coach Ron Caragher said. ``His
routes are getting better, he catches the ball very well, and he
goes and gets it. It's too early to say if Freddie can be the
big-play guy that (McElroy) was, but he has that capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is UCLA's most flamboyant receiver, by far. On Sunday,
he made an acrobatic catch that pulled his shorts to his knees,
exposing his gold bicycle tights. He scrambled to his feet and
scampered through the defense, pulling his shorts up as he ran.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the coaches are trying to temper Mitchell's
enthusiasm, turn his cockiness into quiet confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sometimes we have to get on him,'' Caragher said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell entered training camp as the No. 1 punt returner and
the No. 2 flanker, behind veteran Dan Farmer. Brad Melsby, back
from two years of injury and illness, is the first-string split
end. Sophomore Brian Poli-Dixon, perhaps the most talented of the
group, is behind Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell doesn't plan on being No. 2 for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to see what the team needs,'' he said. ``I'm going
to try to be the deep threat, and on third-and-three, when they're
asking, `Who do we go to?' I want the rock going to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ON ONE LEG: The Bruins will have one scholarship punter/kicker
for the Texas game, All-American Chris Sailer, and here's why:
</P>
<P>
   Teams are allowed a maximum of 105 players. By telling Sailer's
backup, Zak Haselmo, to skip training camp, the Bruins created an
extra roster spot for three weeks. Haselmo, from Cabrillo High in
Lompoc, is expected to rejoin the team Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bruins have more time to evaluate walk-ons for
long-term potential. In recent years, they've uncovered walk-on
gems like Farmer and quarterback Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   (One of the five current walk-ons is Newbury Park receiver
Russell Thomas.)
</P>
<P>
   That said, the plan implodes if Sailer gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   DROPPING BY: Venice High quarterback J.P. Losman, who committed
to UCLA in June, attended practice Saturday to evaluate his
competition: sophomore Drew Bennett and freshmen Scott McEwan, Ryan
McCann and Cory Paus.
</P>
<P>
   Losman, who has taken four summer-school sessions, plans to
graduate from Venice in December and enroll for the winter quarter
_ enabling him to participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming to compete with these guys because Cade (McNown) is
leaving,'' Losman said. ``If I'm not here in the spring, they'll
have a big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   RECRUITING UPDATE: Bernard Riley, a coveted defensive lineman
from Los Alamitos, watched practice Sunday and said he has trimmed
his list to eight schools: Arizona State, Florida State, Michigan,
Notre Dame, Texas, UCLA, USC and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Riley said UCLA and Florida State are his
favorites at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, 6-foot-2 and 300 pounds, is considered the top defensive
line prospect in the state. He plans to take five visits (the
maximum allowed) and decide in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to think about it during football,'' he said. ``I
don't want to get sidetracked with college football during my
senior year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
