<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYERS-MOMS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO PLAYERS' MOTHERS HELP THEIR CHILDREN, AND THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Becky Gatling will never forget her introduction
to the real National Basketball Association. It was November 1991,
and she and her husband, Ray, were waiting outside a locker room
for their son Chris, then a rookie with the Golden State Warriors.
The game had been over for nearly an hour, and while most of the
fans had filed out of the arena, Becky Gatling was amazed by how
many were still hanging around, waiting for the Warriors to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying, `Oh, this is great, look at all these family
members,''' she recalled. ``Then a player came up to me and said,
`Mrs. Gatling, these are not family members. These are hoochie
mamas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hoochie mamas, as the player called the female groupies,
were looking for Chris Gatling and his teammates. One interrupted
Becky Gatling's conversation with a player by jamming a card with
her phone number scribbled on it into the player's hand. Outside in
the parking lot, another ran after a player driving away in his
truck, screaming and waving her arms in a desperate attempt to get
his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `This is a crazy place,''' Becky Gatling said,
still sounding stunned at the thought. ``I told my husband, `This
is really an education.' It was like, welcome to the NBA!''
</P>
<P>
   Gatling shared that tale this weekend at the second annual
Mothers of Professional Basketball Players convention, held at a
hotel here on the shores of the Mississippi River. She was one of
75 women, most with sons in the NBA and also a handful whose
children play for the Women's National Basketball Association, the
American Basketball League and even the Harlem Globetrotters. They
turned out to laugh and learn, and to share with one another the
joys and pains of having a rich, famous and often relentlessly
scrutinized child.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bond between all of us because we've had a lot of
the same experiences and can relate to one another,'' said Georgia
West, mother of free-agent point guard Kevin Johnson. ``Before, I
felt alone with my feelings because my girlfriends didn't
understand, because their sons aren't in the NBA, but these ladies
do. We're like a support group. It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The mothers group was the brainchild of Charlotte Brandon, whose
son Terrell is a two-time All-Star point guard for the Milwaukee
Bucks. While attending the 1996 All-Star Game in San Antonio, she
was struck by the isolation of the players' mothers. Hardly any of
them knew each other, and many, according to Brandon, appeared to
be lonely and uncomfortable in the midst of the adoration being
poured on their sons.
</P>
<P>
   That weekend, she tossed the idea around with a few other moms,
and six months later, 23 mothers, including those of stars Grant
Hill, Gary Payton, Penny Hardaway, Shaquille O'Neal and Mark
Jackson, met in New York City to found the Mothers of Professional
Basketball Players.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the group's 90 members call themselves a sisterhood and
offer examples of the powerful bond they share: how Becky Gatling
received calls from nearly 30 mothers in a two-month period while
she was recovering from breast cancer surgery last spring, and how
Margje van der Weide, the mother of Indiana Pacers center Rik
Smits, flew all the way from the Netherlands to attend last year's
inaugural convention in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Gatling said she spoke with either Brandon, Marie Jackson, Helen
Mashburn or Lucille Harrison, the mother of Shaquille O'Neal, every
day. Brandon, who was diagnosed with cancer of the colon and liver
in 1993, was extremely helpful, sharing stories of how prayer and
faith helped her overcome the disease. The two built such a bond
that their frequent telephone conversations are beginning to
infringe on Chris Gatling's time with his mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group is great except for the fact that now when I call my
mother, she puts me on hold a lot of times because she's talking to
Mrs. Brandon,'' Gatling said in jest.
</P>
<P>
   Since he entered the league seven years ago, Gatling, now a
forward with the New Jersey Nets, has called his parents after
every game. And he is not alone. Nearly every mother said she spoke
with her son at least every other day during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be willing to bet that almost every player calls their
mother every day,'' said Janet Hill, the owner of a Washington
consulting firm and the mother of Grant Hill. ``That's not true of
most 20- to 30-year-old men, but because they have to deal with the
pressures of being traded, being a free agent, living in a foreign
city, being expected or even wanting to play when they're injured,
and being in the relentless media spotlight, they have the need for
constant sustenance. I talk to my son five out of seven days. He
calls me. There are mothers who would die to speak with their adult
sons that often.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The mothers say the camaraderie they enjoy stems from being able
to relax and not worry about one of the bitter fruits of their
sons' success: strangers who try to befriend them in hopes of
gaining access to the players' money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, the other mothers don't feel threatened, and I don't
feel threatened,'' said Carolyn Cato, whose son Kelvin was a rookie
with the Portland Trail Blazers last season. ``They're not out to
get me. I'm not out to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing inspiration from the basketball moms, Cassandra Sneed
Ogden, mother of Baltimore Ravens lineman Jonathan Ogden, started
the Professional Football Players Mothers Association earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   While comforting one another is a major goal, the basketball
moms are more than a social group. Life in the NBA is as much
business as it is basketball, and the mothers feel compelled to
tackle the off-the-court issues that can cause their sons problems.
At last year's convention, they had Horace Balmer, the league's
vice president of security, address them about the women and men
who prey on the players in a social scene that can sometimes be out
of control. Balmer told them about a woman who, after having sex
with players, would save the condom, freeze the sperm and give it
to her friends so they could try to get pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   And this weekend, Yolanda Brooks, a sports psychologist, and
Lonise Bias, a motivational speaker and the mother of University of
Maryland star Len Bias, who died of a drug overdose after being
drafted by the Boston Celtics in 1986, spoke about how the mothers
can help their sons navigate NBA life.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of the mothers, one of those dangers is the news
media. The rash of negative publicity that NBA players have
received within the past year _ including a report last year in The
New York Times that up to 70 percent of the players smoke marijuana
and drink excessively, and a Sports Illustrated article last spring
about players who have fathered numerous children out of wedlock _
had the moms on the defensive. Some even said they stopped watching
Oprah Winfrey's television show after she followed the Sports
Illustrated article with an episode on professional athletes, many
of whom were in the NBA, being negligent fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon, whose son Terrell has a 7-year-old son who was born out
of wedlock, said of the Sports Illustrated article: ``I didn't like
it, and none of the mothers liked it, because what they didn't
report was that while some of the men may have children out of
wedlock, some of these men are real fathers and not just with their
money. A lot of these men really love their children and are taking
care of them. I say if you're going to tell the story, tell the
whole story. But they're just looking for the dirt. All they want
is dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Jackson, the mother of Indiana point guard Mark Jackson,
added: ``This is a new day and a new era, and there are millions of
children born out of wedlock in society today, so why focus on
these players who are just living in what society dictates today? I
don't condone the behavior, but I do condone their right to
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their unhappiness with the coverage, the women were not
blind to the actions of many of the players. Indeed, Brooks, the
sports psychologist, drew cheers when she implored the mothers in a
Saturday morning seminar to ``teach your sons and daughters the
importance of parental responsibility, and that any male can make a
child but it takes a man to raise one.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky Gatling said: ``We know that these guys out here are not
angels. I tell Chris point blank, `You know, you need to zip it up
and keep it in your pants unless you've got all of this money you
want to give away.' I tell him to use a condom or don't do it at
all. I don't want any more grandchildren until I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The mothers' words can still fall upon deaf ears. Chris Gatling
has a 4-year-old daughter out of wedlock and two paternity suits
pending, his mother said. But it's not because he wasn't warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about the NBA is that when players achieve their
fame and notoriety, immediately somebody is in there trying to tear
down everything it took you 17, 18, 20 years to instill in your
child,'' said Pamela Martin, the mother of Los Angeles Clippers
guard Darrick Martin. ``That's why it's extremely important for you
to stay connected to him, whether he wants it or not at that time.
You have to continue to make the comments that they may not want to
hear. You can't forget that you're their mother, not their
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The mothers are also working collectively to advise players who
join the NBA without graduating from college to return to earn
their degrees. And they have prepared literature offering
guidelines on what to look for in an agent, and when the red flags
should go up.
</P>
<P>
   The moms involved other family members in this year's
convention, bringing the total number of participants in New
Orleans to 273, including 28 players. Chris Gatling, Terrell
Brandon, Malik Sealy and others sat on a panel discussing the
stresses of NBA life and came away impressed by the mothers' unity,
ambition and willingness to address weighty issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shock to me,'' Minnesota guard Stephon Marbury told
the women. ``I thought it was just going to be a bunch of mothers
hanging around and eating. But now I think every mother should come
to this, and every player should come. It should be a big event
because you all really have it going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
