<HEADLINE>
BOWEN PROBABLY OUT VS. PURDUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ It's looking unlikely that USC reserve tackle
Ken Bowen _ a two-year starter _ will be available for Sunday's
game against Purdue. He remains sidelined with a hyperextended
elbow and has not practiced in nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good for the game,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's injury would be considered more serious, but he's
dropped as low as third-string on the depth chart at right tackle,
behind starter Matt Welch and Rome Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for him, I feel pretty good,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Trojans doubtful for the game are fullback Marvin
Powell (twisted knee) and defensive lineman Darren Collins, who has
stretched ligaments in his foot and was wearing a soft cast on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mark Cusano, who missed a week with a hamstring
injury, has made ``huge'' strides, according to Hackett, and is
expected to play in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Collins, some more vital members of the defensive line
are nursing bumps and bruises. Defensive end Lawrence Larry (ankle)
and defensive tackle Aaron Williams (pulled groin) did not practice
Sunday. Both are considered day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Grant Pearsall remains out with a sore knee but
might return to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Pearsall's sore knee is opposite the knee in which he tore
ligaments last year. Hackett said he wants to make sure he has
experienced reserves at his position and other spots where players
are returning from serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Center Eric Denmon missed most of last season after undergoing
knee surgery and wide receiver Larry Parker's practice time has
been limited after he redshirted last season with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have strong backups so we don't put too much on
them,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Ife Ohalete is backing up Pearsall; Denmon's backup,
Matt McShane, was actually the No. 1 center after spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   __ Practice-only player: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward isn't
playing against Purdue because of poor academic performance, but
he's getting plenty of snaps and constantly making big plays in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   So is there a chance Hackett might place him back in the lineup
against the Boilermakers? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made that decision,'' Hackett said. ``I love watching him
practice and watching him play. He's a wonderful football player.
He knows he needs to raise his level of performance.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sudden impact: Quincy Woods put on a show Sunday with several
impressive receptions as he converts from quarterback to wide
receiver. He drew cheers from his teammates after catching a deep
pass over the shoulder from Jason Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quincy can help this football team,'' Hackett said. ``I'm
impressed (with his hands).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
