<HEADLINE>
CONGO AND REBELS CLAIM MILITARY GAINS, NEGATING DIPLOMATIC
EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Style changes throughout.)  (With CONGO-SAFRICA) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ The battle lines in the Congo's three-week-old
civil war were redrawn Sunday as government soldiers and their
allies recaptured a critical military base near the Atlantic coast,
greatly reducing the possibility that rebel forces could march into
the capital here.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the rebels appeared to have seized Kisangani,
the country's third-largest city, solidifying their positions in
eastern Congo. Kisangani is also the port of origin for ships that
carry food and other crucial supplies downstream to countless towns
and villages along the great Congo River.
</P>
<P>
   The developments raised the possibility of a protracted war in
which the government and the rebels, backed by their respective
allies, would fight each other from entrenched geographic positions
in this country's second civil war in as many years. The military
advances also overtook diplomatic efforts, led by South African
President Nelson Mandela, to negotiate a peaceful resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has pointed up the existing and emerging ethnic,
political and military rivalries in post-Cold War Africa. The
presidents of Rwanda and Uganda, the countries that Congo's
government and most Western diplomats believe are backing the
rebellion, attended the meeting led by Mandela in South Africa. But
Congo President Laurent Kabila, and his most vocal defenders, the
presidents of Zimbabwe and Angola, were not present to hear
Mandela's call for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Kinshasa remained eerily calm despite another night of a power
blackout imposed by the rebels as soldiers from Zimbabwe patrolled
the streets in flatbed trucks. Top aides to Kabila sounded
significantly more confident that the capital, which had seemed
ready to fall into advancing rebel hands any minute, would remain
under government control.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Kabila said, and the rebels acknowledged, that after
several days of bombing, the government and their Angolan allies
Sunday recaptured a military base in Kitona, in the far west. The
rebels had been flying troops and arms more than a thousand miles
from the territory they control in the east to Kitona, from which
they had begun their march toward Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of the airport at Kitona will prevent the rebels
from replenishing their forces, Western diplomatic and
transportation experts said, even as rebels approaching the capital
are running into Congolese troops assisted by soldiers from
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature to say that Kinshasa won't fall now, but this
is a very difficult situation for them,'' said a Western diplomat
here.
</P>
<P>
   No one ruled out, though, that the rebels, who are said to be as
close as 15 miles from Kinshasa, might make a last-ditch attempt to
drive into this city. Indeed, a private transportation company
official with offices in the region said that rebel soldiers
boarded two trains Sunday in Matadi, a city about 220 miles
southwest of the capital that is under rebel control, and were
headed toward the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Sakombi Inongo, a senior communications adviser to
Kabila, credited Congo's allies with turning the tide for the
government in the region southwest of Kinshasa. ``We have men and
planes from Angola, and we have men and planes from Zimbabwe,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Kitona recaptured by the government, the rebels also no
longer appear to be able to send fresh supplies by air to the
southwest, diplomats and transportation company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kitona airport was quiet Sunday night, officials said. They
also said that there were reports that there was little violence in
the eastern city of Kisangani, which the rebels said they
controled.
</P>
<P>
   In the eastern town of Goma, along the border with Rwanda, a
rebel leader, Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, said in a news conference
that rebel troops had ``arrived in Kisangani and Kisangani has
fallen,'' Reuters news service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Didier Mumengi, Kabila's information minister, said that
Kisangani had not fallen. But two other senior aides to Kabila did
not deny that rebels had captured Kisangani, and diplomats and
transportation company officials said they also had information
that the rebels had captured the city.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The apparent fall of the country's third-largest city is not as
significant as it was during the successful rebellion that Kabila
waged two years ago against Mobutu Sese Seko. Mobutu's 32-year rule
of the nation, which he called Zaire, turned one of Africa's
potentially richest countries into one of its poorest.
</P>
<P>
   During Kabila's efforts to win control of the country, Mobutu
moved foreign mercenaries into Kisangani to stop the rebellion from
the east. But Kabila, who was backed then by Rwanda and Uganda,
easily took the city on his way toward Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   But Kisangani's fall still entails strategic consequences,
Western diplomats said. The Congo River flows for 1,000 miles from
Kisangani to Kinshasa _ past cities, towns and villages that are
surrounded by some of the densest jungle in central Africa and are
inaccessible to trucks traveling in a country with possibly the
worst roads in the world.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no diplomatic solution to this conflict, some
experts predict a that Congo will split into two or more parts. The
rebels would end up controlling the northeast region near Rwanda
and Uganda, while the government would dominate in the west and
south.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, who left Kinshasa more than a week ago, remained Sunday
in the southern city of Lumbumbashi, in his native region, his
aides said. By not attending the conference in Pretoria, Kabila
avoided meeting with the leaders of Rwanda and Uganda, his former
allies, who had placed him at the head of the movement that led to
Mobutu's overthrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
