<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BALLERINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP TRAFFIC RUNS DOWN DIXIE FLAG TO WIN BALLERINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ They had a false start but a true
finish Sunday in the Ballerina Handicap at Saratoga, with the
5-year-old mare Stop Traffic outrunning five other fillies to win
by seven lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Stop Traffic not only stalked and ran down Dixie Flag, who had
sprinted into a long lead with some dizzying fractions, but also
buried the heavy favorite, Colonial Minstrel, who had won seven of
her last eight starts. And once she seized the lead in the
homestretch, Stop Traffic flew home far in front of two other late
runners, Runup the Colors and U Can Do It.
</P>
<P>
   The race was preceded, and even influenced, by a false start
when Runup the Colors and Furlough broke through the gate and
chased each other up the track. They were corralled, brought back
to the gate and then started in proper order. Jerry Bailey gunned
Dixie Flag into the lead with a dramatic dash that threatened to
steal the race, but Shane Sellers, aboard Stop Traffic, had no
intention of letting that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My filly charged the gate,'' Sellers said, ``and at the right
moment, it opened. So it seemed like the right timing. It was
obviously good for us that we got a good break, and when I saw
Jerry opening up with those quick fractions, I just decided to back
my filly up and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   He waited while Dixie Flag was shooting a quarter-mile in 21 3/5
seconds, opening a five-length lead, and spinning a half-mile in 44
2/5 seconds, still in front by three. But Stop Traffic was waiting
for the right moment to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Jerry had much left in his filly just by the
way he was riding her, so I just wanted to save what my filly
had,'' Sellers said. ``Then, at the quarter-pole, I pulled the
trigger, and she opened up in the clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Mandella, the son and deputy to Dick Mandella, who trains
Stop Traffic, said: ``Some jocks will be tempted to go when they
break so well, but when Shane saw that Jerry Bailey wanted the
lead, he remained calm and took a hold. It worked well because we
had a target until the far turn. And when she had about enough of
that, she took off and was full of run.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Flag, after her mad dash, faded from first to sixth and
last. Colonial Minstrel suffered a rough start, chased the flying
leaders into the stretch but finished fifth. Furlough, another
favorite, also showed nothing in the face of all the razzle-dazzle,
finishing fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't run her race,'' said Mark Hennig, who trains
Colonial Minstrel. ``She must have hit the gate when the two other
horses broke through at the start. She had blood coming out of her
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confusion in the gate, Stop Traffic ran the seven
furlongs in 1 minute 22 1/5 seconds, paid $12.40 for a $2 bet to
win and earned $120,000. She is a 5-year-old daughter of Cure the
Blues, and she has won 10 times and run in the money 19 times in 23
starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
