<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8114 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SOLICH-TEX     08-23 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOLICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLICH CHARGED WITH MAINTAINING NEBRASKA'S WINNING TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Imagining the scene is easy.
</P>
<P>
   Last August. Nebraska coach Tom Osborne, he of the medium cool
personality, knocks on the door of assistant head coach Frank
Solich. Osborne asks for a ``few minutes.'' Solich thinks his boss
wants to discuss the Cornhuskers' depth at I-back.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's monotone delivers the news that he plans on the 1997
season being his last and that he will recommend Solich as his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very nonchalant about it,'' Solich said last month
while sitting in the office that Osborne occupied for a quarter of
a century. ``It took about five minutes. Then he left.''
</P>
<P>
   The austere Osborne prided himself on consistency, of not
getting too high or too low during his 25 years as Nebraska's head
coach. Solich clings to the same tenets. But for once, Solich's
stoic, keep-your-keel-even demeanor was no match for the biggest
news of his coaching life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat there for a while,'' Solich said. ``I took a deep
breath. I had a tough time going back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement came Dec. 10 when Osborne announced
his retirement. Solich, a former Nebraska fullback and a 19-year
Cornhuskers assistant was chosen as Osborne's replacement. And when
Nebraska opens its 1998 season Saturday against Louisiana Tech in
the Eddie Robinson Football Classic, Solich gets his chance to
prove that he was the right choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 150 guys on the team, and not one of 'em wanted
anybody else but coach Solich,'' senior fullback Joel Makovicka
said. ``If you were going to find somebody who could handle the
pressure of following coach Osborne, it would be coach Solich.
They've both got the same air of confidence that trickles down to
the players.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the transition at Nebraska, a program of
habits, has been effortless. But that's the off-season perception.
There is the little matter of an upcoming season, the first one in
a quarter century without the angular Osborne on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get to that first game, get this thing rolling,''
said Solich, whose head-coaching experience consists of 13 seasons
as a Nebraska high school coach. ``I've got anticipation for the
first game. My approach has been to assume that we've done all we
can do to prepare for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel burdened. I feel a tremendous responsibility to
maintain the level we're at. I don't want to see it slip an inch.
I'm going to do everything I can to prepare myself and the players
to do that. If I looked too far down the road, I'd feel too
burdened. That would be pretty overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne was 35 when he took over for Bob Devaney in 1973. He
looked every bit of his 60 years when he coached his final game,
the 42-17 victory against Tennessee in the Orange Bowl that gave
the Cornhuskers a share of the 1997 national championship, their
third national title in the last four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Solich is a youthful-looking 53 years old. In a few years, one
wonders if Solich will resemble the ``before'' and ``after''
pictures of U.S. presidents who were aged by the stress of the job.
He keeps in shape running the Memorial Stadium steps five days a
week, but he has cut back on his regular weightlifting sessions.
</P>
<P>
   When it is suggested that he doesn't need to pump iron because
he's carrying the weight of a dynastic program on his back, he
laughs easily. Solich is relaxed. The pressure of the season starts
Saturday against Louisiana Tech, and never mind that Nebraska is a
341/2-point favorite and is again expected to be among the nation's
best teams.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, Solich has been familiar with the
Cornhuskers' perennial success. In the 36 years of the
Devaney-Osborne era, Nebraska never suffered a losing season; the
two worst seasons (6-4) came in 1967 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   After spending his childhood in Cleveland, Solich came to
Nebraska in 1962. He was part of the first recruiting class of
Devaney, who started the Nebraska machine rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-7 Solich weighed less than 160 pounds. During weigh-ins
before the first practice, Solich snuck five-pound weights onto the
scale so that he wouldn't be the team's lightest player.
</P>
<P>
   He played three seasons for the Cornhuskers as a fullback. He
became the first Nebraska back to gain 200 yards in a game and he
still holds the Orange Bowl record for return yards. As a senior,
``Fearless Frankie'' was team captain and All-Big Eight Conference.
</P>
<P>
   And Solich was on his way to becoming a transplanted Nebraskan.
After his stint as a high school coach, a 35-year-old Solich joined
Osborne's staff in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He says he never had a goal, a drive to be a college head coach.
That developed over the years of working for Osborne. There was no
defining moment when he realized he wanted to become a head coach.
But gradually, he realized he was being prepared to succeed
Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   And with that realization came the itch to be his own coach.
Solich's reputation was growing. He started receiving feelers from
schools with openings ... and Osborne appeared far from retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have settled for a rebuilding program,'' said Solich,
who received cursory contact from Oklahoma State and Kansas for
openings at those schools. ``I wasn't holding out for this job.
This will be a tremendous challenge, but there are a lot of jobs
out there like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A curious series of events involving other coaches kept Solich
at Nebraska. In December 1995, Kansas coach Glen Mason changed his
mind and stayed in Lawrence after accepting the job at Georgia. But
a year later, when Jim Wacker left Minnesota, Mason took that job.
The other serious candidate was Solich.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to resurrect a Gophers program that has won 27
games over the last eight seasons, Solich takes over Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a handful programs around the country where if
you've got a chance to be the coach there, you grab it,'' Nebraska
athletic director Bill Byrne said. ``This is one of those jobs.
Nebraska is the kind of place where everything is in place to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all that's expected of Solich is to perpetuate Osborne's
success. Solich won't equal Osborne's longevity, but he knows he'll
be expected to match the assembly line that has averaged 10
victories each of the past 25 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers could go 14-0 and win the national championship,
which would better last year's 13-0 record. But 14-0 is the best
Solich can hope for. Anything less than 10 victories is likely to
set off alarm bells that the dynasty is cracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, we're going to lose some football games here.
But we're not gonna lose a lot,'' Byrne said. ``We're in this with
Frank for the long term. I consider coaches' success to be gauged
as a marathon, not a sprint. We'll get an idea of Frank's success
in three or four years. But I don't think things are going to be a
lot different than what we've seen in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't think about the saying that nothing lasts forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never operated out of the fear of failure,'' Solich said.
``I don't see that as a negative, the amount of games we've won in
the past. I'm not worrying about the record Tom put up last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Orange Bowl, Osborne tried to make Solich's first
season a little easier by saying the Cornhuskers might be an 8-3
team even with a coach named Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the expectations are,'' Solich said. ``Some people
might have 8-3 expectations, but I haven't into run into many of
'em. They don't seem to ask me how we're going to do, they tell me
what we're going to do. That's a little nerve wracking. I know how
the business works. Who is Frank Solich to think I won't be
criticized? I believe I'll be able to handle what comes my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable aspect of this coaching change is
the fact that on that August day, Osborne entrusted his No. 1
assistant with keeping a secret that few people could have kept.
For four months, Solich went about his job as usual, keeping his
emotions in check, helping coach a team he knew would soon be his
own, knowing that he would be taking over for a coaching legend.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that meeting with Osborne more than a year ago, Solich
remembers that he was reluctant even to call his wife with the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited for dinner that night, and then I told her,'' he
said. ``And I crossed my fingers and hoped that she wouldn't tell
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Secrets, like All-America offensive linemen, national rushing
championships and 10-victory seasons, apparently are becoming
Nebraska trademarks. Solich is in charge of keeping the copyright
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we approach things offensively and defensively won't
change,'' he said. ``Philosophically, it will be the same. But yet,
you always are open to change. If change is needed, we'll do it. We
don't change for change's sake. What we've done is hold on to
what's made us successful with some slight adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to look for ways to make a mark on this program.
I don't think I need my own niche. The program has accomplished a
tremendous amount over the years, and it would be ridiculous to
throw aside the things that make it great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
