<HEADLINE>
TRANSIT SYSTEM TIGHTENS SCRUTINY OF DRIVERS' HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hoping to prevent accidents like the fatal crash last
year caused by a chronically ill bus driver who had a seizure at
the wheel, New York City Transit is revamping what officials have
conceded is a flawed system for tracking its employees' health.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year's crash on Fifth Avenue, officials said, the
agency has reviewed the medical files of 16,000 bus drivers, subway
motormen and other workers for seizures and related disorders. It
has taken three bus drivers and a motorman off active duty, and it
is computerizing a record-keeping system so fragmented that doctors
at one agency medical center are often unaware of a worker's
separate file at another center.
</P>
<P>
   And in response to a critical state investigative report last
month, the agency forced the retirement of a doctor found to have
ignored instructions in 1994 to insure that the driver in last
year's crash received treatment for alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has also set up a task force of medical, legal and
worker's compensation officials to meet and share information on
the attendance, accident and health records of workers who might
pose safety risks.
</P>
<P>
   But New York City Transit officials said they were still
troubled at having to rely largely on employees themselves for
medical information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult situation,'' said Al O'Leary, a
spokesman for the agency. ``There's an incentive for them not to
tell us'' about health problems, he said, because employees who do
so can end up on restricted duty and lose thousands of dollars a
year in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four workers taken off active duty have had
accidents on the job related to medical conditions, O'Leary said.
The train operator, however, told doctors that he had passed out
before having an accident in his own car, O'Leary said. And several
transit employees who spoke on condition of anonymity said that one
of the bus drivers had been in a minor accident after passing out
behind the wheel but that the crash had been hushed up at the
depot.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agency has also begun reviewing files to see whether there
are employees with unresolved drug or alcohol problems who should
not be in ``safety-sensitive'' jobs like driving a bus or a train.
</P>
<P>
   According to last month's report by the State Public
Transportation Safety Board, the driver in last year's crash,
Charles Alston, had sought treatment several times for alcoholism,
but was allowed back on the road without having completed
treatment, at one point against the instructions of the transit
department's deputy medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty in keeping track of workers with
substance abuse problems, said the agency's president, Lawrence
Reuter, is that if their problems have not yet been detected by the
management, they can enroll in a confidential union-run treatment
program. Even if they drop out of the program, management is not
notified.
</P>
<P>
   The union maintains that without the guarantee of
confidentiality, many employees with addictions would not seek help
at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0085 </DOCNO>
