<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BICYCLIST-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICYCLIST WITH WATER GUN IS SHOT BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 16-year-old bicyclist in Brooklyn who was carrying
a water pistol was shot and critically wounded early Sunday by two
police officers who were responding to a call about a man with a
gun and who apparently mistook the teen-ager's toy for a real
weapon, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, Michael Jones, was riding his bicycle with a
friend at the intersection of Clifton Place and Bedford Avenue in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, at about 2:40 a.m. when two
plainclothes officers who had been sent to look for a gun-wielding
bicyclist jumped from their car, ordered him to drop his gun and
then opened fire, said Sgt. Gerry Falcon, a Police Department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, who was shot several times in each leg, was listed in
critical condition Sunday night at Kings County Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned friends and family members said that Michael, who had no
criminal record before the incident, had sprayed friends with the
water gun all day Saturday at a nearby block party. Sunday, the
police charged Michael with menacing.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of Michael Jones was one in a series of incidents
in which teen-agers and younger children have been shot _ and, at
times, killed _ by police officers who have mistaken toy guns for
real weapons. Congress has ordered manufacturers to decorate toy
guns with neon colors to label them as fakes, and many chain stores
will not sell toy guns that can be painted to look real.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the police said, the gun resembled a particularly
lethal semiautomatic handgun that has long been a favorite of drug
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently it was a water gun, but it was a very, very
realistic replica of a Tec-9,'' said Marilyn Mode, the department's
deputy commissioner for public information. Tec-9's are
semiautomatic pistols with ventilated five-inch barrels and
magazines that can hold 32 bullets; easily altered to fire as
submachine pistols, they have long been considered the gun of
choice for drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The police department said that Sgt. Michael Jacobellis, 43, and
Police Officer David Gross, 26, opened fire on Michael Jones after
he pulled what appeared to be a large gun from his waistband and
ignored their orders to drop it. But Jermain Congress, 18, who was
riding his bike alongside Michael, said in an interview Sunday that
Michael had either dropped or was dropping the water pistol when
the officers shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's family questioned why the teen-ager would want to hold
onto a water pistol as he was stopped by the police. ``What was he
going to do, spray them in the eyes?'' asked his uncle, Randy
Jones, 36. ``It doesn't make any sense. If they said freeze, he
wouldn't pull a play gun on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980823.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     08-23 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VELARDE PUMPED FOR TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ While some Angels are nonchalant about a
10-game road swing that begins today in New York and will test
their mettle against the best teams in the American League, Randy
Velarde is exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   He is healthy, his two-run triple in the seventh inning on
Sunday afternoon at Edison Field gave the Angels a 3-2 victory over
Toronto, and he's going home to the Bronx, where he played for nine
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge for me to be going back to the old stomping
grounds,'' said Velarde, who collected his 13th and 14th RBI of the
season with that triple. ``You always want to do better when you go
home and this will be an exciting trip for us. It will be a good
measuring stick for us and we'll see what we're made of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pre-playoff preparation, if you will. It's a crucial time
of the season, and every game is a `must' for us.''
</P>
<P>
   On a muggy, 90-degree day, Chuck Finley (10-6) won a game for
only the second time in 10 starts, allowing six hits and the two
runs in 72/3 innings. He walked one and struck out seven, including
the side in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival mopped up to earn his 35th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when the good players get it done,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``It's a great time of the season, and I want
us to go on this trip and have some fun. I don't have to tell them
about the meaning of this trip. They're all adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a great series with the Yankees and with football
starting up, we need the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out and runners on second and third in the eighth
inning, Finley knew he was pitching to his final batter, Toronto
right fielder Shawn Green. With the count 3-2, Finley, a 6-foot-6
lefty, threw one low and away to the left-handed-hitting Green, who
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was either going to walk him or he was going to swing at it
in the dirt,'' Finley said. ``And he went fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Percival came on with two out to face Jose Canseco, striking him
out looking to the delight of the crowd of 34,142.
</P>
<P>
   Percival walked Carlos Delgado to start the ninth, then struck
out Jose Cruz Jr., again looking. After Percival's first pitch to
third baseman Tony Fernandez, Matt Walbeck threw a one-hop strike
to Velarde at second base to get Delgado trying to steal.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended on Percival's next pitch, as Fernandez bounced
out to Velarde. Velarde shook a few hands and scampered into the
dugout, but that didn't match the claps and smiles he displayed
after his seventh-inning triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an emotional player,'' he said. ``And it was a huge hit.
We had them on the ropes a couple of times and couldn't get the big
hit. And I haven't played much in two years, so I had it all
bottled up.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays starter Woody Williams, who has a history of fading
after the sixth inning, was yanked from the game after six innings
for Carlos Almanzar.
</P>
<P>
   And the Angels wasted no time in getting to Almanzar (1-1), as
Walbeck greeted him with a single to right off a 3-1 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Paco Martin followed with a bunt along the first-base line,
which Toronto first baseman Delgado pounced on. But Delgado threw
in the dirt to shortstop Alex Gonzalez at second and both runners
advanced a base when the ball squirted into the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro popped out to short.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Velarde, who said he was comfortable when he stepped
into the box. ``And when you're comfortable, you're confident,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde missed all of last season when he injured his right
elbow in spring training, and he had reconstructive surgery
pioneered by Tommy John a month later. Further problems with that
injury have shelved him for stints this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a split-finger fastball, and on a 1-and-2 pitch I was
just trying to hit it to the big part of the park,'' Velarde said.
``That's exactly what I did.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays scored first, when Cruz led off the second by
doubling down the left-field line. He moved to third on a flyout by
Fernandez, then scored on catcher Mark Dalesandro's single to
right. The Angels bounced back in the bottom of the inning with a
run of their own when Walbeck hit a one-out fly to right with the
bases loaded, scoring Garret Anderson. Martin, spelling Gary
DiSarcina at shortstop, followed that with a deep fly to Shannon
Stewart in left, which Stewart caught as he backpedaled onto the
warning track.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto forged ahead in the fifth when Fernandez led off with a
single, took second on Dalesandro's flyout to center and scored on
a Gonzalez two-out double.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, the Angels' third-string center fielder behind Jim
Edmonds and Reggie Williams, played Gonzalez a bit too shallow.
When he finally had a gauge on the drive, it had sailed over his
head and bounced over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley struck out the side in the sixth, retired the side in
the seventh and got out of trouble in the eighth when he let
Percival finish the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to keep guys healthy,'' Finley said. ``This is
nice to see. Two or three months ago, with all the injuries we had,
there weren't many people who thought we'd be in this position. And
here we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge homestand for us. We felt like we were playing
teams we could beat, and now we have to take it to New York. Now
we're in position to do some big things on the East Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
