<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 62, PLAYER PROVES HE IS STILL IN STEP WITH GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ Striding down the fairway together at the Meadow
Brook Club here Sunday, Gary Player, showing a touch of gray, and
Lee Trevino, gray and somewhat stockier, evoked memories of their
glory days of two decades ago during the final round of the
Northville Long Island Senior PGA Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than being pursued by young turks, as was usually the
case in the 1960s and '70s, the 62-year-old Player and the
58-year-old Trevino were pursuing a ``young'' turk, 51-year-old
Walter Hall, after he birdied the first hole to take a one-stroke
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Player, who started the day two strokes off the lead, caught
Hall and the second-round co-leader, Tom Shaw, at the 11th hole
after consecutive birdies as all three stood at 11 under par.
Player, the winner of 172 tournaments in a 46-year professional
career, including nine Grand Slams, recorded his fourth birdie of
the day at the 401-yard par-4 16th hole. He overtook Hall and went
on to shoot his third straight 68 and win his first Senior PGA
tournament in three years, finishing at 12-under-par 204 for a
one-shot victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a former sales executive who never played on the regular
PGA Tour and was seeking his first victory since joining the senior
circuit last year, shot a 69 to tie for second with 57-year-old
J.C. Snead, who finished with a 67. Trevino, the winner of a record
27 Senior PGA tournaments, including this one twice, was a stroke
back at 206 after a final-round 69.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the $150,000 first prize _ which came a day after he
had won $18,000 for winning the ``superseniors'' 36-hole
tournament-within-a-tournament for players in the field 60 and over
_ Player became the second oldest player to win a Senior PGA event.
The oldest was Mike Fetchick, who won a tournament in 1985 on his
63rd birthday. Player, who plays the senior tour infrequently
because he is busy designing golf courses, also has a golf
equipment company and his horse ranch in his native South Africa.
He will turn 63 on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rewarding and very gratifying to do this,'' said
Player, who has long espoused physical fitness and is still as fit
and trim as he was in his prime and doing at least 1,000 situps
every day. ``It shows what you can do when you exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Player's nerves and tenacity, along with his penchant for
fitness and his shotmaking skills, have always been hallmarks of
his career. And he said his nerves were the key to his victory on
this warm overcast day. ``I had tremendous control of my nerves
today, which I did not yesterday,'' said Player, who had five
birdies and only one bogey. ``I felt very serene from the time I
woke up this morning and kept that mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Steady all-round play also was a factor. ``I don't think I was
ever in the rough,'' said Player, who never missed a fairway and
putted superbly.
</P>
<P>
   Nerves may have hurt Hall at the end when he missed birdie putts
of about 6 feet on the last three holes. Had he made one of them,
he could have forced a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was asked whether Player had an edge in that regard at the
end? ``Absolutely,'' replied Hall, who, until he went on the Asian
golf tour in 1984, had spent three decades in sales. ``He's been
there a thousand times.''
</P>
<P>
   Player, who received a hug and kiss from Trevino on the 18th
green after they had finished their round, said he saw no reason
why he should not continue winning tournaments. ``I think I can
still win at 70,'' he said this weekend. ``And I think someone will
win the Masters in their 60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be Player, who has already won three titles at Augusta
National? ``If I worked at it, I believe I could still do it,''
said Player, who this year became the oldest man ever to make the
cut at the Masters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
