u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRE-BASEBALLS-     08-23 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRE-BASEBALLS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRE UNDER INVESTIGATION DENIES SELLING BALLS FROM PERFECT GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Clark, the umpire under investigation in the sale
of baseballs supposedly used in David Wells' perfect game, denied
emphatically on Sunday that he had anything to do with the sale of
the balls. He also said he could not understand why major-league
baseball would not believe the man who said he sold the balls and
signed Clark's name to a letter authenticating Wells' signature.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who was on vacation when news of the investigation
surfaced last week, said he had not talked to any of the security
people handling the investigation, but he said he spoke with Gene
Budig, the American League president, weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gene a long time ago whatever the bottom line is, the
bottom line is I didn't do it,'' Clark said by telephone from his
home in Williamsburg, Va. ``I had no knowledge of it. I didn't
write the letter, I didn't sign the letter and I certainly don't
condone the letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which bore Clark's signature, accompanied six balls
that Mark Lewis, a memorabilia dealer from Long Island, N.Y.,
bought from Rich Gressle, of Milburn, N.J., who is a friend of
Clark's. Gressle said on Friday that he wrote the letter and signed
Clark's name to it, but that Clark knew nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told people at major-league baseball when this first started
that Al had nothing to do with this, but nobody wanted to believe
that,'' Gressle said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he did not know why baseball officials would not
believe Gressle. ``Do you know anybody who would implicate himself
in something like this?'' Clark asked.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who returns to work Monday night, said he met Gressle a
number of years ago in Trenton, N.J. Gressle said they have been
friends for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a friend of mine; I won't deny that,'' Clark said.
``I've got nothing to hide. I think he just infringed on a
friendship. Like he said, the motivation was greed and money. He
thought he could make some easy money.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he spoke with Gressle once about seven weeks ago
after he learned of the investigation. ``I asked him what it was
all about,'' Clark said. ``He said he screwed up. He said he made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's name has been mentioned before as an umpire who asks for
items from players and clubs. ``With stuff like this, his name
always comes up,'' said one baseball official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said he did not know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked for autographed balls,'' he said, ``and I give
them to charities and auctions and golf tournaments and those
things, just like other umpires do. I've given stuff away, but I've
never sold anything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lewis, the dealer in Centereach, N.Y., said last week he had
bought memorabilia on several occasions from Gressle, including
items from the 1995 game in which Cal Ripken Jr. broke Lou Gehrig's
record for consecutive games. Clark was the third base umpire in
that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the balls came from Clark and other umpires,''
Lewis said, speaking generally of the memorabilia, ``but the
majority from Clark.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 50, said he did not know Lewis, had had no dealings with
him and had never spoken with him. Did he think Gressle might have
sold Lewis memorabilia?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine he did, but I do not know that for sure,'' the
umpire said. ``Have I given Richie Gressle some stuff before? Yes.
Have I been paid for it? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Why has he given Gressle items? ``He's got two kids,'' Clark
said. ``He's a collector. He enjoys that stuff. It was for personal
use only.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a 23-year AL umpire, said he learned of the investigation
from Richie Phillips, the head of the umpires' union. ``I told him,
`I don't know what you're talking about,''' Clark recalled. ``I had
no knowledge that this was happening, that this man wrote the
letter, that he forged my signature. I am completely a victim in
this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
