<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PITCHING-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS TRADE FOR TWO MINOR-LEAGUERS TO BOLSTER BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The New York Yankees traded for two
minor-league pitchers Sunday to bolster their stock of right-handed
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Brian Cashman sent the former No. 1 draft pick
Shea Morenz and minor-league pitcher Ray Ricken to San Diego for
Jim Bruske and Brad Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Bruske, 33, was Cashman's primary objective in the deal.
The pitcher spent most of this season with the Los Angeles Dodgers
before San Diego acquired him on July 23. The Padres optioned him
to Class AAA Las Vegas shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Bruske was 3-0 with a 3.48 earned run average with the Dodgers
and allowed three runs in seven innings for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries to Jeff Nelson and Darren Holmes, and
because right-handers Marty Janzen and Scott Brow have pitched
poorly for Class AAA Columbus, the Yankees are somewhat
short-handed in right-handed relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bruske will probably not be part of the Yankees' postseason
roster, but he will most likely be called up for September and used
in middle relief.
</P>
<P>
   Others likely to be promoted from Columbus, along with Bruske,
when the rosters expand: catcher Mike Figga, outfielders Shane
Spencer and Ricky Ledee, and pitchers Mike Jerzembeck and Mike
Buddie.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, 25, was 9-9 with a 6.39 ERA for Las Vegas. Both he and
Bruske will report to Columbus. To make room for Bruske on their
40-man roster, the Yankees designated Brow for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Morenz, a 24-year-old outfielder, was the Yankees' No. 1 pick in
the 1995 draft and never matched the team's expectations for him,
batting .252 with 15 homers for Class AA Norwich this year. The
Padres wanted to draft Morenz, but lost out to the Yankees. John
Moores, the owner of the Padres, is a friend of the Morenz family.
</P>
<P>
   Ricken, 24, the Yankees' fifth-round pick in 1994, was 0-3 with
a 7.32 ERA for Norwich.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, coming back from tendinitis in his shoulder,
will probably start the first game of Wednesday's doubleheader
against Anaheim, and Hideki Irabu, coming back from a bruised foot,
is expected to pitch Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But as the playoffs draw near, Manager Joe Torre must decide who
will start and who will move to the bullpen. Several weeks ago, it
seemed sure that Orlando Hernandez would be moved to middle relief.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez has been much more aggressive in recent starts,
pitching inside more to left-handed batters, and this may increase
the odds of him remaining in the rotation in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that he's getting both sides out,'' said Torre, referring
to right-handed and left-handed batters, ``it makes for a tough
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wells and David Cone, candidates for the American League
Cy Young Award, are all but assured of being in the rotation for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If Hernandez is a starter in the playoffs, that will probably
mean that Irabu will shift to the bullpen. Those decisions, Torre
said, won't be made until well into September. ``Then we'll just
see who's pitching well,'' he said. ``We'll do what we have to to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
