   (NYT8) HONOLULU -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- HAWAII-REPUBS-1, 8-23 --
Gov. Benjamin Cayetano, left, seeking re-election in Hawaii, with
one of his opponents, Frank Fasi, a former mayor of Honolulu, at a
recent debate. Cayetano, the state's first Filipino-American
governor and a Democrat, may yet become just another victim of the
Asian crisis. Despite the spectacular vistas of ocean, mountains
and lava fields that make tourism the backbone of the state
economy, turmoil in Asian financial markets has rocked Hawaii like
an unrelenting hurricane. (David Scull/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BERKELEY, Calif. -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- LAW-PUBLISHER-MEDIA,
8-23 -- Stephen Elias, a former legal aid lawyer, is associate
publisher at Nolo Press, which produces do-it-yourself legal
guides. In the late 1980s, Nolo started offering a guidebook with
software called ``Willmaker'' that suddenly shifted the company
into a new stratosphere, doubling their revenue. ``The software
seems to pose the greatest threat to lawyers,'' says Elias, who
notes that it is easier and more efficient to prepare a basic will
with software than with a handbook. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- CLINTON-CHURCHES, 8-23 --
The Very Rev. Nathan D. Baxter, speaking to the congregation at the
Washington National Cathedral about President Clinton's
acknowledgment of an inappropriate relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. Clinton's unsavory relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was a
focus of sermons around the nation on Sunday. ``Unless we
acknowledge moral failing -- without excuse -- the soul of our
nation will not heal,'' said Rev. Baxter. ``I still believe
President Clinton loves his country, his family, and his God. And I
know that God loves him.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- , 8-23 -- MOTHER-JUSTICE,
8-23 -- Najee Ali, far left, Yolanda Manuel, 28, and Earl Ofari
Hutchinson, announcing a new petition drive, spurred by an attack
on Ms. Manuel's daughter, to make it a crime to fail to report a
child molestation. Ms. Manuel's 7-year-old daughter, Sherrice
Iverson, was sexually assaulted, strangled and left in a toilet in
a Nevada casino, 43 miles south of Las Vegas. ``This ain't a
political issue. It's a human being issue. It's a justice issue for
my little girl,'' says Ms. Manuel. ``A little girl who will never
be able to reach for her goals.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CINCINNATI -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- P&AMP;G-INTERNET-ADS, 8-23 --
Denis Beausejour, Procter &AMP; Gamble's vice president for
advertising, at an Internet conference that brought together some
400 executives from Internet and consumer marketing companies, at
Procter's headquarters in Cincinnati. Now that the Internet has
become the first medium to actually reduce the viewership of
television, Procter is trying to figure out how to sell soap -- and
other consumer products -- without soap operas. (Mark Lyons/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HOLLYWOOD -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- FILM-PRODUCER-MEDIA, 8-23
-- Tracey Trench, 34, a former director of film development at 20th
Century Fox, at Fox Studios in Hollywood. Ms. Trench is an
independant movie producer who can work on a tight budget. Ms.
Trench is a heroine at Fox, because she brought a happy ending to
the film ``Ever After,'' a retelling of the Cinderella fable with
Drew Barrymore as the heroine, a production that seemed headed for
financial trouble. She is now developing two films for Fox's 2000
film division. (Bart Bartholomew/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ATLANTA -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- TECH-BANKING, 8-23 --
Atlanta-based Security First Network Bank, existed only online
before it opened its first real branch -- which it calls a ``city
office''-- in Atlanta in 1997. Today, many so-called virtual banks,
which were created to exist solely on the Internet, have
reluctantly had to acknowledge the need for face-to-face
interaction with customers for products like loans and have opened
conventional brick-and-mortar branches. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- CATTLE-INTERNET,
8-23 -- David Reynolds, owner of Higher Plain Genetics, in
Cooperstown, N.Y., finds it difficult to attend live cattle
auctions that are a crucial part of his vocation, so he has bought
Holstein embryos online. Luckily for Reynolds, animal husbandry --
like so many other commercial endeavors these days -- has gone
online. ``It's great,'' Reynolds says. ``You just get up in the
morning, log on, see where the prices are and place your bid.''
(Michael J. Okoniewski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
