Denis Beausejour, Procter &AMP; Gamble's vice president for
advertising, at an Internet conference that brought together some
400 executives from Internet and consumer marketing companies, at
Procter's headquarters in Cincinnati. Now that the Internet has
become the first medium to actually reduce the viewership of
television, Procter is trying to figure out how to sell soap -- and
other consumer products -- without soap operas. (Mark Lyons/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HOLLYWOOD -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- FILM-PRODUCER-MEDIA, 8-23
-- Tracey Trench, 34, a former director of film development at 20th
Century Fox, at Fox Studios in Hollywood. Ms. Trench is an
independant movie producer who can work on a tight budget. Ms.
Trench is a heroine at Fox, because she brought a happy ending to
the film ``Ever After,'' a retelling of the Cinderella fable with
Drew Barrymore as the heroine, a production that seemed headed for
financial trouble. She is now developing two films for Fox's 2000
film division. (Bart Bartholomew/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ATLANTA -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- TECH-BANKING, 8-23 --
Atlanta-based Security First Network Bank, existed only online
before it opened its first real branch -- which it calls a ``city
office''-- in Atlanta in 1997. Today, many so-called virtual banks,
which were created to exist solely on the Internet, have
reluctantly had to acknowledge the need for face-to-face
interaction with customers for products like loans and have opened
conventional brick-and-mortar branches. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. -- Aug. 23, 1998 -- CATTLE-INTERNET,
8-23 -- David Reynolds, owner of Higher Plain Genetics, in
Cooperstown, N.Y., finds it difficult to attend live cattle
auctions that are a crucial part of his vocation, so he has bought
Holstein embryos online. Luckily for Reynolds, animal husbandry --
like so many other commercial endeavors these days -- has gone
online. ``It's great,'' Reynolds says. ``You just get up in the
morning, log on, see where the prices are and place your bid.''
(Michael J. Okoniewski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
