<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-McGWIRE-745&AMP;ADD-N     08-23 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McGWIRE-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE HOME RUN TOUR KEEPS ROLLING ALONG  
(nk) 
 By BILL MODOONO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The elements of a rock concert are present,
certainly _ the large crowds, the thunderous applause, the curtain
calls. Even the celebrities visiting backstage. But as the Mark
McGwire home run tour continues its astounding summer run, other
comparisons are becoming appropriate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, before another sellout crowd at Three Rivers Stadium,
McGwire turned in a performance worthy of a minimalist art show. In
the 89-degree heat, he chose not to take batting practice. He
limited his pregame exercise primarily to stretching. When he
waited on deck during the game, he took no practice swings. When he
went out to his first base position, he did not jog until he
crossed the third-base line.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, he delivered the masterpiece _ a picture-perfect
home run into the sun-kissed bleachers in left field in his final
at-bat, which gave him 53 homers for a season that seems headed for
the record books.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' Sammy Sosa, also chasing the single-season homer mark
of 61, hit Nos. 51 and 52 against the Houston Astros Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish every baseball player could feel what I'm feeling
now,'' McGwire said minutes after his St. Louis Cardinals lost,
4-3, to the Pittsburgh Pirates before 42,134 fans, all of whom
seemed to be bigger fans of his than they were of the home team.
</P>
<P>
   After grounding out, walking twice and hitting a double in his
previous four appearances, McGwire hit a 2-2 fastball off Pirates
reliever Ricardo Rincon in the eighth inning that opened a
floodgate of support from what should have been hostile fans.
</P>
<P>
   They stood and cheered and stomped on the dugout and would not
stop until McGwire took what may have been the only curtain call by
an opposing player in the 28-year history of Three Rivers. Not that
McGwire wanted to take it. ``I felt uncomfortable,'' he said,
noting that he did not want to ``show up'' the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, however, talked him into stepping back onto the
field and doffing his cap. When the inning ended and McGwire went
back out to first, he was serenaded by another standing ovation.
This was followed by an exodus by the crowd, despite the tenuous
nature of the Pirates' one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, they had gotten their money's worth. ``It's a
wonderful thing to see,'' Cardinals Manager Tony La Russa said.
``It shows they appreciate what this guy is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa has seen such things before. He remembered a game in
Tiger Stadium during Vida Blue's remarkable rookie season with
Oakland in 1971, for example. ``The difference is, he's doing it
every day,'' La Russa said of McGwire, ``and that's making it real
special.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's celebrity status got a Pittsburgh seal of approval
before the game when retired Penguins superstar Mario Lemieux came
by to meet him. McGwire responded by giving Lemieux an autographed
bat.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is in the midst of a hot streak that has produced six
home runs in seven games, including one in which he pinch-hit. With
32 games remaining, he seems very likely to break the season record
for home runs of 61, set by Roger Maris in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire does not see himself as a sure thing. ``I'm not
close to it,'' he said of Maris' mark. ``I'm a long way away, and
it's a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire attributed some of his recent success to the fact that
he is ``not thinking as much'' but ``doing a lot of reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   What he is not reacting to is the controversy swirling around
his use of the over-the-counter substance androstenedione, a
nutritional supplement intended to raise levels of the male hormone
testosterone in order to build lean muscle mass and promote
recovery from injury. It is legal in baseball but banned by the
National Football League and the International Olympic Committee
because it is thought to provide an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to waste my breath on it,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Cardinals issued a statement credited both
to the team and to McGwire that said that androstenedione is ``a
natural substance'' that has no ``proven anabolic steroid effect.''
The statement said that it raises a player's testosterone levels
for only one hour and that it is used only to enhance workouts, not
on-the-field performances.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a lack of ``documentary evidence'' of adverse side
effects, ``the Cardinals medical staff cannot object to Mark's
choice to use this legal and over-the-counter supplement,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As is the case at many of McGwire's games, a lot of the pressure
fell on the pitchers, who were booed by the fans almost every time
a pitch was thrown out of the strike zone. The fans were so hungry
to see McGwire succeed Sunday, they even gave him some polite
applause for his double to open the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire refuses to be upset about his walks. His two Sunday gave
him 136 for the year and broke a team record set by Jack Clark in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take pride in walks,'' he said. ``Like my college coach
taught me, a walk is as good as a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's traditional baseball wisdom, and McGwire's season is
anything but traditional. In a normal season, for instance,
McGwire's teammate, Fernando Tatis, might have been in line for
some media attention for his 5-for-5 game, which included a homer.
Instead, all Tatis got was jostling from the media horde that was
scrambling to talk to McGwire, who was standing in the locker stall
next to his.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his hot streak, La Russa still plans to rest McGwire on
Monday afternoon when the Cardinals close out their three-game
series with the Pirates, winners of nine of their last 11 games.
McGwire will, however, take batting practice and will be available
to pinch-hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the fans might be disappointed,'' La Russa said,
``but it's never difficult to do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seemed pleased to be getting the day off. He has only
one more scheduled day off the rest of the season. The one-day
vacation and his 53rd homer had him beaming and relaxed during his
post-game news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a game,'' he said. ``I'm playing a game I've played
since I was 9 years old. That's how I look at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
