r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     08-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS SHOULD BE ON THE FIELD, NOT THE MEDICINE CABINETS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question, after this past week, is no longer if.
</P>
<P>
   It's when. And who. And how far is the record-breaking home-run
ball going to travel.
</P>
<P>
   The storybook weeks of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have thrust
baseball's best adventure back onto the front pages again. The
game's most hallowed record is about to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both have a good chance,'' said a man in the Rangers'
clubhouse who knows what record-teasing is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, how close to the plate will the pitchers throw
to them in the last month of the season?'' Juan Gonzalez asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' right fielder's three-month flirtation with Hack
Wilson's record of 190 runs batted in is no longer an issue on the
sports pages. Pitchers took notice. Opportunities seemed to vanish
for a week. Then Gonzalez got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   History doesn't wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay hot,'' Gonzalez said. ``They're both hot
right now. But the thing is, you have to ``stay'' hot.''
</P>
<P>
   After these past five days, McGwire and Sosa are officially ``en
fuego.''. Hard hats are advised in area bleachers. Hail-sized
baseballs are being reported throughout the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, however, Wheaties might not be calling the two
sluggers. Their champion breakfast is called Creatine. And, in
McGwire's case, the pregame snack of choice is Androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone else have a problem with last weekend's wire story?
I sure do.
</P>
<P>
   According to his editor, Associated Press reporter Steve
Wilstein was with a group waiting at McGwire's locker. ``He didn't
touch anything,'' the editor said. But Wilstein ``wrote down only
what he saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop right there. If Wilstein comes to your house, does he have
free rein to look inside your medicine cabinets?
</P>
<P>
   It's rude. It's unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   What if McGwire had an opened fan letter from a _ how shall I
put this? _ more-than-zealous female fan? Would it be OK to print
excerpts from that?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not stop there. Let's let the fans know the entire story.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark _ boxers or briefs?
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland _ spray deodorant or roll-on guy?
</P>
<P>
   But I digress. We're supposed to be talking about home runs
here.
</P>
<P>
   And that's my point. McGwire and Sosa roundly deserve their
upcoming month in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from either of them, but I think
Sammy may have a better chance,'' said shortstop Royce Clayton, who
was a St. Louis teammate of McGwire for the first 40 of his homers.
``For one, Sammy is a bad-ball hitter and, two, they can't walk
him. The guy steals over 30 bases a year. You have to factor that
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with the guys hitting behind Mark, but
teams are just going to walk him an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and Gonzalez concede that Sosa has one other edge going
for him: Wrigley Field's legendary friendly confines. An auspicious
September wind could blow a Sosa pop-up or two _ or 10 _ into the
basket above the Wrigley ivy.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Wrigley Field to Gonzalez, and a starry look comes to
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're talking,'' he said. Gonzalez's lack of affection
for The Ballpark's spacious left-field dimensions are a matter of
local record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too big here,'' he said with a wistful shake of the head.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' Sosa, therefore, has the edge in ballparks. The
Cardinals' McGwire has the edge in ... muscles. Bat speed. Raw
home-run power.
</P>
<P>
   And here we are talking about Androstenedione again.
</P>
<P>
   The stories over the weekend about McGwire's choice of ``diet
supplements'' had a dark edge to them. But in truth, the whole
issue of over-the-counter supplements is shrouded in gray.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether Andro, designed to raise levels of male
testosterone, is harmful, because a 1994 act of Congress removed
much of its regulatory control of the diet supplement business. The
Cardinals' medical staff said it has no objections to McGwire using
either Creatine or Andro.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Androstenedione is the substance, banned since
last December, that was found recently in the sample of Olympic
gold-medal shot putter Randy Barnes, who faces a possible lifetime
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not jump to conclusions in the McGwire case. Baseball
and pro basketball don't ban Andro. And nearly every clubhouse and
pro locker room has somebody who has taken Sudafed to relieve some
sort of congestion. Sudafed, also an over-the-counter drug, is on
the International Olympic Committee's banned list.
</P>
<P>
   A stirring _ and probably historic _ September lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion here is that we keep our eyes on the batter's
box. Not somebody's locker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-98 2311EDT &QL; 
