<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB LEAGUE PROTESTS ATTACKS ON SUDAN, AFGHANISTAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Angered by US strikes on Sudan and
Afghanistan, Islamic leaders Sunday demanded an urgent UN meeting
to protest Washington's ``blatant violation'' of international law.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of increasing tensions with the United States, the
Arab League also called for a UN fact-finding investigation into
the cruise missile attacks and urged the United States to avoid
further attacks. But the league stopped short of asking for any
specific penalties against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Afghanistan Sunday, a spokesman said the Taliban Islamic
movement had restricted the movements of Osama bin Laden, the
target of the US strikes. In Pakistan, Red Cross workers arrived
after being evacuated from Kabul, the Afghan capital, and Kandahar
``pending a change in the situation,'' a Red Cross official said.
</P>
<P>
   While US public support for the missile strikes last week is
high, officials are watching for reactions in Pakistan and other
countries, where small, hard-line Islamic groups are protesting
against the strikes and appear to be gaining public sympathy. Sudan
Sunday asked Washington for a public apology of the missile strike
on a factory and said it would welcome US inspections of the site
and other alleged chemical plants.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, Information Minister Ghazi Salah Din
confirmed that Sudan is recalling its diplomats from Washington
``in retaliation for the US actions.'' But Sudan will not break
relations entirely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a unified effort to explain the missile strikes and maintain
public support for President Clinton's tougher antiterrorism
policy, a half-dozen national security officials appeared on
television to call the strikes successful. ``There may be future
strikes,'' Defense Secretary William S. Cohen warned on NBC's
``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Although an executive order prohibits US-government-sponsored
assassinations, Cohen added that the United States said ``no one
would weep'' if bin Laden died in a future attack. ``If he is in
the line of fire as such, that's his problem,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent a quiet day on Martha's Vineyard after a turbulent
week that included an admission of an improper sexual relationship
with Monica S. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and the first
US attack on suspected terrorism sites in two countries
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   New details about the Aug. 7 bombings of US embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania and preparations for Washington's retaliations also
emerged Sunday. Intercepted phone conversations between two of bin
Laden's aides gave the White House convincing evidence in the
bombings, Newsweek reported. The magazine said a confession by a
33-year-old Pakistani suspect also helped build the case.
</P>
<P>
   General Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said the United States had good information that the bombings in
Africa ``might be only the first two of three and possibly four
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Clinton's harshest critics Sunday endorsed the US
military action. ``I think the president did exactly the right
thing,'' Representative Porter Goss, a Florida Republican who is
chairman of the House Intelligence Committee, told ``Fox News
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press and Reuters was used in this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
