</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-PHONE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE WORKERS IN CONNECTICUT BEGIN A STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of workers from Southern New England Telecommunications
Corp. walked picket lines Sunday as customers braced for possible
service delays on the first day of a strike that began just after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone company and Local 1298 of the Connecticut Union of
Telephone Workers and Communications Workers of America, which
represents the striking workers, did not negotiate Sunday, but each
side expressed eagerness to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get down to doing what we have to do so people can get
back to work here,'' said Jim Grinberg, a spokesman for the union.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the phone company, Kevin Moore, said he expected
the federal mediator who has been overseeing the negotiations to
advise the company of a new schedule for talks on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said ``the vast majority'' of the company's 3,600
management workers had been called in to replace the 6,300 striking
operators, customer service representatives and technicians.
Nevertheless, he said, customers would probably face delays in
reaching operators and having new service installed. The company
provides phone service to nearly 3 million Connecticut customers.
</P>
<P>
   The union called the strike at 12:01 a.m. Sunday after the two
sides failed to reach an agreement in negotiations. The telephone
company and union negotiators had reached a tentative agreement on
Aug. 7, but talks were reopened under the federal mediator, Tom
Carroll, after the proposal met resistance from rank-and-file union
members who said the contract did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   They want the phone company to eliminate its two-tier wage
structure, in which workers doing the same job are paid different
wages, and to provide salary parity with telephone workers in other
states, whom the union contends are paid 20 percent to 25 percent
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to be paid as well as people across the country
for the same jobs,'' Grinberg said. ``We live in one of the most
expensive states in the Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the company had thought negotiations were progressing
on Saturday. ``Until the end of the workday, we were fairly
confident in reaching an amicable settlement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, union workers were manning picket lines at SNET
locations in New Haven, Hartford, Stratford, Meriden and other
Connecticut cities. The Associated Press reported that one picketer
in Stratford suffered minor injuries when he was struck by a car,
and that one person was arrested. It was not clear whether the
incident was related to the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The last strike against SNET, in 1986, lasted eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, 73,000 Bell Atlantic workers went on strike
for two days before negotiators agreed on a two-year contract
guaranteeing that jobs in the company's high-technology growth
areas will go to union employees. Bell Atlantic also agreed to
phase out a nonunion customer service operation in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The communications workers union is also on strike against
another regional Bell company, U S West, which is based in Denver
and provides telephone service to 25 million customers in 14
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
