<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-ROBINSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON OUTLASTS GATTI FOR SPLIT DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During an eight-month layoff, Arturo Gatti changed trainers,
changed training strategies and even changed his hair color. But
when he stepped into the ring against Ivan Robinson at the Atlantic
City Convention Center late Saturday night, nothing had changed
about his style.
</P>
<P>
   In what has now become a familiar scene, Gatti absorbed punches,
dished out punishment and looked on the verge of being knocked out,
only to rally at the end of each grueling round. But Robinson
mirrored the indefatigable Gatti, and in the end it was he who
benefited from the exchanges as he scored a 10-round split decision
in their lightweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a warrior,'' said Robinson (26-2). ``I don't take nothing
from any fighter. I was hurt, but I had to keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   One judge, Ed Leahy, scored the bout 96-93 for Gatti (29-3). But
Steven Weisfeld scored it 96-94 for Robinson and Melvina Latham
scored it 98-93 for Robinson. Both Weisfeld and Latham gave
Robinson rounds five through nine, while Leahy gave Gatti every
round from the third through the 10th except the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   According to Compubox statistics, Gatti threw 835 punches to
Robinson's 795, but Gatti landed only 274, or not quite a third;
Robinson landed 400, just over half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatti is like a stick of dynamite,'' Robinson said. ``You
light that fuse and you don't know when he's going off.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatti scored the only knockdown of the fight when he caught an
off-balance Robinson with a right to the side of the head in the
fourth round. After a particularly brutal sixth round, the two
fighters stood smiling at each other after the bell, seeming to
indicate that they were enjoying the mutual mauling.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti received a small cut underneath his left eye in the third
round, though it was not as severe as the cut he sustained over his
left eye in his fight against Angel Manfredy eight months ago.
Gatti did not attend the postfight news conference. Robinson's only
cut came after the fight, when one of his cornermen jabbed him in
the hand with scissors while removing tape.
</P>
<P>
   Going against conventional wisdom, Robinson took the fight right
to Gatti. Gatti also put tremendous pressure on Robinson, but
Robinson stood his ground. In the 10th round, Robinson took some
heavy shots and looked out on his feet, but he would not go down.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the fight, the promoter, Dino Duva of Main
Events, and Lou DiBella, senior vice president of programing for
HBO, were talking about a rematch. But it will be a while before
Gatti steps into the ring. A victory would have put him in line for
a shot at Cesar Bazan, the World Boxing Council lightweight
champion. That plan has been scuttled.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Robinson, who lost during the American trials
for the 1992 Olympic Games at Barcelona, has opened up a world of
possibilities. There was some talk of matching him with Manfredy,
who stopped Gatti on cuts in the eighth round of their January
fight. Robinson lost to Phillip Holiday in his only title shot in
1996 and wants another chance. He would like to fight Shane Mosley,
the reigning International Boxing Federation lightweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read something in the newspaper that said Shane is such a
powerhouse,'' Robinson said. ``Come on. Shane ain't that much
better than Gatti.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
