u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COLUMN-GREEN-NYT &LR;      08-23 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COLUMN-GREEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FILLING THE IDEA VACUUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 10:45 a.m. Sunday, Mark Green was back on the
steps of City Hall, this time releasing a report on the failures of
state nursing homes. The news conference over, Green, a Democratic
candidate for U.S. Senate, rested a sneaker against a railing and
took stock of his Sunday morning. ``Five cameras,'' he said,
gleaming, before bouncing into a car and heading for the first of
two streets fairs.
</P>
<P>
   And this was a light day.
</P>
<P>
   Green _ short on cash, little known outside New York City, and
widely viewed in political circles as the least likely of the three
Democrats to win the Sept. 15 primary _ is campaigning relentlessly
these days: offering up speeches, attacks and proposals, trying to
nudge his opponents into acknowledging his existence. This week,
Green, who can be glib, is running through his ``Twenty-one ideas
for the 21st Century'' (two down and 19 to go as of Sunday night).
</P>
<P>
   Whether all this exertion will turn Green from the New York City
public advocate into the Democratic challenger to Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato is debatable; there is reason to suspect that Green's
frantic schedule is equally intended to position him for the 2001
mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the case, it is becoming clear that Green _ more
than either rival, Geraldine Ferraro or Charles Schumer _ is the
Democrat who is largely defining the day-to-day course of this
closely watched New York primary.
</P>
<P>
   Green's call last week for a $100 billion Pentagon spending cut
made more of a splash than anything either of his two major rivals
have proposed. As late as Sunday afternoon, Ferraro's
communications director, Stephen Gaskill, was still responding to
it, warning that Green's proposal could endanger the nation's
security. On Friday, Green called for federal support of health
insurance premiums for people who are between jobs. Idea No. 3
comes Monday: health insurance for all the nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   It was Green's needling of Schumer at a candidates' debate that
provoked the exchange between the two men that won all the
headlines. And it was no surprise that after a contentious
television interview that was broadcast Sunday, Ferraro
sarcastically accused her interviewer, Marcia Kramer of WCBS-TV, of
doing the ``Green spin'' after Ms. Kramer pushed Ferraro about why
she had agreed to so few debates. Green has raised the same
question.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most people would agree that it is a good thing when
politicians use campaigns to talk about ideas. That said, Green is
doing this because he has to. As Green likes to say, he does not
have the money of Schumer, who is waging an expensive campaign of
television advertisements, or the celebrity and historic political
base of Ferraro. And if Green has proved himself expert at anything
in his career, it is getting his face on television.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that he is unlikely to win, Green can risk talking
about military cuts and increasing social spending. Those are the
kinds of ideas that can win Green attention and Democratic primary
voters _ but it is also the kind of talk that will gladden D'Amato,
a Republican who has made a habit of attacking his opponents as
liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro and Schumer are running very different _ as in less
adventurous _ campaigns. That is particularly true with Ferraro,
who has accepted the conventional political wisdom that she is the
front-runner, and not risked anything that might upset that. While
Green talks about defense spending, Ferraro shakes hands at subway
stations, not the kind of public appearances that allow for a
rigorous discussion of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has a more active public schedule, and has proposed a
series of ideas that have captured voters' attention, such as
making college tuition tax deductible and allowing teachers to pay
off student loans by working in public schools, while invoking his
legislative record as a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's ideas, if substantive, are not necessarily risky: On
Friday, for example, Schumer talked about high college tuition (he
is against it).
</P>
<P>
   Green's opponents are reacting to his sallies with a kind of
worried disdain. ``Mark Green has a mean streak, and he's trying to
do whatever he can to draw attention to his campaign _ which hasn't
caught on with the voters,'' said Gaskill of the Ferraro campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The point might be correct. But Green is also filling a vacuum.
He is, by his very action, demonstrating his opponents' inaction,
and to some extent, forcing them to talk about issues they might
prefer to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   And win or lose, that might end up being Green's real legacy to
this contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
