<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE WITNESS IN WOMAN'S DISAPPEARANCE QUESTIONED IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A monthlong search for a possible witness in the
disappearance of an Upper East Side millionaire ended early
Saturday when New York City detectives flew to a small Florida
farming town to question him, the police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The man who was questioned, Jose Antonio Alvarez, 24, had
traveled to New York from Florida in June with Sante and Kenneth
Kimes, a mother and son, who are the primary suspects in the
disappearance of Irene Silverman, an 82-year-old widow who vanished
on July 5 and is presumed dead. Alvarez was seen at Mrs.
Silverman's mansion in the days before her disappearance, but then
had disappeared himself.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he resurfaced in Belle Glade, Fla., where he was
living with his parents and working construction jobs. He was
apparently unaware that he was wanted for questioning in New York
and in Manalapan, Fla., where the authorities believe he may have
been with the Kimeses when they used bad checks to purchase an
$80,000 mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Angelo Tsaousis of the Belle Glade Police Department
said he waited with Alvarez while New York detectives flew to Palm
Beach and then drove to Belle Glade, where they arrived and began
questioning Alvarez just before 1 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tsaousis said he did not know what the detectives learned, but
said he believed that they had returned to New York, and Alvarez to
his home, later that morning. The New York City police would not
comment Sunday night on the results of their interview with
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by telephone on WNBC-TV on Saturday night, Alvarez
denied any involvement in Mrs. Silverman's disappearance. The
station quoted him as saying that the Kimeses had hired him as
their handyman at their rental house at the Palm Beach Polo Club,
and then took him along to New York.
</P>
<P>
   He left a week before Mrs. Silverman's disappearance, the
station said, because he found the Kimeses ``strange.'' Alvarez
could not be reached for comment Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses are being held in New York on charges of credit card
fraud and passing a bad check in Utah to buy a Lincoln Town Car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
