<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLOCAUST-SHIP-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD SHIP FINDS A NEW LIFE AS A SYMBOL OF REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLEN COVE, N.Y. _ Days away from being scuttled at sea, the
Regina Maris, a 90-year-old three-masted barkentine that smuggled
Jewish refugees out of Nazi Germany during World War II, has found
a new home here in Hempstead Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   As if emerging from Glen Cove's rich maritime past, the tall
wooden ship is scheduled to arrive here Tuesday morning when she
will be welcomed by Mayor Thomas Suozzi and other city officials,
who plan to make her a star attraction and a symbol of their $220
million waterfront revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   For the last eight years, the rakish prow and 108-foot-high
masts of the Regina Maris have dominated the waterfront of
Greenport, a village about 90 nautical miles east of Glen Cove at
the eastern end of Long Island, where a group of elderly seamen,
all members of Save the Regina Maris Ltd., have labored to keep the
ship afloat, despite her aging timbers and rigging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry to see her go, but we feel we can no longer afford
to keep her here,'' said David Kapell, the mayor of Greenport, who
estimated that it could take $1 million to $5 million to rebuild
the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Regina Maris has long been a part of our community,'' he
said, ``but we have had to come to grips with the fact that the
project to save and restore her was more than we could handle. We
wish Glen Cove well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 239-ton vessel, built in 1908 in Svendborg, Denmark, has had
a storied history, much of it passed down by word of mouth,
according to Merlon Wiggin, executive director of the East End
Seaport Museum and Marine Foundation and president of Save the
Regina Maris.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was a Baltic and North Atlantic trader in the early
days, he said, a transporter of Jewish refugees from European ports
during World War II, a refitted private yacht after the war and,
later, a research vessel that charted the migratory habits of the
humpback whale.
</P>
<P>
   The aging ship fell on hard times in 1988 in Boston Harbor, when
she sank after a bilge pump failed. She was refloated, only to be
scuttled in 1991 to protect her from Hurricane Bob. Later that
year, she was secured by Wiggin and his committee and towed to
Greenport. She was to have been scuttled for a second and final
time later this month when her maritime insurance ran out, but Glen
Cove came to her rescue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The committee will retain an interest in the vessel, but the
majority of a new board of directors will be appointed by Suozzi.
</P>
<P>
   Suozzi said that the Regina Maris, which is Latin for ``Queen of
the Sea,'' would be leaving Greenport late Sunday night and that
she would be towed at a speed of three knots by a tug from Barker
Marine Services of Port Washington, which has agreed to do it at
cost for $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 hours under tow, she is expected to arrive in Glen Cove
and be tied up at Steam Boat Landing, a recently opened waterfront
restaurant that is a part of the city's waterfront revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a plan beyond getting her here, but we're going
to do it anyway,'' Suozzi said. ``Everyone says we're crazy and
that the boat is a mess. But they said the same thing about our
waterfront when we started to clean it up, and so far, we've been
very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city had raised $20 million in federal and state
restoration funds for the waterfront project, and that an
additional $200 million had been pledged by private investors.
</P>
<P>
   He said Glen Cove planned to clean up polluted sites, improve
the waterfront's infrastructure, build new bulkheads and clear
roads into the area for access to a new hotel, shops and high-speed
ferry service to Manhattan and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had already raised more than $20,000 for the
ship's repairs from two donors, more than enough to pay the ship's
annual $5,000 insurance premium. Two business groups in Denmark
have also expressed an interest in helping to rebuild the vessel,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people said it couldn't be done, but we're doing it,''
Suozzi said. ``And we'll do the same with the Regina Maris.'' He
noted that Glen Cove was also home to the Nassau County Holocaust
Memorial and Education Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard they were going to scuttle the Regina Maris and
that she had this incredible history,'' he said, ``we had to save
her and make her feel at home here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
