<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-GORDON-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON GETS ON KEY LIST AFTER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn. )  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Jeff Gordon became the seventh driver to find
out just how hard it is to win five straight Winston Cup races,
finishing fifth on Saturday in his bid to make history in the
Goody's Headache Powder 500.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting his car and a cold, Gordon never led a lap at Bristol
Motor Speedway in his pursuit of a fifth straight victory, which
would have set a modern record.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon joined some exclusive company _ Mark Martin, Bill
Elliott, Harry Gant, Dale Earnhardt, Darrell Waltrip, Cale
Yarborough _ as drivers to get stuck on four straight victories.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the defending Winston Cup champion, also lost valuable
points to the race winner, Martin, in the points standing. Gordon
now leads Martin by just 67 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got fifth,'' said an exasperated Gordon after the race.
``Does that count for anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon added: ``This is one of the toughest places to get
around. I was just trying to make 500 laps. This is a demanding
place, and it takes a lot of a driver, especially when the car is
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Saturday night's race, Gordon had won four times on
the half-mile oval at Bristol, including a race here earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
   All of his victories, however, have come in the daytime race. He
still has never won here under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 10 years since both the day and night races at
Bristol were won by the same driver in the same season. (Dale
Earnhardt swept both races in 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent early in Saturday's race that Gordon's car was
not good enough to win a fifth straight time.
</P>
<P>
   By lap 30 of 500, Gordon had moved up to fifth, but as his car's
handling problems worsened, he began to fall back in position.
</P>
<P>
   By lap 200, however, Gordon began taking back some of those
spots he lost, moving up to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just off a little bit here at nighttime,'' said Gordon,
who failed to lead a lap for the first time in 14 straight races.
``We've got to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon began his streak of four consecutive victories last month
at Pocono. He won again less than a week later at Indianapolis,
where he took home a $1.6 million purse, the largest in U.S.
motorsports history. Gordon went on to victories at Watkins Glen,
N.Y., and at Michigan two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really didn't matter to me,'' Gordon said of the record.
``I would have liked to win. But to come in the top five, that's
all I could ask for. We did exactly what we needed to do as far as
the championship.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gordon cited his starting positions the previous four races as a
major factor in his success.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he started seventh, the worst spot since the streak
began. During the streak, Gordon had started on the pole once, the
outside of the front row once, from the third position twice.
</P>
<P>
   Severe handling problems on Saturday did not allow him to drive
his way to the front of the field.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointed looks on the faces in Gordon's pit after the
race were a stark contrast to the celebration in front of the pit
stall of Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after losing his father, stepmother and stepsister in
a private plane crash, Martin choked back the tears as he took a
fifth checkered flag this season, pulling closer to Gordon in the
championship points standing.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton finished second and the pole-sitter Rusty Wallace
was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This helps me because I was so devastated,'' said Martin, who
led twice for 190 laps, running up front for the last 181. ``Now
it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 24 races at Bristol, Martin, driver of the No. 6 Valvoline
Ford, has scored 17 top-0 finishes, including nine straight.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night marked Martin's 18th top-10 finish this season,
which is more than any other driver. He has finished in the top 10
in each of the last 13 races, which includes 11 top-five finishes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIT STOPS:
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield, who finished eighth on Saturday, has gone from
36 points ahead in the championship points standing to a 518-point
deficit since his first career victory at Pocono in June.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, when the NASCAR Winston Cup visits New Hampshire for
the second time this season, Saturday night's runner-up, Jeff
Burton, will be looking to win his third in four races there. He
won both the 1997 and 1998 Jiffy Lube 300 at Loudon.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, who finished sixth on Saturday after leading
midway through the race, has just one victory in his last 81
starts. It came this season at the Daytona 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
