<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTIST-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ARRESTED FOR SELLING ART WITHOUT CITY PERMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than two weeks after a judge ruled that the city
cannot prevent vendors from peddling art without a permit, Parks
Department enforcement officers on Sunday arrested a 47-year-old
Tarrytown man for selling paintings without a city permit in front
of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Similar charges against three artists arrested in the spring
were dismissed earlier this month by Judge Lucy Billings of State
Criminal Court. In her ruling, the judge said art should be
regarded as a form of free speech and accorded the same
constitutional protection as spoken and written matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, officers arrested Patrick Christiano for
selling paintings and poetry without a permit, said Edward Skyler,
a Parks Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Another artist, Sue Walters Balmuth, said Christiano was one of
the three artists whose cases were dismissed by Judge Billings.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's incident began when Christiano was issued a summons for
violating the city's permit policy. He returned a half-hour later,
began selling again, was issued another summons, and refused to
leave. He was charged with failing to comply with Parks Department
orders, Skyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing Judge Billings' ruling, Skyler argued Sunday that the
judge had no authority over the agency's ability to enforce its
regulations. He repeatedly cited the orders of a federal court
judge in Manhattan who ruled earlier this year that the city had
not violated the First Amendment by limiting the number of artists
who could sell their works in parks or on adjacent sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Under a policy that went into effect in March, the city issues
permits to artists who sell their works in these areas; 24 are
issued every month for the two wide sections of sidewalk on Fifth
Avenue in front of the Metropolitan, for a $25 fee.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations sparked raucous protests in front of the museum
in the spring, with artists displaying banners lampooning Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani as Hitler. Weekend after weekend, Parks
enforcement officers arrested the protesters, seized their artwork
and issued fines as high as $1,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
