<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APOLLO-THEATER-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLLO THEATER WORKERS SAY THEY WILL JOIN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying they have endured poor working conditions for
years, stagehands at the financially troubled Apollo Theater
announced Sunday that they were joining a union in hopes of getting
health benefits, retirement funds and higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing effort comes as the state attorney general's
office is investigating the financial relationship between the
private foundation that runs the theater and a broadcasting company
that tapes television shows there. Members of the stage crew said
Sunday that their complaints were a completely separate issue. But
they chose to organize while the theater was under investigation in
hopes of drawing more attention to their cause, said Joseph Gray, a
senior stagehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that because of the investigation, our plight would
be in the spotlight a little more,'' said Gray, who said he has
worked at the Apollo for 10 years without health benefits or a
pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   The stagehands went even further in their publicity strategy,
hiring a press agent to reach out to a reporter, designating three
senior stagehands to give interviews and asking the reporter to
delay contacting the theater management until Sunday night, when
they finally informed the management of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said all 34 members of the theater's stage crew signed up
last week for membership in Local No. 1 of the International
Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees, which represents 2,150
stagehands in New York City. James Claffey Jr., the theater
business manager of Local No. 1, said as many as 300 union members
would wave signs and distribute informational fliers Monday in
front of the historic theater, on 125th Street in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Blake, the executive director of the Apollo Theater
Foundation, said Sunday that she could not comment because she had
not yet heard the details of the organizing effort. Christopher
McKenna, a spokesman for Attorney General Dennis Vacco, also
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit foundation runs the Apollo Theater for the state,
which owns it. But the theater has fallen into disrepair in recent
years, and state officials announced in May that they would
withhold $750,000 in loans and grants from the foundation until
questions about its finances had been answered.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, state officials are questioning whether the
foundation's board allowed a company, Inner City Broadcasting, to
significantly underpay the foundation for use of the Apollo and its
name in taping a popular television show there. The company
retained the theater under a five-year licensing agreement.
U.S.Rep. Charles Rangel, the chairman of the foundation's board, is
close friends with Percy Sutton, the owner of Inner City
Broadcasting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the licensing agreement, Inner City was supposed to pay
the foundation $2,000 per taping or 25 percent of the show's
profits, whichever was greater. But state officials say the
foundation's executives told its board early this year that Sutton
owed at least $3 million under the agreement, which expired at the
end of last year. When the board pressed for payment, it received
only $200,000, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Rangel both say the foundation received all that it
had been owed. But James Claffey Jr., theater business manager of
Local No. 1, who is leading the organizing effort, said the charges
of financial mismanagement made the union especially eager to help
organize the Apollo stagehands. He said the Apollo stagehands made
between $15 and $20 an hour, while unionized stagehands in New York
made between $25 and $38. The Apollo stagehands _ who are in charge
of lighting, sound and set production _ work at the theater part
time, because the theater usually puts on only one or two shows a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo stagehands said they were also seeking better working
conditions and scheduled lunch hours. They will be sworn in as
members of Local No. 1 next month, Claffey said. If the Apollo
management does not agree to negotiate a contract, the union will
file a petition with the National Labor Relations Board, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Dessisso, an Apollo stagehand, said he liked working at
the theater but was not making enough to support his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going after them with any vengeful reasons,'' he
said. ``This is just business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
