<HEADER>
A8286 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHEME-2Takes-1stlede     08-23 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHEME-2Takes-1stlede-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD TRUMP ADMIRER GUILTY OF DEFRAUDING HUNDREDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Claiming Donald Trump and Mother Teresa as
references, it's no wonder Stephen Murphy had such an easy time
ripping people off.
</P>
<P>
   After federal investigators discovered that the self-proclaimed
homeless-man-turned-millionaire sold interest in buildings and
mini-malls he never purchased, Murphy pleaded guilty to six felony
charges last month and will be sentenced by a judge in November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of mostly elderly investors are marveling at
how easy it was for the social chameleon to take their money.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Oaks, Calif., resident Rudy Kretschec, a 66-year-old
retiree, gave more than $15,000 to Murphy in 1992, hoping to make
money to pass on to his five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't get the feeling it was flim-flam. He was so good at
what he did, believe me, you would invest,'' Kretschec said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   He said Murphy found out about his Korean War experience and
used a ``veterans have to stick together'' approach to lure
investment funds. In Murphy's books, advertisements and television
appearances in the early 1990s, the 49-year-old said he was a
Vietnam veteran who used to live out of his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the American success story,'' Kretschec said.
</P>
<P>
   Kretschec was by no means alone, and Murphy is by no means the
last of the flim-flammers, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment fraud is the wave of the future,'' said FBI Special
Agent Dan Bolick, who specializes in fraud investigation in the Los
Angeles area. ``All of these other (scams) are getting smaller and
the one category that is getting bigger is investment fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy couldn't be reached, but his public defender, Ellen
Barry, pointed out that Murphy had plenty of legitimate business,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually was selling real estate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy owned American Capital Investments Inc., a company
supposedly set up for buying, operating and selling real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Christopher Painter said Murphy's first
program, Plaza Del Sol, solicited investments for a shopping center
that was never bought _ a fact that was concealed from investors.
He ended up raising more than $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of Murphy's beach-side Marina Del Rey office were
filled with kudos and accolades, including a picture of Mother
Teresa. Investors said Murphy pointed out a framed letter,
supposedly from Mother Teresa, when making his sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   His book, ``Formerly One Up on Trump,'' includes a complimentary
letter purportedly signed by The Donald himself.
</P>
<P>
   After telling investors that he had resold property at a large
profit, he urged them to ``roll over'' their funds to other
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including Kretschec, were given monthly interest payments.
But prosecutors claim those payments came from other investors'
funds, not from ACI properties.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission finally caught up to
Murphy in the summer of 1993, and got a court order to freeze his
assets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney's Office spokesman Thom Mrozek called Murphy a con
man who will pay for his schemes with a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an environment with an overheated stock market, these
so-called securities gurus pose a particularly dangerous threat. As
we saw during the S&AMP;L crisis of the 1980s, con men have been
particularly effective in separating investors from their money,''
Mrozek said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Murphy pleaded guilty to five counts of mail fraud and
one count of making false statements to a financial institution,
Painter said. Murphy faces 55 years in prison, although the U.S.
Attorney's Office will recommend five years through a plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   (2nd TAKE TO FOLLOW)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
